[White "Introduction"]
[Black "Introduction"]
[Result "*"]

{ Welcome to the Colle-Zukertort!   This club player favourite remains a killer weapon in 2022 and continues to notch up the points at club and tournament level. It's no surprise when we consider that White's set-up is both easy to play and offers decent attacking chances. As you'll see in our introductory section, both your authors, Richard Palliser and Simon Williams, have made good use of the opening over the years and here offer both a full repertoire for White after 1. d4 d5, as well as lines they themselves very much believe in. There is the odd forcing sequence, but in short White's ideas are easy to grasp and, yes, the odd very modern twist is thrown in to bamboozle even an experienced 1. d4 d5 defender along the way. }
1. d4
{ This classic opening move should need no introduction. White seizes central space. We'll now see what happens when, as so often occurs in practice, Black copies for the first few moves. }
1... d5 2. Nf3
{ With this move, White prepares to enter the Colle setup, and remains flexible with the c-pawn, contrary to the Queen's Gambit. The extra control over e5 rules out lines such as the Albin Countergambit. }
2... Nf6 3. e3
{ The characteristic Colle advance and one patented by Edgard Colle @@StartBracket@@1897-1932@@EndBracket@@, six-time Belgian Champion and a world-class player before he died tragically young due to a gastric ulcer. While White does block in the dark-squared bishop, there's another diagonal than c1-h6 we want to deploy that key piece to, and in the meantime, White prepares to deploy the light-squared bishop to a fine spot on d3. }
3... e6 4. Bd3
{ The natural square to develop the bishop, which will very often prove White's most effective attacker. }
4... c5 5. b3 { Preparing the fianchetto of the dark-squared Colle bishop. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Killer Colle Strategies"]
[Black "The Key e5 Outpost "]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r1bq1rk1/p2nbppp/1p2pn2/2pp4/3P4/1P1BPN2/PBPN1PPP/R2Q1RK1 w - - 0 9"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ Here we see a typical Colle-Zukertort situation. White has completed development, bar deploying the major pieces, while Black is still to complete his own queenside fianchetto. As such, it's time to strike and head forwards. }
9. Ne5
{ The thematic advance. White clears the way for the f-pawn to advance, if needed, and the f3-square is also cleared, be it for the queen, d2-knight or, after f2-f4, the rook on f1. }
9... Bb7
{ 9...Nxe5?!  10.dxe5  This misguided exchange worries some players new to the Colle-Zukertort, but White should rarely fear the exchange of knights on e5.   Note here how Black cannot leap into e4 without losing a pawn and how powerful the bishop on d3 is beginning to look.  10...Nd7  11.c4!?  There's absolutely nothing wrong with 11. f4  as we'll see in ourfirst theory section, and 11. Qh5!? is also quite tempting and decent, but here this is a well-timed advance, one which secures White an early clear advantage. There are three short but important lines here:   A.  11...Bb7  12.cxd5  exd5  13.f4  Talk about a powerful pawn roller. While Black is quite passive and devoid of play, White's set-up bristles with energy and potential. Next up may well be Qh5 to force a weakness, after which Rf3-h3 or Rf3-g3 could follow and, yes, the fianchettoed bishop may also join the attack after an e5-e6 breakthrough. In short, this would be a dream scenario for White.   B.  11...dxc4  12.Nxc4  The best way to recapture as the knight is quick to eye up a certain hole in the black position: d6.  12...Bb7  13.Qg4  Once again, we see a dream opening scenario for White. The simple plan is Rad1 followed by Nd6, after which the knight will either dominate Black or the bishop on b2 become a monster in the event of a ...Bxd6; exd6 exchange.   C.  11...d4!?  This rather desperate-looking advance is the best try that the engines can come up with. Leading in development, White should not panic and should just find the best way to exploit his lead in development and the target on d4.  12.exd4  cxd4  13.Bxd4!  Yes, the pawn can simply be snaffled as both forward discoveries caused by the knight on d7 can be met by Be4.  13...Nxe5?!  14.Be4  Black can't save his knight and rook, and so must give up the exchange for clearly nowhere near enough compensation. For example:  14...Qxd4  15.Bxa8  Rd8  16.Nf3  Qf4  17.Qe2  The bishop on a8 is quite safe, meaning White is just the exchange up and with the rooks coming quickly to the d-file. }
10. Qf3
{ There's unsurprisingly nothing too much wrong with  10.f4  @@StartBracket@@10. Qe2 is our main recommendation. Here as we'll see later on@@EndBracket@@ but Richard has always liked the option of taking control of the e4-square where possible, thereby denying Black any liberating ...Ne4 manoeuvre. We should also note that the queen, as well as a rook, might be quite happy to sidle over to h3. }
10... a6
{ A slightly slow move, if a typical one in such positions where Black often finds it hard to find a plan. At least ...a6 prepares a possible ...b5 and also prevents any potentially awkward Bb5 pins in the event of ...Re8. }
11. Qh3
{ Richard preferred  11.Rad1  calmly building up, in Palliser-M.Houska, British League @@StartBracket@@4NCL@@EndBracket@@ 2001, but should have continued to deploy the queen. Can you spot White's threat? }
11... Ne4
{ Black's best defence, closing down the b1-h7 diagonal and not falling for the trap.   A.  11...b5??  12.Nxd7  This reveals White's big idea. Clearly Black can't recapture with the knight due to mate and taking back with the queen also has a rather obvious downside:  12...Qxd7  13.dxc5!  White threatens to remove the key defender on f6 and is also ready to secure the extra pawn with b3-b4.  13...Ne4!?  14.f3  Ng5  15.Qg3  Clearly Black remains under pressure on the kingside, with h2-h4 but one threat, and White will at least manage to secure the rather handy extra pawn with b3-b4. Talk about an ideal outcome from the opening!   B.  11...cxd4?!  12.Nxd7!  White can simply recapture on d4, but this exchange is even stronger. Keep an eye on White's bishops and queen!  12...Qxd7  13.Bxd4  The key follow-up. Once again White threatens a game-ending capture on f6 and is also ready to both take control of e5 and expand with f2-f4 followed by Rf3-g3.  13...h6  14.f4!  Continuing the plan and rightly refusing to be deterred by material gains, leaving White clearly better.   14.Bxb6  Bb4  15.Nf3  Bc3!  isn't so clear.  Now Rf3-g3 will increase the pressure and, due to the hook on h6, White might even consider g2-g4-g5. }
12. Rad1
{ Bringing a further piece into play  12.f3  Ng5  13.Qg3  f6!  isn't as effective. White now threatens to win material down the d-file with exchanges on d7, c5 and e4. }
12... Nxe5 13. dxe5
{ The position is already uncomfortable for Black. Not only is there serious pressure down the d-file, but White is now threatening to ask some major problems on the kingside with f2-f3 Ng5 @@StartBracket@@to keep h7 protected@@EndBracket@@; Qg3. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Killer Colle Strategies"]
[Black "The Killer Kingside Attack "]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r4rk1/pp1b1ppp/2n1pn2/3pN3/3P4/qPPB4/P2N1PPP/R2Q1RK1 w - - 0 13"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ Here we see a typical scenario. Black has exchanged on d4, which increases White's control of e5  (a rook or queen can support the knight there from behind on the e-file)  , but has managed to exchange off the potentially venomous Zukertort bishop on b2. Given time, he will try to gang up on the pawn on c3, which is doing a fine job holding the b4 and d4 points, but while that is happening, White can very much build up his attack. }
13. f4
{ Now ...Nxe5; fxe5 is only going to give White a dream attack and in any case, Rf3-h3 is coming. }
13... Rac8 14. Rf3
{ Consistent and now we might note that even if Black did manage to get ...Rxc3 in, that capture might run into a discovered check on h7. }
14... g6
{ A.  14...Qb2??  15.Ndc4!  A neat trap and the reason the black queen cannot stray too far forwards. Black is losing the queen and a pawn for just two minor pieces.   B.  14...Rc7!?  15.Rh3  Consistent and now we should see what might happen if Black refuses to make a potentially weakening advance on the kingside:  15...Rfc8  16.Nxd7  Rxd7  17.Bxh7+!  Ouch. White has just netted a clear pawn and broken through to the black king:  17...Nxh7?  18.Qh5  Kf8  19.Qxh7  Black's position is already in tatters with the g-pawn set to fall. }
15. Qe1
{ A third strong move in a row from White who simply wants to attack with Qh4 and Rh3. }
15... Kg7 16. Rh3
{ 16. g4!? was also promising, but after Black's last move, it's wise to keep the queen on  e1  for now and not to fall for  16.Qh4?  Qb2  when Black would this time win material. }
16... Be8
{ 16...Nxe5  17.fxe5  Ng8  18.Nf1!?  Like in the main line, here we see Black hunkering down for a long defence, but his vulnerable kingside means that White is still clearly for choice. White would like to go Ng3 followed by crashing through with Nh5+! and is also quite happy to offer a pawn to retain control of the position:  18...Qb2  19.Rc1!  Qxa2  20.Ne3  Now we get to appreciate a second strong point behind regrouping the knight via f1. White simply intends to crash through on the dark squares with Ng4 and Nf6, and is just doing pretty well:  20...Qxb3?   20...f5!?  21.exf6+  Nxf6  22.Qh4  This is still a very dangerous attack for White, with h7 the main target and everything secure enough at the back:  22...Qd2?  23.Qh6+  Kg8  24.Rd1!  Qb2  25.Bxg6!  And the black king is a goner.  21.Ng4  Bb5  22.Nf6!  Threatening mate.  22...Nxf6  23.exf6+  Kxf6  24.Qh4+  Black's king can now run, but it can't really hide:  24...g5  25.Qh6+  Ke7  26.Qxg5+  Kd7  27.Rb1!  White is winning material and the game. }
17. Ndf3
{ Bringing another piece closer to the black king while moving the knight away from any potential ...Qb2 issue. }
17... Rh8 18. Qd2
{ 18.g4!  While ruling out ...Qb2 for good cannot be bad.   And with  18.Qh4  h5!  fighting on for Black, White should have got his advance underway straight away by throwing the g-pawn forwards. As well as the option of breaking through with f4-f5 and/or g4-g5, there is also now a threat of Nxc6 followed by Qe5, pinning the knight on f6.  18...a6?  19.Nxc6  Rxc6  20.Qe5  Qd6  21.g5  Qxe5  22.Nxe5  Black can now move the attacked knight, but only at the cost of the exchange. }
18... Ne7
{ Too slow and  18...h5  or even  18...h6!?  would have been a much better defensive try. }
19. g4
{ Keeping the black knight out of f5 as White enjoys a turbocharged attack. The simple and rather strong threat is f4-f5 followed by Qh6+. Having been treated to such a Colle-Zukertort master class, we might as well see how Hoi-Danielsen, Danish Championship, Ringsted 1995, concluded: }
19... Qa5 20. Rc1
{ 20.f5!  This brutal breakthrough would have been even stronger than sensibly maintaining control:  20...Qxc3  21.Qh6+  Kg8  22.Rf1!  The final piece joins in the attack and Black surely isn't going to survive, with one simply and deadly plan that of Kh1 @@StartBracket@@so that ...Qxd4 isn't check@@EndBracket@@ followed by Ng5 and a massacre down the f-file. }
20... Bb5
{ 20...h6!  21.f5!  This is still a pretty dangerous attack, but better that than the game for Black. }
21. Bb1
{ Continuing to maintain full control ahead of striking on the other flank. }
21... h5
{ Desperation with f4-f5 imminent and with Black completing lacking any counterplay due to White's fine prophylactic play on the queenside. }
22. Ng5
{ Never forget to identify not just what your opponent's move threatens and/or prepares, but also if there are any downsides to it! Here Danish GM Hoi, a long-time leading Colle exponent, spots that Black's last move rather weakened g5. As such, White can hop forwards, ignoring the attack on g4 to target f7. }
22... Rcf8
{ 22...hxg4  23.Rxh8  Rxh8  24.Nexf7  This is also extremely bad news for Black. White's knight on f7 may cause further chaos from e5, d6 or even d8, and sooner or later, e6 or g6 is surely going to fall. }
23. f5
{ Boom! Black might have two knights and two rooks around his king, but there just isn't a defence. }
23... Qa6
{ 23...hxg4  24.Rxh8  Rxh8  25.fxe6  This is just a game-ender as White is about to break through to the king:  25...fxe6?  26.Nxe6+  Kg8  27.Qg5  The only surprise here is that it's only mate in 8!   23...exf5  24.gxf5  White now threatens to capture on g6 then invade on e6.  24...Nxf5!?  25.Bxf5  gxf5?  26.Ne6+!  The arrival of the white queen spells the end and Black doesn't even have a tricky defence:  26...Kh7!?  27.Qg5!  Rfg8  28.Nf8+!  Rxf8  29.Qxf5+  There's surely no surprise that it's now mate in five. }
24. Re1
{ Simple chess, threatening to exchange on e6 then crash through with a sacrifice on g6. }
24... exf5
{ 24...hxg4  25.Rxh8  Rxh8  26.fxg6  fxg6  27.Nxg6!  This would have been a stylish finish, decisively ripping open lines:  27...Nxg6  28.Nxe6+  Kf7?  29.Bxg6+  Kxg6  30.Qg5+  Once again, it's soon going to be mate. }
25. gxf5 Qd6
{ 25...Ne4!?  26.Nxe4  Calmly countering Black's last-ditch try.  26...dxe4  27.c4  Be8  28.Bxe4  White has netted a pawn, gaining a dangerous central pawn-roller in the process and all the while as the black defences remain extremely shaky on g6 and f7. }
26. Ree3
{ Hardly terrible, but White might have spotted that he already had a rather strong threat.   26.fxg6!  fxg6  27.Nxg6!  Nxg6  28.Ne6+  Once again, we find Black in a position where resigns is the recommended move, since he must either ditch his queen or see, after Bxg6, the white queen decisively invade via g5. }
26... Nfg8
{ 26...gxf5!?  27.c4!  While the overwhelming focus may be on the kingside, White is still happy to make major gains elsewhere.  27...dxc4  28.bxc4  Be8  29.c5!  Forcing the black queen to a worse square, especially if it wants to continue protecting the knight on e7, thereby allowing ...Ng4 to be an option.  29...Qd8  30.Rhg3  Ng4  31.Ref3  With the knight on e7 defended, clearly Nxg4 and Rxe7 wasn't on, but White doesn't need to win material right away. He now threatens both Bxf5 and h2-h3, and there isn't even anything resembling a satisfactory defence for Black. }
27. fxg6 Qf6
{ This was a strange point to resign in Hoi-Danielsen, but White would surely have spotted the threat of mate and won with 28. Ref3. In any case there was no longer a defence:   A.  27...Nxg6?  28.Nxg6  fxg6  29.Ne6+  The horrendously exposed black king clearly isn't going to survive, since moving to h7 walks into White taking h5 with check.   B.  27...fxg6!?  28.c4!  dxc4  29.bxc4  Be8  30.d5!  Black has avoided being poleaxed on g6, but has lost the key battle for e6, meaning Ne6+ and/or Qd4 is clearly going to clean him up. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Killer Colle Strategies"]
[Black "Exchanging on c5 "]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r2qkb1r/3b1ppp/p1n1pn2/1ppp4/3P4/1P1BPN2/PBPN1PPP/R2Q1RK1 w kq - 0 9"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ Here we see a slightly unusual approach from Black, if one which is by no means unknown at club level, an early queenside expansion. Clearly Black wants to push White back with ...c4, so White should react on the queenside. }
9. dxc5
{ Opening up the bishop on b2, while being aware that White has two central pawns breaks: c2-c4 and e3-e4. }
9... Bxc5 10. e4
{ 10.c4  This also looks like a decent try, preparing to exchange on d5:  10...bxc4  11.bxc4  Nb4!?  12.Be2  White has a pleasant edge, since the knight on b4 can easily be kicked backwards, after which White's bishops will rake the black kingside from b2 and d3. First, though, White may consider leaping forwards with Ne5 and would also be delighted to activate his other knight with ...dxc4; Nxc4. }
10... d4
{ A.  10...dxe4?  11.Nxe4  The position has opened up before Black is ready, thereby landing him in early trouble:  11...Nxe4   11...Be7  12.Qe2  And again Black is under heavy pressure, with Rfd1 and the undermining a2-a4 high on the agenda.  12.Bxe4  O-O  13.Ne5  Black is losing the exchange.   B.  10...O-O !  11.e5  Ng4  12.Qe2  White's extra space and ability to drive the black knight back to h6 gives him an edge, but no more than that. If allowed, he should look to expand with a2-a3, b3-b4 and Nb3, taking full control of d4 while preserving the light-squared bishop. }
11. e5 Nd5
{ 11...Ng4  12.Ne4  Be7  13.Nd6+!  This reminds us to never forget about the potential power of the fianchettoed bishop.  13...Bxd6  14.exd6  e5  15.h3  Nh6  16.Re1  Black's centre is collapsing and the unopposed dark-squared bishop is about to become a pretty powerful piece indeed. }
12. Ne4 Qb6
{ Now in Palliser-Price, Yeovil Open 2002, Richard took control of b4 with  13.a3!?  but removing the bishop-pair would have been even stronger: }
13. Nxc5 Qxc5 14. Re1
{ White is clearly somewhat for choice. We might expand with Ng5, striking against h7 and both members of Black's royal family, since Ne4 is also an issue. White also has ideas of simply Qd2 and ganging up on d4, while if Black ever castles kingside, he may well walk into a Nxd4 trick. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Killer Colle Strategies"]
[Black "The Trap "]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r2q1rk1/pb1n1ppp/1p1bpn2/2ppN3/3P1P2/1P1BP3/PBPN2PP/R2Q1RK1 b - - 0 10"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ Take a good look at this position! Clearly Black would like to connect the rooks, so is there anything more natural than moving the queen to c7? }
10... Qc7 11. Nxd7
{ The refutation. We've found well over 60 OTB examples of 10...Qc7, including some from players strong enough and experienced enough they should have known better. There are countless more examples on Lichess and surely from chess clubs around the world. As 10...Qc7 hasn't always gone unpunished, please remember that this is a position where White can make very good use of both the strong knight on e5 and bishop-liberating exchange on c5! }
11... Qxd7
{ 11...Nxd7!?  12.dxc5!  This is also pretty strong. Indeed, the engines now think that Black must simply ditch a pawn and retreat the bishop to e7. Let's see why:  12...Nxc5?   12...Bxc5?  13.Bxh7+!  13...Kxh7  14.Qh5+  Kg8  15.Bxg7!  A classic double bishop sacrifice. White simply wants to give mate on either h8 or via Qg5+ and Rf3-h3. There's simply no good defence:  15...Bxe3+  16.Kh1  f6  17.Bh6!  Much stronger than the  @@StartFEN@@r4rk1/pbqn2B1/1p2pp2/3p3Q/5P2/1P2b3/P1PN2PP/R4R1K w - - 0 17@@EndFEN@@  17.Rf3?  Bxf4!  of Nodirjanova-Beddar, Dresden Women's Olympiad 2008. White simply wants to get the queen in:  17...Ne5  18.Bxf8  Bxd2  19.Ba3!?  White is winning as retreating the knight from e5 would walk into a decisive rook lift.  13.Bxh7+!  13...Kxh7  14.Qh5+  Kg8  15.Bf6!!  A gorgeous and quite deadly move.   15.Bxg7?  would fail to  15...f5!  16.Rf3  Qxg7  17.Rg3  Rf7  .  15...gxf6  16.Qg4+  Kh7  17.Rf3  Mate follows. }
12. dxc5
{ Opening up the bishop on b2 and so preparing to obliterate the black kingside. }
12... Bxc5
{ 12...Be7!  13.cxb6  axb6  14.Qe2  White is a healthy pawn up and might usefully expand with a2-a4, e3-e4 or Nf3-e5, but better this than recapturing for Black. }
13. Bxf6
{ The e3-pawn is small fry when going right for the throat is the plan. } 13...
Bxe3+
{ 13...gxf6  14.Bxh7+!  Kxh7  15.Qh5+  A familiar motif. Black is going to be cleaned up on the open g- and h-files:  15...Kg7  16.Qg4+  Kh7  17.Rf3  It's mate in two. }
14. Kh1 gxf6 15. Bxh7+
{ Our favourite and quite decisive sacrifice, as in, amongst others, Cornhill-Barber, York @@StartBracket@@rapid@@EndBracket@@ 2012, and Malezkey-Kazantsev, Barnaul 2014. }
15... Kxh7
{ 15...Kh8  16.Qh5  This is also a game-ender with Qh6 and/or Rf3 up next. }
16. Qh5+ Kg7 17. Qg4+ { A key check, preventing the black king from fleeing. }
17... Kh7 18. Rf3
{ It's now mate in four, since White can even ignore any desperado black bishops. }
18... Bxf4 19. Rh3+ Bh6 20. Qh5 { The black king is going to be mated on g8. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Killer Colle Strategies"]
[Black "The Timely c2-c4 Break "]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r2qk2r/pbpnbppp/1p2p3/3p4/3Pn3/1P1BPN2/PBPN1PPP/R2Q1RK1 w kq - 0 9"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ Here we see Black holding back on the ...c5 break, which is slightly unusual, but by no means bad. At such times, White should give serious thought to expanding himself with c2-c4, especially when that helps to undermine a knight on e4. }
9. c4
{ Useful expansion, especially as clearly Black can't consider taking on c4 here  9...dxc4??  10.Bxe4   9.Ne5  This would, of course, be our normal leap, but here dxe5 won't come with tempo and Black is well set up to exchange:  9...Nxe5!  10.dxe5  O-O  Black is extremely solid here and we'd really prefer to try and avoid such scenarios. }
9... O-O 10. Qc2
{ Increasing the pressure against e4, while also setting up potential pressure against c7 and h7. }
10... Nxd2
{ A.  10...f5  11.cxd5  exd5  12.Ne5!  This now works better as any exchange on e5 would leave White with a passed pawn and he can always drive away the Stonewall-style knight on e4 with f2-f3.   B.  10...Ndf6!?  11.Rac1  11...Rc8  12.Rfd1  This is clearly very solid for Black, but we'd still slightly prefer to take White, who has deployed both rooks and can still consider Ne5 ideas. Note too that it's probably best to exchange if Black now breaks:  12...c5  13.dxc5!  Now Black must be slightly careful due to the white rook vis-à-vis the queen on d8, and use the knight on e4.  13...Nxc5  14.Be2  White's forces are slightly the more harmonious. He might improve his diagonal control with Bd4 and Qb2 or even, in the event of ...Ncd7, Qb1 and Bd3. Meanwhile Black must be slightly careful still with his queen:  14...Qc7?!  15.cxd5  Nxd5  16.b4!  Suddenly Black is in trouble with Qa4 on if his attacked knight retreats and even the best defence leaves him struggling:  16...Ba6!   16...Nxb4?  17.Qc3  17.Nc4  Nd7  18.Qa4  Exchanging on c4 would now lose all the light squares and be a big concession, but  18...Qb7?  fails to  19.Nd6!  .  And even the computer's tricky top line leaves White clearly for choice:   18...Bxb4!?  19.Qxa6!  Nc5  20.Nxb6!  Saving the queen and continuing to force matters:  20...Nxa6  21.Rxc7  21...Naxc7  22.Nxc8  Rxc8  23.Rc1  The pin and bishop-pair leave White with good chances to grind out a win in the endgame. }
11. Nxd2
{ Continuing to eye h7.   11.Bxh7+?  Kh8  12.Nxd2  g6!  This is the problem:  13.Bxg6  fxg6  14.Qxg6  Rf6  15.Qh5+  Kg7  White may have three pawns for the piece, but Black is doing very well with only the white king set to feel the heat. }
11... f5
{ A.  11...g6  12.Rad1  White centralises ahead of further central expansion.  12...Rc8  13.e4  c6?!   13...c5  14.exd5  exd5  15.dxc5  Nxc5  16.Be2!  White preserves his light-squared bishop, which heads round to f3 and also has a small edge in part due to the vis-à-vis on the d-file and the weakness of the long, dark-square diagonal.  14.Rfe1  Qc7  15.Nf3  This left White well centralised, as well as Black cramped and facing a strong attack in Brkljaca-Abramovic Belgrade 2007, where h2-h4-h5 was one idea and Qd2-h6 another.   B.  11...Nf6!?  12.c5!?  Black has avoided weakening his kingside, but at the cost of being slightly cramped. White will now look to expand with b3-b4 and Nf3-e5 and must have a small edge. }
12. cxd5
{ The problem is that  12...exd5  would now drop f5 and we've both seen similar exchanges on d5 underestimated when ...f5 is played many times at club level. }
12... Bxd5
{ This was G.Nagy-Tisaj, Internet @@StartBracket@@blitz@@EndBracket@@ 2020, where White should have expanded while going after the black king: }
13. e4 fxe4 14. Nxe4
{ White might have an IQP, but he is somewhat better with Nc3 the immediate threat and Rae1 also set to increase the pressure on Black's fragile structure. }
