[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Killer Colle Strategies"]
[Black "Zukertort, J. vs. Blackburne, J.  London Masters, 1883"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 e6 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. e3 d5 4. Bd3
{ The natural square to develop the bishop, which will very often prove White's most effective attacker. }
4... Be7 5. O-O
{ Delaying b2-b3 by a move is perfectly reasonable when Black isn't threatening ...c4 to push the bishop back from d3. }
5... O-O 6. b3 c5 7. Bb2 Nc6 8. Nbd2
{ Model play thus far from Zukertort in his own opening! } 8... cxd4 9. exd4 b6
{ 9...Nb4  10.Be2  A calm retreat and reason why White need not fear ...Nb4 here @@StartBracket@@things would be different if Black already had a major piece on the c-file@@EndBracket@@. Both sides are about to lose two tempi:  10...b6  11.a3  Nc6  12.Bd3  The bishop returns. White may now look to the classic knight leap to e5 and here that might even be combined with Re1 and a rook lift via e3, not f3, all the while fighting against any possibility of ...Bb7; ...Nxe5; fxe5 Ne4. }
10. c4
{ Zukertort decides it's time to up the ante and gets on with things. Instead,  10.a3  would reach the same position as the previous variation and will be ourmain recommendation in the course. }
10... Ba6 11. Re1 Rc8 12. Rc1
{ Sensibly developing both rooks to semi-open files, but will Black now maintain the tension or inflict hanging pawns on White? }
12... Na5
{ Beginning to stray slightly off kilter.   12...dxc4  13.bxc4  Bb7  14.Qe2  A typical hanging pawns scenario, albeit one where Black has lost a tempo with his light-squared bishop. White should now be looking for any tactical possibilities to blow Black away with a well-timed d4-d5 advance. In such regard, Rad1 will be a useful move, while the latest engines are even tempted to involve Harry at some stage soon with h2-h4!?. }
13. Ne5 { Zukertort overprotects c4 while continuing to head forwards. } 13...
Bb4 14. c5
{ One of two strong moves  14.Re3!  being the other, as Blackburne finds himself coming under a certain clamp. }
14... Bxd3
{ 14...Bb7!  15.Re3!  A promising gambit. While Black picks up a pawn, White will go straight for the king:  15...bxc5  16.dxc5  Rxc5  17.Rxc5  Bxc5  18.Rh3  Already Bxh7+! is a threat and Black must weaken his kingside, leaving White with pretty decent compensation. }
15. Nxd3 Bxd2 16. Qxd2 Ne4 17. Qe3
{ The attack on the queen is easily dealt with as Black's difficulties become clear. He might like to release the tension and exchange on c5, but then dxc5 will turn the bishop on b2 into something of a monster. }
17... Re8 18. f3 Nf6 19. Rc2
{ 19.Qf4  Nd7  20.Bc3!  would have been an even better way to prepare queenside expansion. }
19... Nd7 20. Rec1
{ Zukertort simply want to blow Blackburne away with his advanced c-pawn. }
20... bxc5
{ 20...Nc6  21.b4  b5  22.Bc3  White will play to arrange a2-a4 and enjoys a pleasant edge, but Black should have dug in so, not freed the key Zukertort bishop for active duties. }
21. dxc5 Nb8 22. Ne5
{ Our favourite advance, but less powerful here than usual.   22.f4!  f6  23.Qg3  This was the way to gain a large advantage. While the bishop breathes fire down the long diagonal, White will simply aim the rooks against e6. }
22... f6
{ The obvious move Zukertort was hoping to provoke. Can you see what's wrong with it?   22...Nac6  23.f4  d4!  24.Qf2  White still has his useful passed c-pawn, but is only slightly for choice here:  24...Nxe5  25.fxe5  Nc6  26.Rd1  The engines give White only a fractional advantage here and it would have very much been a case of game on. }
23. c6
{ The refutation and a tactical blow which Blackburne must have overlooked. }
23... Rc7
{ A.  23...fxe5?  24.c7  Qe7  25.cxb8=Q  Rxb8  26.Rc7  Black is getting annihilated on the dark squares.   B.  23...d4!  was recommended by Zukertort, but even here White is much better:  24.Qe4  Re7  25.Nd3!  As so often, the tactics favour the side with the safer king, which is White here:  25...Rxc6   25...Naxc6  26.Nb4  f5  27.Qxd4!  Talk about exploiting a pin. Even if Black sensibly declines to capture, he is somewhat worse:  27...Rd7!  28.Qe3  Rd1+  29.Rxd1  Qxd1+  30.Kf2  The pin remains, leaving Black tied down and under pressure.  26.Nc5  White's wide array of threats @@StartBracket@@Ba3, b3-b4, Bxd4@@EndBracket@@ leave Black with nothing better than to return the pawn on d3 and grovel. }
24. Qd2
{ 24.Qe1!  This sneaky retreat would have left Black's position collapsing on the dark squares:  24...fxe5  25.Qxa5  25...Qd6  26.b4!  Now the c-pawn will more than live as a comrade arrives on b5 or Black will lose material to the various pins:  26...Rxc6?   26...Nxc6?  27.Qa6  27.Rxc6  Nxc6  28.Qa6 }
24... fxe5
{ 24...Nc4!  25.bxc4  fxe5  White has a few tempting options here, including the simple capture and exchanges:  26.Bxe5  Rxc6  27.cxd5  exd5  28.Bb2  With clear targets on d5 and g7, White is the clear favourite, but still has a fair bit of work to do. }
25. Qxa5 Qc8
{ 25...d4  26.Qxe5  d3  27.Rd2  This also leaves Black's position collapsing and the c-pawn taboo:  27...Nxc6?  28.Rxc6!  Rxc6  29.Qxg7 }
26. Bxe5 Rf7
{ 26...Rxc6  27.Qxa7  The defence is overloaded and White will win material. }
27. Bxb8 Qxb8 28. c7 Qc8 29. Qxa7
{ White now has three connected passed pawns, but Zukertort first moves to sensibly exploit his huge c-pawn while attacking Black's centre with tempo. }
29... e5 30. Rc5 e4 31. Rb5 Rff8 32. Rb8 Qd7 33. Rxe8 Rxe8 34. Qa4
{ By no means the only way to win, but a simple and good human solution. The rook ending's an easy win. }
34... Qxa4 35. bxa4 Rc8 36. fxe4 dxe4 37. Kf2 Kf7 38. Ke3 Ke6 39. Kxe4 g6 40.
Rc6+ Kd7 41. Kd5 *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Killer Colle Strategies"]
[Black "Rubinstein, A. vs. Salwe, G. Lodz (3), 1903"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. e3
{ 2.Nf3  Nf6  3.e3  e6  4.Bd3  This would, of course, be our preferred and slightly more exact move order. }
2... e6 3. Bd3 Nf6 4. Nf3
{ The great Rubinstein is back on course and next completes his development in perfect Colle-Zukertort fashion. }
4... c5 5. b3 { Preparing the fianchetto of the dark-squared Colle bishop. }
5... Nc6 6. Bb2
{ Completing White's ideal bishop set-up. We'll begin our detailed coverage by looking at what happens if Black fears ideas of dxc5 and so elects to exchange on d4 before going ...Be7. Such an idea was traditionally criticised, as now going Qe2 or Re1 will support a Ne5 advance while keeping Black out of e4, but the latest engines don't seem to mind it for Black. }
6... Bd6 7. Nbd2 O-O 8. O-O
{ With the king safely housed, White may now think about expansion with Ne5, a policy which Black's next only helps. }
8... cxd4 9. exd4
{ And here we have themainline in Chapter 3. The exchange on d4 has left White with firm control of e5. Despite that, nothing too terrible would be happening to Black if he now fianchettoed, but instead Salwe was to be too creative. }
9... Nh5 10. g3
{ Keeping the knight out of f4 so was praised by some annotators, but was probably not best.   10.Re1!  This should be an edge for White, since now the bishop can drop back to f1 if needed, while the ideas of both c2-c4 and Ne5 will exploit the black knight's slightly unusual position on the kingside. }
10... g6
{ Securing the knight, but also rather weakening.   10...f5  11.Ne5  Nf6  12.c4  This should be a little better for White, in part because he can meet any ... Ne4 raid with f2-f3, whereas Black can never use a pawn to push the knight on e5 away. }
11. Ne5 Bd7 12. f4
{ 12.Ndf3  This again looks quite pleasant for White, with Re1 and c2-c4 both on the agenda, and Black a little low on counterplay, but Rubinstein prefers a classic advance. }
12... Ng7
{ 12...f5!?  13.Qe2  White must have an edge here, but at least Black doesn't suffer from a strangely fianchettoed knight, as he now does in the game. }
13. a3
{ 13.Ndf3  Nf5  14.Qd2  This was a better way to retain control, since White doesn't need to fear any invasion on b4:  14...Nb4?  15.Bxf5  exf5  16.Ba3!  The pin is clearly rather problematic for Black to deal with. }
13... f5
{ The knight on g7 may cover e6, but it's also a long way from e4 and this is not a good type of Stonewall for Black.   13...Nf5!  14.Bxf5  exf5  15.c4  This can only be assessed as unclear, since both kings are potentially vulnerable and White's centre may yet be either weak or strong. }
14. Qe2
{ Rubinstein begins to take control as Salwe drifts further into passivity. }
14... Be8 15. Ndf3 Rc8 16. Kh1
{ With Black struggling for counterplay, Rubinstein realises that he can whip up a quick and powerful attack, while tucking his king away safely in the corner. }
16... h6
{ 16...Nxe5  17.dxe5  This feels like the best of the tempting recaptures, since a white bishop or knight will rather dominate proceedings from d4:  17...Bc5  18.Bd4  Bxd4  19.Nxd4  Just compare the knights and White can always support his with Qf2 if needed. }
17. Qe3 Be7 18. Rg1
{ White is now all set for g3-g4. Rather than sit tight and suffer, Salwe plumps for a radical counter, but it doesn't work out especially well. }
18... g5 19. g4
{ Anyhow! Lines are clearly going to open fast and likely to the detriment of the king on g8. }
19... gxf4
{ 19...fxg4  20.Nxg4  This is also a pretty big attack, not least with h6 collapsing and Black liable to be blown away in a sacrificial storm:  20...gxf4?  21.Nxh6+  Kh8  22.Rxg7!  22...Kxg7  23.Rg1+  Kh8  24.Qxe6  And it's going to be mate after all. }
20. Qxf4 Bg5 21. Nxg5
{ The immediate queen retreat was pretty good, but there's something almost mesmeric about Rubinstein's simple and strong play. }
21... hxg5 22. Qg3
{ Black's king is very much still the target and he now collapses quickly. }
22... f4
{ 22...Nxe5  23.Qxe5  fxg4  24.Rxg4  Qf6  25.Rxg5  is a clear extra pawn, but at least Black could then exchange the queens and mount some resistance. }
23. Qh3 { In we go... } 23... Nxe5 24. Qh7+ Kf7 25. dxe5 Rg8 26. a4
{ A very nice touch, not failing to include the Zukertort bishop in the attack after all. Black's king won't now manage to run away. }
26... b6 27. Ba3 Rc5 28. Qg6+ Kf8 29. Qf6+
{ Yet more simple and extremely strong chess. Rubinstein has spotted that the hapless knight hasn't a single safe square available. }
29... Qxf6 30. exf6 Bc6 31. Bxc5+ bxc5 32. fxg7+
{ It's a whole rook and Rge1 would be up next. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Killer Colle Strategies"]
[Black "Vaganian, R. vs. Adams, M. Armenia vs. World, 2004"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 e6 3. e3 b6 4. Bd3
{ For a second game, we find White happy to tackle Black's prospective Queen's Indian set-up with Colle play. }
4... Bb7 5. O-O d5
{ Adams elects to place a pawn right in the middle of the board after all and now the game quickly transposes to familiar Colle-Zukertort waters. }
6. b3 Bd6 7. Bb2 O-O 8. Ne5
{ With Black yet to touch his c-pawn, White goes straight for the leap rather than begin with  8.Nbd2  . }
8... c5 9. Nd2
{ Model play thus far from the former Soviet Champion and legendary Armenian Grandmaster. }
9... Nc6
{ Here we have the mainline ofChapter 4.   9...Ne4!?  10.Bxe4!  A good exchange in this position, especially with Black having done his best to blunt the bishop's gaze against h7.  10...dxe4  11.dxc5!  Bxc5  12.Qg4!  A brutal idea of the dangerous Ukrainian GM Igor Kovalenko. White simply wants to crash through on g7:  A.  12...h5   B.  12...Qxd2??  13.Nc4  Black is losing his queen.   C.  12...f5!  13.Qg3!  White's dark-square pressure and control of e5 gives him an ongoing, pleasant advantage and all because the knight still can't really be captured due to the various discoveries which the knight on e5 will set up:  13...Qxd2?  14.Rfd1  14...Qe2  15.Nd7  15...Qg4!  16.Qc7  White's powerful initiative ensures that he will at least regain his material with interest.  13.Qxh5!  This fearless capture improves over the 13.Qe2 of Kovalenko-Druska, Ordu 2018. Rfd1 is next up and even here the knight on d2 taboo:  13...Qxd2?  14.Rfd1  Qxc2   14...Qa5  15.Rd8!  A lovely as well as very powerful sacrifice. Can you now calculate the win?  15...Rxd8  16.Qxf7+  Kh7  17.Qg6+  Kg8  18.Qxe6+  Kh7  19.Qg6+  Kg8  20.Ng4!  There's simply no defence for the beleaguered black monarch.  15.Nc4  This time Black isn't getting mated, but his queen is trapped. }
10. a3
{ A little nudge and one seen enough in the Colle-Zukertort to keep Black's knight out of b4 and so away from the important bishop on d3. }
10... a5 11. f4
{ Thematic expansion as White supports his outpost before swinging a major piece over towards the black king via f3. Now Black might have sought some counterplay with 11...a4!?, but Adams was to prefer another standard enough motif, the transfer of Black's queen's knight over to help the kingside defence. }
11... Ne7 12. Rf3 cxd4 13. Bxd4
{ With Black's knight away from c6, recapturing so with the bishop becomes extremely tempting. White now threatens to whip up a massive attack with Rh3 and Ng4, for instance, and Adams was to uncharacteristically fail to mount a tough defence. }
13... Bxe5
{ 13...Bc5  14.Rh3  In practice this still feels quite dangerous for Black, but objectively he should be OK - so long as he's happy to defend well on the kingside. }
14. fxe5
{ Adams likely underestimated this unstereotyped but fairly strong recapture.   14.Bxe5  Ne4!  This is much less clear with lines closing and ...f6 on the way. }
14... Ne4
{ 14...Nd7?  15.Bxh7+!  Kxh7  16.Rh3+  Kg8  17.Qh5  17...f6  18.Rf1!  This direct assault completely overwhelms the defence. There's just no defence as White checks on h7 then crashes through on f6, or by bringing his knight over to g5:  18...f5  19.Nf3 }
15. Rh3
{ Vaganian continues to eye the black king, but also has a strong positional idea in mind. }
15... Nf5 16. Bxe4
{ Once again, we find this slightly unexpected exchange on e4 causing problems for Black. Here his kingside isn't about to be destroyed a la Kovalenko, but White is about to obtain either much the better bishop or a good knight against bad bishop scenario. }
16... dxe4 17. Nc4 Nxd4
{ A.  17...b5?!  18.Qh5  h6  19.Nd6!  A powerful breakthrough, as pointed out by Finkel in his notes to this game for ChessBase. Black pretty much must exchange on d6 and then suffer from several weaknesses, not grab the pawn:  19...Nxd6  20.exd6  Qxd6??  21.Bxg7!  It's suddenly all over.   B.  17...Rc8!  A typically calm engine resource, leaving White to either continue to try and break through on the kingside or exploit any small edge which the forcing endgame line gives him:  18.Bxb6   18.Qh5!?  Qxd1+  19.Rxd1  Ba6  20.Bxa5  Bxc4  21.bxc4  Rxc4  22.g4  . }
18. exd4 Bc6
{ Too slow.   18...f5!  19.Nd6  Qe7  20.Qh5  This is, of course, clearly better for White, but also somewhat preferable to the game for Black. }
19. Nd6 Qg5 20. Rc3
{ Vaganian first drives the bishop to a more exposed square before kicking the queen and then expanding with tempo. }
20... Bd5 21. Rg3 Qf4 22. c4 Bc6 23. Qf1
{ Simple chess. Black must pretty much now consent to a truly miserable endgame. }
23... Qxf1+
{ 23...Qh6?  24.d5!  24...Bd7  25.Nxe4  This would, unsurprisingly, also have been rather crushing. }
24. Rxf1 Rab8 25. Rf4
{ We're used to seeing Michael Adams on the other side of such positions which his spider-like play often leads to. Here, though, he is devoid of counterplay and can only watch as Vaganian instructively keeps the queenside closed while improving his own pieces. }
25... b5 26. c5 a4 27. b4 Rbd8 28. Rfg4 g6 29. Rf4
{ White is even able to clamp down on any notion of a desperate ...f6 break. }
29... Kg7 30. Rf6 Rd7 31. Kf2
{ It's high time to improve the king. Sooner or later, White wants to break through on the kingside, but he might as well place all the pieces on their best squares first. }
31... Ra8 32. Ke3 Raa7 33. h4 h6
{ 33...h5  White might now continue to manoeuvre or opt to crash through:  34.d5!?  34...exd5  35.Nf5+  Kh7  36.Nd4  Ba8  37.Nxb5  This will be followed by Nd4 or Nd6 and either breaking through on f7 or g6, or just advancing the connected queenside passed pawn duo. }
34. Rh3 Rd8 35. Rh1 { Heading for f1 as a decisive blow looms. } 35... Re7
{ 35...Rad7  36.Rhf1  Rf8  37.d5!  This is also a decisive breakthrough, followed by collecting b5 or crashing ahead on the kingside:  37...exd5  38.h5  38...g5  39.Nf5+ }
36. h5 g5
{ Allowing a tactical blow after all, but Black's cause had long been positionally bankrupt.   36...Rdd7  37.hxg6  fxg6  38.Rhf1  Black won't be able to handle the decisive infiltration via f8 @@StartBracket@@or f7@@EndBracket@@. }
37. d5 Bxd5 38. Nxb5
{ The knight will return to d6, after which Black won't be able to cover f7 and halt the soon-to-be-onrushing pawns for long. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Killer Colle Strategies"]
[Black "Williams, S. vs. Haria, R. British Ch. 2019"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 e6 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. e3 d5 4. Bd3
{ The natural square to develop the bishop, which will very often prove White's most effective attacker. }
4... Bd6 5. O-O O-O 6. b3 b6 7. Ne5
{ Yet again we see Black's delay in breaking with ...c5 causing White to opt for something more externally ambitious than immediately completing the fianchetto. We're soon back in standard waters though. }
7... Bb7 8. Bb2 Nbd7 9. Nd2
{ Of course, this position could also occur had White gone @@StartFEN@@rnbq1rk1/p1p2ppp/1p1bpn2/3p4/3P4/1P1BPN2/P1P2PPP/RNBQ1RK1 w - - 0 7@@EndFEN@@  7.Bb2  , 8. Nbd2 and only then 9. Ne5. Now Black should probably strike back in turn by launching his own king's knight into e4, whereas Haria allows Simon to take control of that key square. }
9... Qe7 10. Qf3 Ba3
{ A big decision, if an idea in general which is seen a fair amount in the Colle-Zukertort. While the bishop on b2 isn't currently too active, experienced black players are aware of the carnage it can cause @@StartBracket@@after dxc5 or Bxd4, for instance@@EndBracket@@, and so elect to prophylactically exchange it off. }
11. Bxa3 Qxa3 12. Qh3 { With a threat. } 12... g6
{ A.  12...Nxe5?!  13.dxe5  Ne4  14.f3  Using the weakness of h7 to drive the knight back:  14...Ng5  15.Qh5  h6  16.h4!  Nh7  17.f4  This feels like a pretty dangerous attack, especially if Simon was playing White! Already f4-f5 is an idea, as is g4-g5.   B.  12...Rad8!?  13.f4  Ne4  14.Rad1!  White is slightly for choice here, with ideas of both Nf3 and Nxe4 dxe4; Bc4, but at least this way Black would have avoided weakening his kingside. }
13. f4
{ An extremely strong version of our favourite f2-f4 advance. Suddenly a rook lift followed by doubling the major pieces on the h-file looms, as does a Yusupov style attack with Nd2-f3-g5. }
13... Qe7 14. Ndf3 Nxe5
{ 14...c5  15.Ng5!  This still feels pretty scary for Black, with Qh6 one threat and White might also calmly involve both his rooks via the f-file, perhaps as a prelude to pushing the g-pawn. }
15. fxe5
{ Usually the right recapture and especially so here when Black's knight can't leap forwards in any effective manner. }
15... Nd7
{ 15...Ne4  16.Qh6  Already there is a big threat and even the obvious defensive try leaves Black struggling:  16...f6  17.exf6  Nxf6  18.Qg5  White dominates the kingside and dark squares, and will simply increase the pressure with Ne5 followed by doubling rooks, just as Simon now does in the game. }
16. Qg3
{ Freeing Harry for action and with such a vulnerable kingside, it's no surprise that Haria now consented to take on a pretty grim French-type set-up. }
16... f6 17. exf6 Nxf6 18. Ne5
{ Clearly Black must now fear a blow on g6, as well as the simple and strong plan of White doubling rooks. }
18... Qg7 19. Qh3 Rae8 20. Rf2 Bc8
{ As active a square as any for this truly miserable bishop and notably the engines long feel Black is passed the point of no return. Simon now demonstrates why. }
21. Raf1 { Now Qh4 and, if the knight retreats, Rf7 will clean Black up. }
21... Nh5 22. g4
{ Simon wants even more than winning queen for rook and knight by invading on f7, and why not? }
22... Rxf2 23. Rxf2 Nf6 24. g5 Nh5 25. Be2
{ A very human decisive, retaining all White's positional plusses while picking off a key pawn.   25.Rf7  Qxf7  26.Nxf7  Kxf7  27.Be2!  This would surely have also won, with the extra queen likely to quickly be rampant. }
25... Rf8 26. Bxh5 gxh5 27. Qxh5 Ba6 28. Qg4
{ Trying to make the bishop bad again as White also welcomes any endgame with such a fine, centralised knight on e5. }
28... Rxf2 29. Kxf2 Qf8+ 30. Qf3 Qe8
{ 30...Qxf3+  31.Kxf3  31...Bb5  32.Kf4  Kg7  33.Ng4  Kg6  34.h4  This is, of course, but quite lost, as well as positional hell for Black. }
31. Qf6 Qh5
{ A desperate bid for activity, but Simon fully knows that 'queen and knight, they're alright' and now demonstrates why. }
32. Qxe6+ Kf8 33. Nd7+
{ A killer check. Haria now sportingly allows the mate at the end of what has been an unusually one-sided struggle ever since White launched such a powerful early attack in our favourite set-up. }
33... Kg7 34. Qf6+ Kg8 35. Qf8# *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Killer Colle Strategies"]
[Black "Yusupov, A. vs. Scheeren, P. Eu. Team Ch. 1983"]
[Result "*"]

{ This has long been one of Richard's favourite Colle-Zukertort games. In general he's tried to avoid using the same illustrative games here as in his 2008 book 'Starting Out: d-pawn Attacks', but this classic win from Colle legend Artur Yusupov was just too hard to resist! }
1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 e6 3. e3
{ We see that White can also meet Black's attempt to play a Bogo or Queen's Indian @@StartBracket@@after 3. c4@@EndBracket@@ with the Colle. }
3... c5 4. Bd3 d5
{ And now we're back in familiar waters, with White set to play our favourite move, one which helps both his bishops. }
5. b3 { Preparing the fianchetto of the dark-squared Colle bishop. } 5... Nbd7
6. Bb2 b6 7. O-O Bb7 8. Ne5
{ White could have continued standard development with  8.Nbd2  but against Black's slightly unusual set-up, Yusupov elects to up the ante without delay and now Black may have become concerned by Bb5 ideas. }
8... a6 9. Nd2 b5
{ Consistent with Black's slightly unnecessary last, but also an ambitious advance. Can you see how White might respond? }
10. Nxd7
{ A strong exchange as Yusupov is quick to open lines and put his superior development to good use. Of course, White needed to avoid ...c4; The pinning  10.Qf3!?  was, as such, also an option. }
10... Qxd7
{ 10...Nxd7  11.dxc5!  Nxc5  12.Qh5  Once again we see White quick to open up the Zukertort bishop and stand somewhat better. Just compare the dark-squared bishops and kings! There's no need to fear an exchange on d3 here @@StartBracket@@any trade of rooks on an open c-file won't help Black untangle his kingside@@EndBracket@@, and White is all set to thematically expand with f2-f4 and Nf3. }
11. dxc5
{ This does allow the bishop on f8 to develop in one stroke, but more importantly, Black's kingside is going to feel the heat from those most harmoniously-placed bishops on d3 and b2. }
11... Bxc5 12. Qf3
{ An immediate exchange on f6 would not be a great use of White's monster dark-squared bishop, but now it's a threat as Yusupov also introduces ideas of Qg3, which could be awkward to meet. }
12... Be7
{ A.  12...d4?  13.Ne4!  Continuing to go forwards while forcing favourable exchanges.  13...Nxe4  14.Bxe4  Bxe4  15.Qxe4  Black will lose a pawn, unless he prefers to blunder a piece on the d-file:  15...Rd8  16.exd4  Bxd4??  17.Rad1   B.  12...Qe7!?  13.Qg3!  13...O-O  14.a3!?  This follows some analysis from Yusupov himself. White is slightly for choice, with ideas of both the aggressive Nf3-g5 and taking a queenside clamp with b3-b4, Nb3 and Bd4. }
13. Qg3 { Once again g7 and the black king are White's targets. } 13... O-O 14.
Nf3
{ 14.f4  was also promising, but Yusupov has spotted a powerful attacking idea, one which Black now overlooks. }
14... Rac8
{ A.  14...h6?!  15.Ne5  Qc7  16.f4  This time the knight has settled on e5, not g5, but White is clearly in full control and will likely increase the kingside pressure with Ng4.   B.  14...Bd6!?  15.Ne5!   15.Qh4  This looks tempting, but Black may well be OK after an only response:  15...Ne4!  Qe7  16.f4  Again we find White with a clamp and, as well as Ng4 ideas, both f4-f5 and even a2-a4 might ask Black some awkward questions. }
15. Ng5
{ Suddenly h7 is under direct attack and Black must weaken his kingside. }
15... g6
{ 15...h6?  16.Nh7!  A powerful leap and one which forces Black to part with the exchange on f8. }
16. Qh4 h5 17. Rad1
{ Centralisation and lining the rook up against the enemy queen is rarely a bad policy.   17.Qd4!?  Qc7  18.a4  b4  19.Nf3  A promising alternative to retain clear control. White might even manage to get Ne5 followed by Qf4 in and then some sort of sacrificial blow.   19.f3?  This was Richard's earlier idea here, but there's a tactical flaw:  19...e5!  20.Qxe5  Qxe5  21.Bxe5  Nd7  22.Bf4  Nc5  23.Be2  f6  24.Nh3  Unsurprisingly, with White pushed backwards so, Black must have decent compensation. }
17... Nh7
{ 17...Qc7  18.f4  Even this would have been very nice for White, who might now play for a similar sacrifice to that which we're about to see in the game:  18...Bc6?  19.Be5  Qd7  20.g4!  20...Nxg4?  21.Qxh5!  It's mate in two. }
18. Qxh5
{ Olé! Yusupov exploits his fine attacking set-up to crash through in style. }
18... Bxg5 { 18...gxh5??  19.Bxh7 } 19. Bxg6
{ The key follow-up and one which ensures that White will regain his piece with interest. }
19... f6 20. f4 Qg7 21. fxg5 Nxg5 22. h4 { Ever forwards! } 22... Ne4
{ 22...Nh7  23.Rd4!  This was Yusupov's idea and all Colle-Zukertort players should always be weighing up any possible rook lifts when attacking. Here the arrival of the rook on g4 will herald the end:  23...f5  24.Bxh7+  Qxh7  25.Rg4+!  It's mate in two again. }
23. Bxe4 dxe4 24. Rf4 { The black queen is a goner. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "...Nc6 / ...Be7 Setup with ...cxd4"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4
{ In this course we'll map out a full repertoire for White after  1...d5  ,  based around a classic Colle approach with 2. Nf3 and 3. e3. }
1... d5 2. Nf3
{ With this move, White prepares to enter the Colle setup, and remains flexible with the c-pawn, contrary to the Queen's Gambit. The extra control over e5 rules out lines such as the Albin Countergambit. }
2... Nf6 3. e3
{ White is now all set to go Bd3 and then b2-b3 and Bb2. Black's main move here is to copy with 3...e6, but some stronger or uncompromising opponents may prefer something else. }
3... e6 4. Bd3
{ The natural square to develop the bishop, which will very often prove White's most effective attacker. }
4... c5 5. b3 { Preparing the fianchetto of the dark-squared Colle bishop. }
5... Nc6 6. Bb2 cxd4
{ Relieving the central tension is very typical at this moment. } 7. exd4
{ Needless to say, we recapture with the pawn and so maintain maximum control of the key e5-square. }
7... Be7 8. O-O O-O 9. Nbd2 { White continues with all the standard moves. }
9... b6 10. a3
{ This useful device intends to continue with Qe2 @@StartBracket@@now that ...Nb4 is ruled out@@EndBracket@@ and only then Ne5, as we'll cover inChapter 1 @@StartBracket@@instead here  10.c4  was seen in the illustrative introductory gameZukertort-Blackburne, London International Masters 1883@@EndBracket@@. }
*

