1. d4
{ In this course we'll map out a full repertoire for White after  1...d5  ,  based around a classic Colle approach with 2. Nf3 and 3. e3. }
1... d5 2. Nf3
{ With this move, White prepares to enter the Colle setup, and remains flexible with the c-pawn, contrary to the Queen's Gambit. The extra control over e5 rules out lines such as the Albin Countergambit. }
2... Nf6 3. e3
{ White is now all set to go Bd3 and then b2-b3 and Bb2. Black's main move here is to copy with 3...e6, but some stronger or uncompromising opponents may prefer something else. }
3... e6 4. Bd3
{ The natural square to develop the bishop, which will very often prove White's most effective attacker. }
4... c5 5. b3 { Preparing the fianchetto of the dark-squared Colle bishop. }
5... Nc6 6. Bb2 Bd6 7. O-O O-O 8. Nbd2
{ This might be considered the main line of the Colle-Zukertort. White has played all the right moves so far, but we now have a small surprise in store for Black should he attempt to force through ...e5 by deploying the queen to e7. }
8... Re8 9. dxc5 Bxc5 10. c4
{ This timely change of approach exploits the slightly slow nature of ...Re8. White has pressure against d5 and the kingside, and may just continue with a2-a3 and Qc2, as we'll see inChapter 4. }
