{ White is now all set to go Bd3 and then b2-b3 and Bb2. Black's main move here is to copy with 3...e6, but some stronger or uncompromising opponents may prefer something else. }
3... e6 4. Bd3
{ The natural square to develop the bishop, which will very often prove White's most effective attacker. }
4... c5 5. b3 { Preparing the fianchetto of the dark-squared Colle bishop. }
5... Nbd7 6. Bb2 b6 7. O-O Bb7 8. Ne5
{ The immediate leap is justified when Black delays developing his dark-squared bishop on e5. Play may now transpose to one of the main lines  @@StartBracket@@  8...Bd6  9.f4  or  8...Be7  9.Qe2  @@EndBracket@@  , but White also hopes to tempt Black forwards on the queenside. }
8... a6 9. Nd2 b5 10. Nxd7
{ Black often underestimates this exchange, which can be a strong one when played in conjunction with opening up the Zukertort bishop on b2. }
10... Qxd7 11. dxc5 Bxc5 12. Qf3
{ With Qg3 next up, Black was already under pressure inYusupov-Scheeren, European Team Championship, Plovdiv 1983. }
