1. d4
{ In this course we'll map out a full repertoire for White after  1...d5  ,  based around a classic Colle approach with 2. Nf3 and 3. e3. }
1... d5 2. Nf3
{ With this move, White prepares to enter the Colle setup, and remains flexible with the c-pawn, contrary to the Queen's Gambit. The extra control over e5 rules out lines such as the Albin Countergambit. }
2... Nf6 3. e3
{ White is now all set to go Bd3 and then b2-b3 and Bb2. Black's main move here is to copy with 3...e6, but some stronger or uncompromising opponents may prefer something else. }
3... g6 4. c4
{ A strong central challenge as we angle for an improved version of a Grünfeld. }
4... Bg7 5. cxd5
{ Now  5...Nxd5  6.e4  would see White losing a tempo, but also obtaining a fairly secure centre since here Black lacks the standard Grünfeld exchange of knights on c3. }
5... O-O 6. Be2 Nxd5 7. e4
{ Again, the key advance and now  7...Nf6  8.Nc3  would leave Black a little low on counterplay. }
7... Nb6 8. O-O Bg4 9. Nbd2
{ This key follow-up keeps White secure on f3 and d4 and, indeed, Black faces a few issues in this variation, as we'll see further inChapter 10. }
