3... c5 4. dxc5
{ Again, a principled exchange. Now  4...Qa5+  5.Nbd2  Qxc5  6.a3!  prepares to expand rapidly with b2-b4, so Black may instead prefer something more unbalanced. }
4... e6 5. b4 { Taking up the challenge ahead of shoring up b4. } 5... a5 6. c3
axb4 7. cxb4 b6 8. Bb5+
{ A key check to speed up White's development and not  8.cxb6?  Bxb4+  . } 8...
Bd7 9. Bxd7+ Nbxd7 10. a4
{ This advance is the point of White's play as we return the extra pawn to obtain an well-advanced queenside pawn duo. }
10... bxc5 11. b5
{ This rich position is essentially a kind of reversed Abrahams-Noteboom variation. White aims to complete development with Bb2, O-O and Nbd2, after which he might be able to break in the centre with e3-e4 or begin to roll the queenside pawns. We'll consider it in some detail inChapter 11. }
