[Result "*"]

1. d4
{ In this course we'll map out a full repertoire for White after  1...d5  ,  based around a classic Colle approach with 2. Nf3 and 3. e3. }
1... Nf6 2. Nf3 e6 3. e3
{ The Colle also works well against Nimzo and Queen's Indian players! Now  3...d5  4.Bd3  would return play to our main line, but Black can also fianchetto. }
3... b6 4. Bd3 Bb7 5. O-O
{ Kingside development first. White is now able to meet  5...Ne4  with  6.c4!  and otherwise simply wants to continue in classic Colle-Zukertort fashion with b2-b3, Bb2 and Nbd2. }
5... c5 6. b3 Be7 7. Bb2 O-O 8. Nbd2
{ Completing our favourite set-up and now Black must decide whether he wants to retain the central tension or exchange on d4 @@StartBracket@@incidentally, in this line he'll often in practice have already exchanged those pawns@@EndBracket@@: }
8... Nc6 9. a3
{ This is ever a good reaction to ...Nc6, sidestepping any potential issues with ...Nb4, and if Be2 cxd4; exd4 Nd5. }
9... Rc8 10. Qe2
{ The white queen is unlikely to find a better square and White may now challenge for the centre with c2-c4, as well as bring the rooks to c1 and d1. We'll see how play may continue in bothChapter 17 andYusupov-Hulak, Jakarta International 1983. }
