[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "Queen's Indian Setup with ...cxd4 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4
{ In this course we'll map out a full repertoire for White after  1...d5  ,  based around a classic Colle approach with 2. Nf3 and 3. e3. }
1... Nf6 2. Nf3 e6 3. e3
{ The Colle also works well against Nimzo and Queen's Indian players! Now  3...d5  4.Bd3  would return play to our main line, but Black can also fianchetto. }
3... b6 4. Bd3 Bb7 5. O-O
{ Kingside development first. White is now able to meet  5...Ne4  with  6.c4!  and otherwise simply wants to continue in classic Colle-Zukertort fashion with b2-b3, Bb2 and Nbd2. }
5... c5 6. b3 Be7 7. Bb2 O-O 8. Nbd2
{ Completing our favourite set-up and now Black must decide whether he wants to retain the central tension or exchange on d4 @@StartBracket@@incidentally, in this line he'll often in practice have already exchanged those pawns@@EndBracket@@: }
8... cxd4 9. exd4 Nc6 10. a3
{ Again this is a handy prophylactic device, after which White improved his king's rook with Rfe1 and then went c2-c4, quickly seizing a powerful initiative in Hodgson-Jackelen, German Bundesliga 2001. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "Queen's Indian Setup with ...cxd4 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4
{ In this course we'll map out a full repertoire for White after  1...d5  ,  based around a classic Colle approach with 2. Nf3 and 3. e3. }
1... Nf6 2. Nf3 e6 3. e3
{ The Colle also works well against Nimzo and Queen's Indian players! Now  3...d5  4.Bd3  would return play to our main line, but Black can also fianchetto. }
3... b6 4. Bd3 Bb7 5. O-O
{ Kingside development first. White is now able to meet  5...Ne4  with  6.c4!  and otherwise simply wants to continue in classic Colle-Zukertort fashion with b2-b3, Bb2 and Nbd2. }
5... c5 6. b3 Be7 7. Bb2 O-O 8. Nbd2
{ Completing our favourite set-up and now Black must decide whether he wants to retain the central tension or exchange on d4 @@StartBracket@@incidentally, in this line he'll often in practice have already exchanged those pawns@@EndBracket@@: }
8... cxd4 9. exd4 d6 10. c4
{ With Black's queen's knight likely en route to d7, it makes sense to fight for control of the centre so. }
10... Nbd7 11. Re1
{ Black now isn't exactly set to expand with ...e5 and the rook may prove useful here should White ever get in d4-d5 and/or start a kingside attack. }
11... Re8 12. Rc1
{ White's set-up is quite a harmonious one and now we may even be able to begin to expand on the queenside with b3-b4 and even Nd2-b1-c3, as we'll see inChapter 16. }
