[White "1) ...Nc6 / …Be7 Setup with …cxd4"]
[Black "...Nc6 / ...Be7 / ...cxd4 Setup: 8...O-O #5"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Nf3
{ With this move, White prepares to enter the Colle setup, and remains flexible with the c-pawn, contrary to the Queen's Gambit. The extra control over e5 rules out lines such as the Albin Countergambit. }
2... Nf6 3. e3 e6 4. Bd3
{ The natural square to develop the bishop, which will very often prove White's most effective attacker. }
4... c5 5. b3 { Preparing the fianchetto of the dark-squared Colle bishop. }
5... Nc6 6. Bb2
{ In this first chapters, we'll begin by looking at a popular set-up at club level, where Black combines ...Nc6 with the slightly more passive ...Be7. We'll then progress to consider the ultimate main line, ...Nc6 and ...Bd6 set-ups, before looking at set-ups with ...Nbd7 and Black's other options against the Colle-Zukertort.  Here we'll focus on:  Chapter 1:  6...cxd4  7.exd4  Be7   Chapter 2:  6...Be7   As you're probably aware by now, transpositions abound in the Colle-Zukertort and here, for instance,  6...b6  7.O-O  Bb7  8.Nbd2  Be7  9.Ne5  O-O  10.f4  would but be another route into a position we'll consider in via a  6...Be7  7.O-O  O-O  8.Nbd2  b6  9.Ne5  Bb7  10.f4  move order. }
6... cxd4 { Relieving the central tension is very typical at this moment. } 7.
exd4
{ Needless to say, we recapture with the pawn and so maintain maximum control of the key e5-square. }
7... Be7
{ A more passive square for the bishop than d6, but a common choice at club level, often for two reasons: Black is used to placing this bishop on e7 in the Queen's Gambit Declined and, for a more experienced player, they may want to meet Ne5 with an exchange of knights which would not, of course, be possible if dxe5 then forked a bishop on d6 and knight on f6. }
8. O-O
{ A decent case can also be made for  8.Nbd2  and even  8.a3  but there's absolutely no reason not to safely house the king before completing queenside development and deciding whether or not to jump into e5. }
8... O-O
{ Black follows suit. As we've already mentioned, there are transpositions abound:  8...b6  9.Nbd2  Bb7  10.a3  This keeps Black out of b4 and doesn't obviously allow Black anything better than basically a transposition to the line we see here. }
9. Nbd2
{ Continuing our favourite development pattern and refusing to fear  9...Nb4  when  10.Be2  followed by 11. a3 and 12. Bd3 will replace the bishop. }
9... b6 { Further natural development from Black, if not forced. } 10. a3
{ Once again, this is a useful prophylactic nudge and good preparation for Qe2. There's no need to rush with Ne5, although we did see a Colle-Zukertort legend making a good case for  10.c4  inZukertort-Blackburne. }
10... Bb7
{ Black completes what is a pretty sensible set-up for him, albeit a slightly passive one. }
11. Qe2
{ Simple chess, connecting the rooks. Note one main difference between the two sides is that White can easily now sink his knight into e5,  whereas ...Ne4 will cost Black a pawn and, yes,  11.Ne5  Nxe5!  12.dxe5  Ne4  would equalise for Black. }
11... Qc7 12. Ne5
{ White leaps forward and frees the way for both f2-f4 and Ndf3. With Black's queen on c7, White might even prefer the latter, especially if he wants to team it up with c2-c4 and Rac1. We should also note what happens if Black now tries to free his position with an exchange on e5: }
12... Nxe5 13. dxe5 Nd7
{ The threat of ...Nc5 to hunt down the light-squared bishop appears a little annoying, but despite that White can claim an edge: }
14. Nf3 Nc5 15. Nd4
{ The white knight radiates power and we are now set to expand with f2-f4 after all, with both Rae1 and b3-b4 @@StartBracket@@fighting for the c5-square and to keep the bishop on b7 a fairly bad piece@@EndBracket@@ also likely to prove useful and any exchange on d3 will be met by cxd3. }
