11... Rc8
{ Black's most popular choice by some margin, placing the rook on the half-open c-file. }
12. Ne5
{ It's time to head forwards and now White may well involve the rooks via Rae1 and f2-f4. }
12... Nxe5
{ Lacking counterplay, Black elects to exchange knights and before White is in a position to reply with an f-file-clearing fxe5 recapture. }
13. dxe5 Ne4
{ The move that Black would like to make work, especially if happy with mass exchanges and playing for a draw, but it does cost a pawn: }
14. Nxe4 dxe4 15. Bxe4 Bxe4 16. Qxe4
{ Now White will consolidate, if allowed, with Rfd1 and c2-c4, so Black probably has to invade: }
16... Qd2 17. Rac1 Rfd8 18. Rfe1
{ While Black is clearly quite active, he shouldn't have quite enough for the pawn and White might improve his pieces with g2-g3, Kg2, h2-h4 and Re2, driving the black queen backwards. }
