13. dxe5 Nd7 { Trying to reroute to c5, but it's not happening. } 14. b4
{ A strong advance and much better choice than  14.c4?  Nc5   Suddenly Black finds himself quite cramped and with White all set to expand. Indeed, even f4-f5 is very much on the cards and, of course, any counter ...f6 break would lead to Black dropping the e6-pawn, thereby revealing another good point behind placing the queen on e2. @@StartFEN@@2rq1rk1/pb1nbppp/1p2p3/3pP3/1P6/P2B4/1BPNQPPP/R4RK1 b - - 0 14@@EndFEN@@  14...a5  15.c3   Vishy Anand and some other decent players have made a decent case for  15.Qg4  which is a good move, but the text may well be even stronger.  Now White is all set to dominate with Nf3-d4 and/or crash through with f4-f5 and we are even happy to see Black force the pace.  15...d4  16.cxd4  axb4  17.axb4  Bxb4  18.Ne4  The point. Despite Black's mini-breakout, White dominates the board and stood clearly better in Oparin-Tarigan, Titled Tuesday Blitz 2022. One idea to increase the pressure is Ra7, another Bc1 followed by Ng5 with a dangerous looking attack indeed, and all the while as Black continues to struggle for counterplay. }
