[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2) ...Nc6 / …Be7 Setup without …cxd4"]
[Black "...Nc6 / ...Be7 Setup: 7...Qc7"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Nf3
{ With this move, White prepares to enter the Colle setup, and remains flexible with the c-pawn, contrary to the Queen's Gambit. The extra control over e5 rules out lines such as the Albin Countergambit. }
2... Nf6 3. e3 e6 4. Bd3
{ The natural square to develop the bishop, which will very often prove White's most effective attacker. }
4... c5 5. b3 { Preparing the fianchetto of the dark-squared Colle bishop. }
5... Nc6 6. Bb2 Be7
{ Black gets on with the process of completing kingside development. } 7. O-O
{ Following our standard approach: deploy the bishops to fine squares, house the king and only then, usually, look to involve the knights with Nbd2 and Ne5. }
7... Qc7
{ This is clearly quite a specific approach. Indeed, Black is hoping to equalise with  8.Nbd2  cxd4  9.exd4  Nb4! }
8. dxc5
{ A change of approach and one we quite like against an early ...Qc7, whether Black has gone ...Bd6 or ...Be7. By all means stick to 8. a3 followed by 9. Nbd2 if you prefer, but we are allowed to aim for even more and to try and exploit Black's move order!  Incidentally, if you don't mind playing with hanging pawns then  8.c4!?  is also a good choice. }
8... Bxc5 9. Nbd2
{ White completes development and asks Black: Are you worried by an exchange on f6? We're in no rush to part with our big bishop, but don't be surprised if Black were now to go  9...Qe7  or  9...Be7  when White should still open up the position with  10.c4  . Probably a more critical response is for Black to castle: }
9... O-O 10. c4
{ Only now are we threatening to take on f6. Why? Well after, say,  10...b6?  11.Bxf6  gxf6  12.cxd5  exd5  Black's pawn structure would be completely shredded, with big holes on the kingside, as well the IQP. }
10... dxc4 11. Nxc4
{ Activating the knight while taking control of e5 once again. Now Rc1 and Nce5 would be a simple way to increase the pressure and  11...b5?  12.Nce5  merely loosens Black's position. }
11... Rd8 12. Qe2
{ Sensibly stepping off the open file while renewing the idea of Rc1 and Nce5. Rc1 is definitely going to prove useful, as might then expansion with a2-a3 and b3-b4 or even a direct attack against h7 with Ng5.  In short, White has a pleasant advantage.  12...Nb4  13.Bb1  Nbd5  14.Nce5   Having preserved a key attacking piece, the light-squared bishop, White heads forwards and this leap may be even stronger than:  14.a3  of Itkis-Flom, Arad 2012.   White now threatens to whip up a sudden attack with Ng5 and also has ideas of Rc1 and a2-a3 followed by b3-b4. We should also note that with Black quite passive and behind in development, the engines even wonder if White might not suddenly strike with g2-g4!? and then g5, followed by assaulting h7. Put that in your pipe and smoke it! }
