4... c5 5. b3 { Preparing the fianchetto of the dark-squared Colle bishop. }
5... Nc6 6. Bb2 Be7
{ Black gets on with the process of completing kingside development. } 7. O-O
{ Following our standard approach: deploy the bishops to fine squares, house the king and only then, usually, look to involve the knights with Nbd2 and Ne5. }
7... O-O
{ Black usually follows suit. Once again,  7...Nb4  is nothing to fear due to  8.Be2  ,  and if  8...cxd4  9.exd4  Qc7  10.a3!  ,  as we saw inthis line in Chapter 1. }
8. Nbd2
{ Sensibly continuing development and now  8...cxd4  9.exd4  would, of course, take play back into the realm ofChapter 1 }
8... b6
{ By some margin Black's main move and we should now be on the look-out after ... Bb7 for his trying to time an exchange of knights on e5 followed by going ... Ne4. }
9. Ne5
{ The direct approach. Yet again, we want to go f2-f4 then attack. Instead,  9.Qe2?!  Nb4  is not recommended.   But if you don't mind a slower, manoeuvring approach,  9.a3  Bb7  10.Qe2  is far from a terrible alternative and has been used by Mamedyarov. }
9... Nb4 10. Be2
{ Needless to say, we preserve the bishop and will now aim to get in f2-f4, a2-a3 and Bd3. It's also worth pointing out that Black should now continue with  10...Bb7  as ...Ba6 ideas blunder a piece to c2-c3, since the knight on b4 then lacks a safe square. }
10... Bb7 11. f4
{ Expansion before kicking the knight, as  11.a3  Nc6  12.Bd3  doesn't lead to ourmain line @@StartBracket@@after 9...Bb7@@EndBracket@@ and can be met by  12...Nxe5!  13.dxe5  Ne4  . }
11... Ne4
{ 11...Rc8  12.a3  Nc6  13.Bd3  and we're back in our main line, i.e.  @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/p3bppp/1pn1pn2/2ppN3/3P4/1P1BP3/PBPN1PPP/R2Q1RK1 b - - 1 9@@EndFEN@@  9...Bb7  10.f4  Rc8  11.a3  . }
12. Nxe4
{ Taking the chance to double Black's pawns and also avoid a simplifying exchange on d2. }
12... dxe4 13. a3 Nd5 { This must be critical, attacking e3. } 14. Qd2
{ A fairly forced response. Had the black knight not gone to d5, White would have had ideas of Qe1-g3 and so, yes, here c2-c4 followed by Rad1 and Qe1-g3 is very much a plan. }
14... f6
{ 14...Rc8?!  15.c4  Nf6  16.Rad1  White enjoys an active and harmonious set-up, and we'll see how he was quick to make good use of the Zukertort bishop on b2 in Yusupov-N.Spiridonov, European Team Championship, Plovdiv 1983. }
15. Ng4 cxd4 16. Bxd4
{ The best way to recapture, keeping the bishop active, while avoiding  16.exd4  f5!  Now any ...f5 advance will merely leave a huge hole on e5, while ...h5? would be pretty weakening and can easily be met by Nf2.   White's simple plan is to expand with c2-c4 and b3-b4, after which Rfd1 may offer chances to invade down the d-file. While Black is quite solid, White's position looks slightly the easier to handle and Black didn't survive in the long run in both Stefanova-Doluhanova, Monte Carlo  @@StartBracket@@blitz@@EndBracket@@ 2017, and Tikkanen-Eriksson, Swedish League 2019. }
