{ The natural square to develop the bishop, which will very often prove White's most effective attacker. }
4... c5 5. b3 { Preparing the fianchetto of the dark-squared Colle bishop. }
5... Nc6 6. Bb2 Be7
{ Black gets on with the process of completing kingside development. } 7. O-O
{ Following our standard approach: deploy the bishops to fine squares, house the king and only then, usually, look to involve the knights with Nbd2 and Ne5. }
7... O-O
{ Black usually follows suit. Once again,  7...Nb4  is nothing to fear due to  8.Be2  ,  and if  8...cxd4  9.exd4  Qc7  10.a3!  ,  as we saw inthis line in Chapter 1. }
8. Nbd2
{ Sensibly continuing development and now  8...cxd4  9.exd4  would, of course, take play back into the realm ofChapter 1 }
8... b6
{ By some margin Black's main move and we should now be on the look-out after ... Bb7 for his trying to time an exchange of knights on e5 followed by going ... Ne4. }
9. Ne5
{ The direct approach. Yet again, we want to go f2-f4 then attack. Instead,  9.Qe2?!  Nb4  is not recommended.   But if you don't mind a slower, manoeuvring approach,  9.a3  Bb7  10.Qe2  is far from a terrible alternative and has been used by Mamedyarov. }
9... Nxe5 10. dxe5 Nd7 11. f4
{ A dream scenario for White, who already threatens to force a serious weakness on the kingside with Qh5, after which we should be looking to lift a rook or blow Black away with an f4-f5 strike. This is also a position where you have a definite choice - a good case was made for  11.c4!?  back in the introductory section on the e5 outpost.   We'll see after  11.f4  how quickly Black was blown away after  11...Re8?!  @@StartBracket@@preparing ...Nf8@@EndBracket@@  12.Qf3  in Bu Xiangzhi-Thorhallsson, Reykjavik @@StartBracket@@rapid@@EndBracket@@ 2013, and he instead advised to try and close lines. }
11... f5 12. exf6
{ Simple chess, opening lines and still hoping to attack with Qh5. } 12... Nxf6
13. c4
{ A change of approach, but also a strong advance to increase the pressure. Now any ...dxc4?; Nxc4 exchange will leave Black with an isolated e-pawn and especially a big hole on e5. Meanwhile White has spied another good post for the queen, c2. }
13... Bb7 14. Qc2 h6 15. Rad1
{ A fine, harmonious set-up for White, in contrast to which Black's position is riddled with holes, most notably on e5 and g6. As such, unsurprisingly Nf3-e5 will but ratchet up further the pressure on Black, who must also watch out that his light squares don't collapse after a timely f4-f5 strike. }
