{ The natural square to develop the bishop, which will very often prove White's most effective attacker. }
4... c5 5. b3 { Preparing the fianchetto of the dark-squared Colle bishop. }
5... Nc6 6. Bb2 Be7
{ Black gets on with the process of completing kingside development. } 7. O-O
{ Following our standard approach: deploy the bishops to fine squares, house the king and only then, usually, look to involve the knights with Nbd2 and Ne5. }
7... O-O
{ Black usually follows suit. Once again,  7...Nb4  is nothing to fear due to  8.Be2  ,  and if  8...cxd4  9.exd4  Qc7  10.a3!  ,  as we saw inthis line in Chapter 1. }
8. Nbd2
{ Sensibly continuing development and now  8...cxd4  9.exd4  would, of course, take play back into the realm ofChapter 1 }
8... b6
{ By some margin Black's main move and we should now be on the look-out after ... Bb7 for his trying to time an exchange of knights on e5 followed by going ... Ne4. }
9. Ne5
{ The direct approach. Yet again, we want to go f2-f4 then attack. Instead,  9.Qe2?!  Nb4  is not recommended.   But if you don't mind a slower, manoeuvring approach,  9.a3  Bb7  10.Qe2  is far from a terrible alternative and has been used by Mamedyarov. }
9... Qc7 10. a3
{ We hope that by now the warning symbol flashed in your brain upon seeing the early ...Qc7 and so you took control of b4, while avoiding  10.f4?!  Nb4!  Only now that has been ruled out does White want to expand on the kingside. }
10... Bb7 11. f4
{ While Black's position is fairly solid, it's telling that White has scored just over 70% from here. Many club players simply don't like being attacked on the kingside. As White we should just remember to be looking to lift the king's rook here; the queen will be safe and active enough for now on e2. Indeed, with the b7-bishop protected by the black queen, Qf3 ideas would be most unwise. }
11... a5 12. Qe2
{ 12.Qf3??  c4!!  This is a vicious trap to remember - and avoid! Black will either win material with ...c3 or a discovered attack on the white queen:  13.bxc4  dxc4  14.Nexc4  b5  There's just nowhere good for the knight to go. }
12... a4 13. Rac1
{ The rook takes up position on the same file as the black queen. White might even now force ...axb3; cxb3 with Bb5 or even consider a radical idea on the other flank: g4-g5, as well as just Rf3-h3.  13.Rf3?!  This can't really be recommended due to an exchange on e5 then ...Ne4, but it did lead to a rapid massacre in a game between two strong Russian Grandmasters:  13...Ne4?  14.dxc5!  Nxe5  15.Bxe5  Qxc5  16.Rh3!  g6??  17.Nxe4!  dxe4  18.Qh5!!  And Black was forced to resign in Rakhmanov-Ponkratov, Sochi @@StartBracket@@rapid@@EndBracket@@ 2016. Talk about the power of the Zukertort bishop! }
