5... Nc6 6. Bb2 Be7
{ Black gets on with the process of completing kingside development. } 7. O-O
{ Following our standard approach: deploy the bishops to fine squares, house the king and only then, usually, look to involve the knights with Nbd2 and Ne5. }
7... O-O
{ Black usually follows suit. Once again,  7...Nb4  is nothing to fear due to  8.Be2  ,  and if  8...cxd4  9.exd4  Qc7  10.a3!  ,  as we saw inthis line in Chapter 1. }
8. Nbd2
{ Sensibly continuing development and now  8...cxd4  9.exd4  would, of course, take play back into the realm ofChapter 1 }
8... b6
{ By some margin Black's main move and we should now be on the look-out after ... Bb7 for his trying to time an exchange of knights on e5 followed by going ... Ne4. }
9. Ne5
{ The direct approach. Yet again, we want to go f2-f4 then attack. Instead,  9.Qe2?!  Nb4  is not recommended.   But if you don't mind a slower, manoeuvring approach,  9.a3  Bb7  10.Qe2  is far from a terrible alternative and has been used by Mamedyarov. }
9... Bb7 { Black usually follows up by completing the fianchetto so. } 10. f4
{ Our favourite follow-up to landing the knight on e5. It also avoids allowing Black fairly easy equality with  10.a3   10.Qf3?!  Nb4  would clearly not be wise.  10...Nxe5!  11.dxe5  Ne4  Only now that he can recapture with the f-pawn will White consider keeping Black out of b4 with a2-a3. }
10... Nxe5 11. fxe5
{ One of the main points behind our set-up. White will now gain a very strong attack if the knight retreats and is well placed to remove it should it instead advance: }
11... Ne4 12. Nxe4
{ Simple chess, retaining the bishop. White has much more often gone  12.Bxe4  dxe4  13.Qg4  ,  but after the simplifying  13...Rc8!  14.c4  cxd4  15.Bxd4  Bc5!  Black should be able to equalise. }
12... dxe4 13. Bc4
{ White may now expand with a2-a4 and very much still has ideas of Qg4, which might even threaten Rxf7 if Black is careless, while also facilitating Rad1.  Black is quite solid and equal in the eyes of the engines, but White's extra space means his game is the easier to play and, indeed, he's scored 71% from here in over-the-board and correspondence practice.  13...Bg5!?  14.Qe2  a6  15.a4  White first sensibly keeps control.  15...Bh6?!  16.Rad1  Then he centralises and enjoyed a very pleasant advantage in Gelfand-Veremeichik, Belarus 1983.   There are two key ideas to be aware of here, on top of the threat of dxc5. Firstly, d4-d5 exd5; Bxd5 Bxd5; Rxd5, which might lead to the e4-pawn falling after Qg4 and this could be a reality whether Black's bishop is on h6 or g7. Secondly, here, installing a rook on d6.   If we imagine White one day getting in exd6 after a trade of rooks there, then the bishop on b2 would be a monster.  16...cxd4  17.Bxd4!  Threatening Bc5 and much stronger than the young Gelfand's 17. exd4.  17...Qc7  18.h4!  White's bishops are most powerful, giving full control of the board and the simple and strong idea now is g2-g4-g5, either trapping Black's bishop or forcing him to weaken with ...g6, after which a combination of Rf6 and h4-h5 should leave White with very heavy pressure indeed against the black king. }
