{ Naturally we preserve a key bishop and now 12. a3 and 13. Bd3 will follow unless Black reacts. }
11... cxd4 12. exd4 Ne4 13. c3
{ Driving the knight back from b4 while overprotecting d4. } 13... Nc6 14. Nxe4
dxe4 15. Ng4
{ While Black is very solid here, we quite like White's position which bristles with potential, as well as the better structure, Tienhoven-Simal Moreira, correspondence 2018. The knight will take up a perfect blockading role on e3, after which White might both look to play on the kingside @@StartBracket@@Qe1-g3 and, if allowed, f4-f5@@EndBracket@@, as well as expand in the centre with  Rad1  and c3-c4, thereby turning the bishop on b2 into a fire-breathing prelate once again!  In case you're wondering why we preferred @@StartFEN@@r2q1rk1/pb2bppp/1p2p3/3pN3/1n1PnP2/1P6/PBPNB1PP/R2Q1RK1 w - - 1 13@@EndFEN@@  13.c3!?  to  @@StartFEN@@r2q1rk1/pb2bppp/1p2p3/3pN3/1n1PnP2/1P6/PBPNB1PP/R2Q1RK1 w - - 1 13@@EndFEN@@  13.a3  take a look at a plausible continuation: }
15... f5 16. Ne3 Bf6 17. Bc4
{ Here the d-pawn isn't attacked, so White could also consider  17.g4!?  but it's simpler and probably even better to attack e6 while offering further support to a central breakthrough: }
17... Qd7 18. d5 exd5 19. Nxd5
{ Suddenly Black is in huge trouble as White will invade on the seventh: }
19... Kh8 20. Nxf6 Qxd1 21. Raxd1 Rxf6 22. Rd7
{ Surely White's attack will crash through after Bf7 and c3-c4, not to mention Rfd1 if needed? }
