[White "2) ...Nc6 / …Be7 Setup without …cxd4"]
[Black "...Nc6 / ...Be7 Setup: 7...O-O / 9...Bb7 #5"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Nf3
{ With this move, White prepares to enter the Colle setup, and remains flexible with the c-pawn, contrary to the Queen's Gambit. The extra control over e5 rules out lines such as the Albin Countergambit. }
2... Nf6 3. e3 e6 4. Bd3
{ The natural square to develop the bishop, which will very often prove White's most effective attacker. }
4... c5 5. b3 { Preparing the fianchetto of the dark-squared Colle bishop. }
5... Nc6 6. Bb2 Be7
{ Black gets on with the process of completing kingside development. } 7. O-O
{ Following our standard approach: deploy the bishops to fine squares, house the king and only then, usually, look to involve the knights with Nbd2 and Ne5. }
7... O-O
{ Black usually follows suit. Once again,  7...Nb4  is nothing to fear due to  8.Be2  ,  and if  8...cxd4  9.exd4  Qc7  10.a3!  ,  as we saw inthis line in Chapter 1. }
8. Nbd2
{ Sensibly continuing development and now  8...cxd4  9.exd4  would, of course, take play back into the realm ofChapter 1 }
8... b6
{ By some margin Black's main move and we should now be on the look-out after ... Bb7 for his trying to time an exchange of knights on e5 followed by going ... Ne4. }
9. Ne5
{ The direct approach. Yet again, we want to go f2-f4 then attack. Instead,  9.Qe2?!  Nb4  is not recommended.   But if you don't mind a slower, manoeuvring approach,  9.a3  Bb7  10.Qe2  is far from a terrible alternative and has been used by Mamedyarov. }
9... Bb7 { Black usually follows up by completing the fianchetto so. } 10. f4
{ Our favourite follow-up to landing the knight on e5. It also avoids allowing Black fairly easy equality with  10.a3   10.Qf3?!  Nb4  would clearly not be wise.  10...Nxe5!  11.dxe5  Ne4  Only now that he can recapture with the f-pawn will White consider keeping Black out of b4 with a2-a3. }
10... Rc8
{ Black's most common choice, preparing to strike against d3 and c2. } 11. a3
{ Prudently keeping Black out of b4 and the bishop on d3 free from harassment. Black has now tried a great many moves in practice, but, in short, you won't go too far wrong if you can get in Qe2 and Rf3-h3, beginning an attack. Note that while Qf3 instead may also look tempting, it can all too easily walk into a powerful, hidden blow with ...c4. }
11... Nxe5 12. dxe5
{ Not our usual recapture, but here taking back in the manner we became accustomed to inChapter 1 makes good sense, in part because White lacks a great option after  12.fxe5  Ne4  . }
12... Ne4 13. Nxe4 dxe4 14. Bc4
{ Simple chess as White preserves slightly the more active bishops. If allowed, he will now whip up an sudden attack with Qg4 and f4-f5, so Black would be well advised to exchange the queens: }
14... Qxd1 15. Raxd1
{ Simplification has occurred and Black is unlikely to get mated, but White should not be unhappy and holds a definite edge, with f4-f5 likely to prove the key breakthrough.  15...Rcd8!  16.g4!?  An attempt to maintain the tension and avoid the further simplification which 16. f5 could well lead to.  16...Rxd1  17.Rxd1  Rd8  18.Rf1!  Rd2  19.Rc1  White has lost time with his rook and conceded the open file, but retains an edge.   Why? Quite simply, f4-f5 is the main pawn break in the position, a3-a4 may also prove a useful advance, White's king can easily head for e2 or stroll up to g3, and Black's rook won't look so active once 20. Bc3 has driven it backwards.   15...Rfd8?!  16.f5!  exf5  17.e6!  Black was already in serious trouble here in Haeusler-Pollina, correspondence 2001, with exf7+ a major threat and unable to keep lines closed:  17...f6  18.Rd7  Black is losing significant material. }
