1. d4 d5 2. Nf3
{ With this move, White prepares to enter the Colle setup, and remains flexible with the c-pawn, contrary to the Queen's Gambit. The extra control over e5 rules out lines such as the Albin Countergambit. }
2... Nf6 3. e3 e6 4. Bd3
{ The natural square to develop the bishop, which will very often prove White's most effective attacker. }
4... c5 5. b3 { Preparing the fianchetto of the dark-squared Colle bishop. }
5... Nc6 6. Bb2
{ While set-ups with ...Be7 are fairly common at all levels, not least in club and weekend tournament chess, Black's most popular set-up according to ChessBase's vast main database has been a set-up combining ...Nc6 with ...Bd6, which we'll now move on to. Once again, White should be looking to complete development with O-O and Nbd2, and then to invade e5. With Black's dark-squared bishop back on e7, he could often consider a ...Nxe5 exchange, but with the bishop on d6 that would, of course, be a major blunder.  Specifically we'll discuss:  Chapter 3:  6...cxd4  7.exd4  Bd6   Chapter 4:  6...Bd6 }
