[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "3) ...Nc6 / …Bd6 Setup with ...cxd4"]
[Black "...Nc6 / ...Bd6 / ...cxd4 Setup: 8...Ne4 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Nf3
{ With this move, White prepares to enter the Colle setup, and remains flexible with the c-pawn, contrary to the Queen's Gambit. The extra control over e5 rules out lines such as the Albin Countergambit. }
2... Nf6 3. e3 e6 4. Bd3
{ The natural square to develop the bishop, which will very often prove White's most effective attacker. }
4... c5 5. b3 { Preparing the fianchetto of the dark-squared Colle bishop. }
5... Nc6 6. Bb2
{ Completing White's ideal bishop set-up. Let's see what happens if Black fears ideas of dxc5 and so elects to exchange on d4 before going ...Be7. Such an idea was traditionally criticised, as now going Qe2 or Re1 will support a Ne5 advance while keeping Black out of e4, but the latest engines don't seem to mind it for Black. }
6... cxd4 { Relieving the central tension is very typical at this moment. } 7.
exd4
{ Needless to say, we recapture with the pawn and so maintain maximum control of the key e5-square. }
7... Bd6
{ The most critical placement of the bishop for Black - supporting an eventual ...e5 push. }
8. O-O
{ Continuing our favourite pattern of development and now Black usually follows suit and houses the king too. }
8... Ne4 9. c4
{ A good response to Black's attempt to beat us to the central bounce as it were. White seizes space and can now challenge the intruder on e4 with Nc3. Note too that we very much welcome any attempt Black now makes to support his knight, Stonewall style, with the weakening ...f5. }
9... O-O 10. Nc3
{ Putting pressure on Black's center by developing the knight to its most natural square, now that c4 has been played. }
10... f5 11. cxd5
{ A good moment to exchange. Now if Black recaptures, White will simply swipe the pawn on d5 and go a pawn to the good. As you've probably spotted, there is a desperado then on h2, but that would be a terrible blunder: White has Bc4 at the end. As such, Black must exchange on c3 to avoid being a clear pawn down: }
11... Nxc3 12. Bxc3 exd5 13. Re1
{ White has a pleasant edge, with Black suffering from the hole on e5. White shouldn't rush to occupy that, but should aim to improve the pieces, with one simple plan that of a2-a3, b3-b4 and Qb3. If Black is careless, keep an eye out for a potential Ng5 raid, while if Black tries ...f4 and ...Bg4 then simply Be2 is likely to be a good response, since any future exchange of light-squared bishops will but leave d5, e6 and possibly even h7 more vulnerable. }
