10... a6 11. c5
{ Seizing space. White will now begin to take control of e5 with Re1, has the plan of expansion with a2-a3 and b3-b4, and might even cause problems with Na4-b6. }
11... Bf4 12. Re1
{ Maintaining full control by preventing Black from breaking out with ...e5. Now a2-a3 and b3-b4 may well follow, quite possibly teamed up with g2-g3 and a timely Ne5. And, yes, Black cannot break free here:  12...e5?  13.dxe5  Nxe5  14.Nxe5  Bxe5  15.Nxd5!  A powerful temporary Sacrifice. Clearly Nxc7 and Bxe5 are big threats and Black cannot avoid landing in huge trouble even if he makes the obvious captures:  15...Bxh2+  16.Kh1  Nxd5  17.Qh5  With a certain threat and just look at how White's mighty bishops rake the vulnerable Black kingside.  17...h6  18.Qxd5  There just isn't a good move here for Black, since  18...Qf4  fails to  19.Be5  and meanwhile Qe4 and/or Qd4 will force a very serious gash in the kingside.   For example,  18...Bf4  19.Qe4  f5  20.Qe7  Thanks to the possibility of Bc4@@StartBracket@@+@@EndBracket@@, the invasion of the seventh proves devastating, with Bxg7 one threat and Qxc7 Bxc7; Re7 an even bigger one. }
