9... Re8 10. Ne5
{ Immediately, but Black's last was a little slow and White, who might continue with a2-a3 and f2-f4 or just Qe2 and Ndf3, is also hoping to provoke Black into challenging the strong knight on e5: }
10... Nd7 11. Bxh7+
{ Boom! The classic Greek Gift sacrifice lands, if in a slightly unusual form. }
11... Kxh7 12. Nxf7
{ Much stronger than the 12.Qh5+? of Yusupov-Sanz Wawer, Warsaw @@StartBracket@@rapid@@EndBracket@@ 2013, tempting though that is. Instead, White keeps the check in reserve and simply wants to take on d6, having spot that the rook on e8 is potentially loose. Indeed,  12...Qe7  13.Nxd6  would be pretty disastrous for Black followed by Ba3 or  13...Qxd6?  14.Qh5+  and even the counter sacrifice doesn't especially help him: }
12... Bxh2+ 13. Kxh2 Qh4+ 14. Kg1
{ White is simply a pawn up and set to go Nf3-g5@@StartBracket@@+@@EndBracket@@, with Nd6 another useful move which might come with tempo. }
