{ This doesn't have to be played just yet, but is a good choice, ruling out ...Nb4 ideas for good, while intending to begin to expand with Ne5. }
10... Bb7 11. Ne5
{ Just as in inthis line in Chapter 1, it's also possible to first go  11.Qe2  ,  but unlike there, White need not fear an exchange of knights on e5 here, which would either cost Black a piece or the bishop-pair and a potentially vulnerable kingside. }
11... Bxe5 12. dxe5 Nd7 13. Qh5
{ Not a bad first move by the queen! Black's dark squares would now be extremely vulnerable after  13...g6?  14.Qh6!  when the e5-pawn is taboo due to f2-f4 ideas. However, even the alternative isn't too ideal for Black: }
13... h6 14. b4
{ Richard's idea from 'Starting Out: d-pawn Attacks' is yet to receive a test, but still seems pretty strong. White rules out ...Nc5, thereby keeping Black cramped. The simple and strong plan is f2-f4, Rf3 and Rg3, and Black can't even force the queens off: }
14... Qg5 15. Qe2
{ Now f2-f4 will come with tempo and, of course, the e5-pawn is taboo. } *

