{ Needless to say, we recapture with the pawn and so maintain maximum control of the key e5-square. }
7... Bd6
{ The most critical placement of the bishop for Black - supporting an eventual ...e5 push. }
8. O-O
{ Continuing our favourite pattern of development and now Black usually follows suit and houses the king too. }
8... O-O 9. Nbd2
{ Continuing our favourite pattern of development and once again refusing to fear  9...Nb4  ,  since after  10.Be2  the bishop will be quick to return to d3 following a2-a3 @@StartBracket@@or even c2-c3@@EndBracket@@. If Black now does something slow, White may well rule out any annoying ...Nb4 notion with 10. a3 and then expand with Ne5, whether before or after Qe2. }
9... b6 10. a3
{ This doesn't have to be played just yet, but is a good choice, ruling out ...Nb4 ideas for good, while intending to begin to expand with Ne5. }
10... Bb7 11. Ne5
{ Just as in inthis line in Chapter 1, it's also possible to first go  11.Qe2  ,  but unlike there, White need not fear an exchange of knights on e5 here, which would either cost Black a piece or the bishop-pair and a potentially vulnerable kingside. }
11... Rc8 12. Qe2
{ Consistent with our approach against 11...Qc7. White simply supports the knight on e5, while holding back on f2-f4 for a move. Only next does White want to go f2-f4, possibly followed by Rf3-h3, and note too that now  12...Ne7  transposes to a position we'll see via  @@StartFEN@@r2q1rk1/pb3ppp/1pnbpn2/3pN3/3P4/PP1B4/1BPN1PPP/R2Q1RK1 b - - 2 11@@EndFEN@@  11...Ne7  12.Qe2  Rc8  ,   while  12...Qc7  would be the same as the  @@StartFEN@@r2q1rk1/pb3ppp/1pnbpn2/3pN3/3P4/PP1B4/1BPN1PPP/R2Q1RK1 b - - 2 11@@EndFEN@@  11...Qc7  12.Qe2  Rc8  move order. }
12... Nd7 13. f4
{ Consistent. Now Rf3-h3 is very much on the cards, attacking h7, while also freeing f1 for the other rook. Note too that thanks to the queen being on e2, Black can't really touch his f-pawn: }
13... f6 14. Nxc6 Rxc6 15. Qxe6+
{ White is already much more than just a pawn up, since Qh3 @@StartBracket@@or  15...Rf7  16.Bxh7+!  @@EndBracket@@ will force further major weaknesses. }
