{ This doesn't have to be played just yet, but is a good choice, ruling out ...Nb4 ideas for good, while intending to begin to expand with Ne5. }
10... Bb7 11. Ne5
{ Just as in inthis line in Chapter 1, it's also possible to first go  11.Qe2  ,  but unlike there, White need not fear an exchange of knights on e5 here, which would either cost Black a piece or the bishop-pair and a potentially vulnerable kingside. }
11... Rc8 12. Qe2
{ Consistent with our approach against 11...Qc7. White simply supports the knight on e5, while holding back on f2-f4 for a move. Only next does White want to go f2-f4, possibly followed by Rf3-h3, and note too that now  12...Ne7  transposes to a position we'll see via  @@StartFEN@@r2q1rk1/pb3ppp/1pnbpn2/3pN3/3P4/PP1B4/1BPN1PPP/R2Q1RK1 b - - 2 11@@EndFEN@@  11...Ne7  12.Qe2  Rc8  ,   while  12...Qc7  would be the same as the  @@StartFEN@@r2q1rk1/pb3ppp/1pnbpn2/3pN3/3P4/PP1B4/1BPN1PPP/R2Q1RK1 b - - 2 11@@EndFEN@@  11...Qc7  12.Qe2  Rc8  move order. }
12... Qe7 13. f4
{ Consistent as the rook lift is prepared and note too how useful our pawn on a3 is for helping to keep Black's pieces bottled up. }
13... Rfe8 14. Rf3
{ Continuing the simple and strong plan. White simply wants to increase the pressure on the kingside with Rh3 and Bxh7+ if allowed, with Ndf3-g5 and g2-g4 also potentially useful attacking moves.  14...Qf8?!  15.Rh3  g6  16.g4!  A bold advance, but one which is fully justified here as Black is rather low on counterplay.   White simply wants to target the knight on f6 with g4-f5, and if ...Nh5 then Rxh5 gxh5; Qxh5 will be a very strong exchange sacrifice to rip open lines, with Ng4/d7-f6+ then very much in the offing.  16...Qg7  17.Rf1!  With Black having overprotected h7, the exchange sacrifice is no longer quite so promising, so White calmly builds up and improves his worst-placed piece.  17...Ne7  18.Rf2  We've followed the classic Colle-Zukertort game Maroczy-Blake, Hastings 1923/24, where White was doing pretty well.   His crafty plan was to place the rook opposite the black queen with Rg2 and then to target f7 and h7 with Nd2-f3-g5. }
