Rc7 14. Rae1
{ White takes further control of e4. Now Rf3-h3 is one idea, g2-g4 another and c2-c3 may also prove useful, not least in the event of  14...Qa8  @@StartBracket@@preparing ...Ne4@@EndBracket@@  15.c3  ,  after which White may expand not just on the kingside, but also with b3-b4 and a3-a4. }
14... Ne8 15. g4
{ White displays no fear and encourages Black to carry out his 'threat'. }
15... f6 16. Rf3
{ This is why. Clearly if Black exchanges on e5 then  16...fxe5?!  17.fxe5  will see White regaining his piece with interest as the bishop on d6 doesn't have a good square, and White was now ready to go Rh3 in Sunye Neto-Ljubojevic, Brasilia 1981. Let's see what might happen if Black tries to free a retreat square for his bishop on d6: }
16... g6 17. Rh3 Rc8 18. Ndf3
{ This knight as the black king really begins to feel the heat. White is now ready to go Qf2-h4 or even Qe3, f4-f5 and Qh6. }
18... fxe5 19. fxe5 Bb8 20. Ng5
{ Black might be a piece up, but is quite simply lost as there's just no good way to defend h7, with Rxh7 @@StartBracket@@Nxh7 also would be far from shabby@@EndBracket@@ followed by Qe3-h3 one simple and very strong threat. }
