{ White was initially a little outplayed before eventually triumphing after  14.Rf3  in Bruzon Bautista-Anand, Leon @@StartBracket@@rapid@@EndBracket@@ 2006, but we prefer to prophylactically cover c2, thereby threatening just to nab a pawn with Bxb5.   Black is also unlikely to be helped by  14...b4  15.axb4  Bxb4  16.c3  ,  so should probably just defend b5. }
14... a6 15. Rf3
{ Only now, with Black held up on the queenside for the time being, does White begin to lift the rook. While Black's position is fairly solid, White's set-up looks the easier and more fun side to be. The immediate idea is Rh3 when Bxh7+! will be a threat, with both Nd2-f3-g5 and g2-g4-g5 two other ways to increase the pressure on the kingside. }
