[Round "?"]
[White "4) ...Nc6 /  …Bd6 Setup without ...cxd4"]
[Black "...Nc6 / ...Bd6 Setup: 8...Qe7 #10"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Nf3
{ With this move, White prepares to enter the Colle setup, and remains flexible with the c-pawn, contrary to the Queen's Gambit. The extra control over e5 rules out lines such as the Albin Countergambit. }
2... Nf6 3. e3 e6 4. Bd3
{ The natural square to develop the bishop, which will very often prove White's most effective attacker. }
4... c5 5. b3 { Preparing the fianchetto of the dark-squared Colle bishop. }
5... Nc6 6. Bb2 Bd6
{ Developing the bishop to it's most active square without releasing the central tension will be the topic of this chapter. }
7. O-O
{ Now  7...cxd4  8.exd4  would, of course, take play back into the realm ofChapter 3, but many strong opponents won't hurry to release the tension. }
7... O-O
{ 7...Qc7?!  This has attracted the attention of a few players strong enough to know better and is an ambitious move White welcomes for the same reason as in avariation like this in Chapter 2.  8.dxc5!?  Bxc5  9.Nbd2  With c2-c4 on the agenda, as well as a timely Bxf6, White has a pleasant edge as we saw. }
8. Nbd2
{ Consistent development and also best. Note that  8.Ne5?!  would be premature:  8...cxd4  9.exd4  Qc7  . Black threatens both ...Nb4 and to take on e5, to which White lacks a great response and is definitely not for choice.   After  8.Nbd2  we're in the heart of the main line and will, as such, have one further divide:   A.  8...Qe7    B. or  @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/pp3ppp/2nbpn2/2pp4/3P4/1P1BPN2/PBPN1PPP/R2Q1RK1 b - - 6 8@@EndFEN@@  8...b6  Those are Black's two most common moves, with   C.  @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/pp3ppp/2nbpn2/2pp4/3P4/1P1BPN2/PBPN1PPP/R2Q1RK1 b - - 6 8@@EndFEN@@  8...cxd4  9.exd4  and a transposition toChapter 3 in third place.   Instead, any slow moves can be dealt with through our favourite plan of expansion, i.e. Ne5 and f2-f4, while we'll now see why c7 isn't as good a square for the black queen as e7.   D. Indeed,  8...Qc7?!  9.dxc5  Bxc5  10.c4  leaves Black under pressure as we saw back via a  @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pp3ppp/2n1pn2/2pp4/3P4/1P1BPN2/PBP2PPP/RN1QK2R b KQkq - 2 6@@EndFEN@@  6...Be7  7.O-O  Qc7?!  8.dxc5  Bxc5  9.Nbd2  O-O  10.c4  move order inhere }
8... Qe7 { Attempting to break through with ...e5. } 9. a3
{ A sneaky little move, not only failing to prevent 9...e5, but even encouraging the break! Another decent choice here is Simon's old preference for  9.dxc5  Bxc5  10.c4   But what's wrong with @@StartFEN@@r1b2rk1/pp2qppp/2nbpn2/2pp4/3P4/1P1BPN2/PBPN1PPP/R2Q1RK1 w - - 7 9@@EndFEN@@  9.Ne5  we hear you ask? The problem isn't the old main line,  9...cxd4  10.exd4  Ba3  @@StartBracket@@we saw how play might then pan out in our introductory section,The Kingside Attack, featuring Hoi-Danielsen, Danish Championship, Ringsted 1995@@EndBracket@@  (, but rather the cunning, modern)  @@StartFEN@@r1b2rk1/pp2qppp/2nbpn2/2ppN3/3P4/1P1BP3/PBPN1PPP/R2Q1RK1 b - - 8 9@@EndFEN@@  9...Qc7!?   or @@StartFEN@@r1b2rk1/pp2qppp/2nbpn2/2ppN3/3P4/1P1BP3/PBPN1PPP/R2Q1RK1 b - - 8 9@@EndFEN@@  9...cxd4  10.exd4  Qc7   After ...Qc7, Black is losing a whole tempo with the queen, but is able to equalise fairly easily as there just isn't a great way for White to deal with the twin threats to his knight on e5 and of 10...cxd4 11. exd4 Nb4.   David Rudel made a decent case for  10.f4  cxd4  11.exd4  Nb4  12.Rf3!?  Nxd3  13.cxd3  in his book 'Zuke 'Em', but while Black is forced to defend, modern engines show that he is doing pretty well, especially after  13...Ne8  .   Rather than burn our bridges so, with 9. a3 we cut out any ideas of ...Nb4 and are now ready to expand after all with Ne5 and f2-f4 unless Black reacts in the centre. }
9... e5 { Taking up the challenge so must be critical. } 10. dxc5
{ An essential exchange as we play to break up Black's imposing-looking centre. }
10... Bxc5 11. b4
{ And this is an important follow-up as we begin to force the pace. This position has scarcely been tested yet over the board, but has received a bit of correspondence testing. Now, of course,  11...e4?  12.bxc5  would leave Black without a great capture and set to suffer from structural damage, as after  12...exd3  13.cxd3  Qxc5  14.Bxf6  gxf6  15.Nh4!?  The difference in king safety is stark. }
11... Bd6 12. c4
{ This powerful break, underpinned by some fairly simple tactics, first attracted Richard to the idea of 9.a3!? a few years ago. White simply wants to exchange with @@StartFEN@@r1b2rk1/pp2qppp/2nb1n2/3pp3/1PP5/P2BPN2/1B1N1PPP/R2Q1RK1 w - - 0 12@@EndFEN@@  13.cxd5  Nxd5  and then begin to expand with  14.Bc4  and/or Ne4. }
12... e4 13. Bxf6
{ The point behind White's play. We are definitely not losing a piece, but are breaking up Black's centre while seizing the upper hand! }
13... gxf6 14. cxd5 { The forcing moves continue. } 14... exd3 15. dxc6 bxc6
16. Nd4
{ This looks like a strong manoeuvre. The pawn on d3 is weak, but there's no rush to try and surround it. Instead, White eyes c6 @@StartBracket@@Rac1 may well follow@@EndBracket@@, as well as the hole on f5. The immediate idea is Qf3 or if  16...Qe5  17.N2f3  and Rc1, and meanwhile it's not totally impossible Black could blunder: }
16... Bb7 17. Nf5
{ The twin threats to the queen and of mate force resignation. } *

