Nxe4
{ Now Black must desperado his bishop or he'll just be two pawns down after Nxd6  @@StartBracket@@  15...Qg6?  16.Nxd6  Bh3  17.Ne1  more than defends followed by c4-c5 and maybe Qf3@@EndBracket@@. }
15... Bxh2+ 16. Nxh2 Qg6 17. Ng3
{ Simple chess. White is a pawn up and clearly better. Indeed, he has twice gone on to win from here, in Brousek-Jarabinsky, correspondence 2004, and Breivik-Aleksic, Paracin 2015. White may activate the queen via f3 and f4  @@StartBracket@@or h5@@EndBracket@@, with c4-c5 also likely to prove a very useful move, securing a long-term outpost on d6. }
