10... a6 11. f4
{ There's no reason not to expand so and the knight on e5 is now overprotected, a handy feature which ensures White will definitely have a decent option if Black now continues his queenside expansion, as Nimzowitsch no less once did: }
11... b5 12. dxc5 Bxc5 13. Qe1
{ We prefer this slightly sneaky queen move to the  13.Qf3  of Van Vliet-Nimzowitsch, Ostend 1907, when Black might have made a decent positional pawn sacrifice with  13...Nxe5  14.fxe5  Ne4!  . Now White is all set to attack with Rf3-h3 and Qh4, and also has options if Black does still elect to change the central situation: }
13... Nxe5 14. fxe5 Ne4 15. b4 Bb6 16. Bd4
{ This is why White was happy to voluntarily accept doubled e-pawns. If Black exchanges on d4, the pawns will, of course, be undoubled and in any case White has an edge. One good positional plan is that of Nb3 followed, if allowed by Bxe4 dxe4; Rd1; another, the more direct Rf3-h3. }
