{ Just as inChapter 3, this advance makes a lot of sense, ruling out ...Nb4 for good before cementing the knight in place with f2-f4 and now  10...Qe7  11.f4  would take us back to a position we saw via a  @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/pp3ppp/2nbpn2/2pp4/3P4/1P1BPN2/PBPN1PPP/R2Q1RK1 b - - 6 8@@EndFEN@@  8...Qe7  9.a3  b6  10.Ne5  Bb7  11.f4  move order.   We should note too that here  10...cxd4  11.exd4  would basically transpose to the main line ofChapter 3, something which has happened fairly often, although here Black's main moves are to involve his queen's rook and to immediately begin to reroute the knight from c6. }
10... a5 11. f4
{ White is consistent and we now saw  11...Ne7  12.Rf3  cxd4  13.Bxd4  back in one of our introductory games, Vaganian-Adams. What happens though if Black instead continues the queenside advance? }
11... a4 12. Qf3
{ Richard's idea from 'Starting Out: d-pawn Attacks'. The queen simply wants to sidle over to h3: }
12... axb3 13. cxb3 Qe7
{ 13...cxd4  is also possible when after  14.exd4  the position could do with a test.   Black is fairly solid, but note how White has control of not just e4, but also all the entry squares down the c-file, meaning that he may well be able to continue with b3-b4 and Rae1. Then Qh3 may well be particularly strong and don't forget that there's always the g-pawn to hurl into the attack if the need arises. }
14. Qh3
{ White's clear target is the knight on f6 and Black must be quite careful. Indeed, the a3-pawn is taboo as shown by Richard's 2008 analysis: }
14... cxd4 15. exd4 Bxa3 16. Bxa3 Rxa3 17. Rxa3 Qxa3 18. Nd7
{ Black can save the exchange, but not also h7 and is clearly in some trouble. }
18... Rc8 19. Nxf6+ gxf6 20. Nf3
{ Stronger than taking on h7. Now d4 is secure and White simply wants to blast open yet more lines with f4-f5. We have to agree with the engines that White has superb compensation and attacking chances. }
