1. d4 d5 2. Nf3
{ With this move, White prepares to enter the Colle setup, and remains flexible with the c-pawn, contrary to the Queen's Gambit. The extra control over e5 rules out lines such as the Albin Countergambit. }
2... Nf6 3. e3 e6 4. Bd3
{ The natural square to develop the bishop, which will very often prove White's most effective attacker. }
4... c5 5. b3 { Preparing the fianchetto of the dark-squared Colle bishop. }
5... Nc6 6. Bb2 Bd6
{ Developing the bishop to it's most active square without releasing the central tension will be the topic of this chapter. }
7. O-O
{ Now  7...cxd4  8.exd4  would, of course, take play back into the realm ofChapter 3, but many strong opponents won't hurry to release the tension. }
7... O-O
{ 7...Qc7?!  This has attracted the attention of a few players strong enough to know better and is an ambitious move White welcomes for the same reason as in avariation like this in Chapter 2.  8.dxc5!?  Bxc5  9.Nbd2  With c2-c4 on the agenda, as well as a timely Bxf6, White has a pleasant edge as we saw. }
8. Nbd2
{ Consistent development and also best. Note that  8.Ne5?!  would be premature:  8...cxd4  9.exd4  Qc7  . Black threatens both ...Nb4 and to take on e5, to which White lacks a great response and is definitely not for choice.   After  8.Nbd2  we're in the heart of the main line and will, as such, have one further divide:   A.  8...Qe7    B. or  @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/pp3ppp/2nbpn2/2pp4/3P4/1P1BPN2/PBPN1PPP/R2Q1RK1 b - - 6 8@@EndFEN@@  8...b6  Those are Black's two most common moves, with   C.  @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/pp3ppp/2nbpn2/2pp4/3P4/1P1BPN2/PBPN1PPP/R2Q1RK1 b - - 6 8@@EndFEN@@  8...cxd4  9.exd4  and a transposition toChapter 3 in third place.   Instead, any slow moves can be dealt with through our favourite plan of expansion, i.e. Ne5 and f2-f4, while we'll now see why c7 isn't as good a square for the black queen as e7.   D. Indeed,  8...Qc7?!  9.dxc5  Bxc5  10.c4  leaves Black under pressure as we saw back via a  @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pp3ppp/2n1pn2/2pp4/3P4/1P1BPN2/PBP2PPP/RN1QK2R b KQkq - 2 6@@EndFEN@@  6...Be7  7.O-O  Qc7?!  8.dxc5  Bxc5  9.Nbd2  O-O  10.c4  move order inhere }
8... b6 9. Ne5
{ Invading in our favourite fashion without delay. Now the scene is set for a2-a3 followed by f2-f4 and there's no need to fear  9...Nb4  10.Be2  .   That said, it's also possible to begin with  9.a3  if you prefer and even the virtually unknown  9.e4!?  is worth a thought if you like to be independent, an advance based around the key point  9...cxd4?  10.Bb5!  . }
9... Bb7 { Consistent. } 10. a3
{ Just as inChapter 3, this advance makes a lot of sense, ruling out ...Nb4 for good before cementing the knight in place with f2-f4 and now  10...Qe7  11.f4  would take us back to a position we saw via a  @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/pp3ppp/2nbpn2/2pp4/3P4/1P1BPN2/PBPN1PPP/R2Q1RK1 b - - 6 8@@EndFEN@@  8...Qe7  9.a3  b6  10.Ne5  Bb7  11.f4  move order.   We should note too that here  10...cxd4  11.exd4  would basically transpose to the main line ofChapter 3, something which has happened fairly often, although here Black's main moves are to involve his queen's rook and to immediately begin to reroute the knight from c6. }
10... Ne7 11. Qe2
{ Against Black's solid and sensible knight regrouping, White calmly completes development. We must avoid  11.f4?!  Ne4!  when an exchange of e4 merely creates good squares for the knight on e7 to leap to.   That said,  11.dxc5!?  bxc5  12.f4  is interesting and could do with some testing, with the idea of  12...Ne4  13.Nxe4  dxe4  14.Be2  followed by Nc4 and Qe1-g3.   With 11. Qe2 White keeps all options open @@StartBracket@@dxc5 and f2-f4 are very much still on the agenda@@EndBracket@@, while hoping that Black won't welcome the tension and, as we saw back inChapter 3,  @@StartFEN@@r2q1rk1/pb2nppp/1p1bpn2/2ppN3/3P4/PP1BP3/1BPNQPPP/R4RK1 b - - 2 11@@EndFEN@@  11...cxd4  12.exd4  leaves White in control of e4 and with attacking chances.   Now  11...Rc8  would transpose to our main line  @@StartBracket@@@@StartFEN@@r2q1rk1/pb3ppp/1pnbpn2/2ppN3/3P4/PP1BP3/1BPN1PPP/R2Q1RK1 b - - 0 10@@EndFEN@@  10...Rc8  11.Qe2  Ne7  @@EndBracket@@,  but Black can also move his queen or a knight: }
11... Ne4 12. Bxe4
{ Taking up the challenge. It's also possible to go  12.Rfd1  ,  placing the rook vis-à-vis the black queen. With the exchange on e4, White's doubles Black's pawns and still has designs down the d-file. }
12... dxe4 13. dxc5 { Not failing to open up the Zukertort bishop. } 13... Bxc5
14. Rfd1
{ Black is very solid here, but White's position still looked slightly the easier to handle in Pavlidis-Michelakos, Greek Championship, Thessaloniki 2017. Not only is Nxe4 a threat, but White has the easy-to-play plan of Nf1-g3 followed by Qg4, targeting e4, as well as g7 and possibly even e6. White also has ideas of b4 Bd6; Nc4, as well as of leaping into d7 as with  14...Qc7  15.Nf1  f6  16.Nd7!  . }
