11... Qc7 12. f4
{ Finally we make the key advance. If Black plays slowly then White may either exchange off a defender with 13. Ng4 or swap the exchange for a strong centre and attacking chances through @@StartFEN@@r4rk1/pbq1nppp/1p1bpn2/2ppN3/3P1P2/PP1BP3/1BPNQ1PP/R4RK1 w - - 0 12@@EndFEN@@  13.Rf3!?  c4!  14.bxc4!  dxc4  15.Ndxc4  . Black is, though, likely to invade on e4 whilst he can: }
12... Ne4 13. dxc5
{ This exchange is far from forced, but we quite like to give Black some options  @@StartBracket@@  13.Nec4!?  and  13.Rac1  are also reasonable options@@EndBracket@@.   Now  13...Bxc5  14.b4!  seizes some useful space.   13...bxc5  14.Bxe4  dxe4  15.Ndc4  weakens Black's pawns and the knight recapture temporarily reopens the b1-h7 diagonal: }
13... Nxc5 14. Bxh7+ { Boom! } 14... Kxh7 15. Qh5+ Kg8 16. Rf3
{ Route one stuff. We have to admit that White's attack is only good enough for a draw with best play, but how many opponents, already shell-shocked by the unexpected Greek Gift, are going to find a succession of only moves? Now  16...g6?  17.Rg3  is already all over, so Black must create a flight square on f7: }
16... f6 17. Rh3
{ Now  17...fxe5?  18.fxe5  should be winning as the f-file opens and so will the key long diagonal after exd6 or ...Bxe5; Bxe5. As such, Black must take the other way: }
17... Bxe5 18. fxe5 f5 19. Rf1
{ White is a piece down, but the threat of Rf3-g3 is a very strong one. The engines display their favourite '0.00', but you'd have to be pretty calm or just a pretty strong player to figure out how to defend here with the clock ticking: }
19... Ne4 20. Nxe4 dxe4 21. c4
{ Here too Black may be able to scramble a draw with care, but not only is g2-g4 now an issue, White also has the threat of Qh7+ Kf7; Rh6!. }
