{ Playing the queen's knight to d7 at such an early stage is a little rare, but as we're already well aware, transpositions abound in the Colle-Zukertort and here we'll examine all those lines were Black combines an early ...c5 with ...Nbd7.  He may well, for instance, begin  5...Be7  6.Bb2  and only now  go  6...Nbd7   or even  5...Be7  6.Bb2  O-O  7.O-O  b6  8.Nbd2  Bb7  9.Ne5  and only then  9...Nbd7  .  Specifically we'll examine:   Chapter 5: Black combines ...c5, ...Nbd7 and ...Bd6   Chapter 6: Black combines ...c5, ...Nbd7 and ...Be7   Of these, the lines in chapter 6 is the more common in practice, at least at club level where players often react to the Colle-Zukertort in a rather passive fashion. We should also mention here that on the odd occasion Black has been known to consider another destination for his dark-squared bishop. }
6. Bb2
{ We'll now see what happens when Black develops his bishop to  d6  . Note that  6...cxd4  7.exd4  Bd6  8.O-O  makes even less sense for Black than when the knight is on c6 and, as such, has rarely been seen. White need no longer worry about any ...Nb4 ideas and can simply continue with Nbd2, Qe2, f2-f4 and our favourite kingside attacking plans. }
6... g6
{ 6...cxd4  7.exd4  g6  8.Nbd2  Standard enough development and there's a reason for delaying castling short here.   We should also note that here White also has  8.Qe2!?  and if  8...Bg7  9.Ba3!?  preventing Black from castling.  8...Bg7  9.Qe2  A slight twist from our usual plan, although if you like to be simple, White can still continue with O-O, Ne5 and f2-f4. Now if  9...Nh5  10.g3  is fine and the king doesn't even have to go to the kingside:  9...O-O  10.O-O-O  This position is yet to receive a proper test, but we rather like Stockfish's idea. White simply wants to go Ne5 followed by h2-h4 and g2-g4. That should lead to a powerful attack, in contrast to which meeting ...a5 with a2-a4! will keep lines closed against our own king. }
7. O-O
{ White refuses to change course for now, but is no longer looking so much at Ne5 ideas @@StartBracket@@Black will be very solid down the a1-h8 and b1-h7 diagonals with his own bishop on g7@@EndBracket@@, as to exert some central pressure and begin to open the position up with ideas of a quick c2-c4 and/or dxc5. }
7... Bg7 8. c4
{ Challenging in the centre, while allowing the queen's knight to be developed to c3 to increase the pressure on d5. White may also continue with Qe2 to connect the rooks and while, in the event of an exchange, both recaptures on c4 are possible, we'll usually take back with the bishop, looking then to the e3-e4 advance and possibly any Ba6 raid to exchange off a fianchettoed bishop on b7. }
8... O-O 9. Nc3
{ Consistent. Only now is White ready to exchange in the centre and Black usually ignores that, preferring to aim for a double fianchetto set-up. }
9... b6
{ 9...dxc4!?  10.Bxc4  Simple chess.   10.bxc4!?  b6  11.Qe2  Bb7  12.Rad1  followed by Ne5 and f2-f4 is also possible if you're feeling more aggressive@@EndBracket@@.  White is now ready to go Qe2 and Rfd1, exerting a bit of pressure down the d-file. Observe how it may not be so easy for the black queen to find a great square @@StartBracket@@...Qe7 may leave it vulnerable to a timely Ba3 and going to c7 only encourages Rac1@@EndBracket@@, and also how White should be keeping an eye on the queenside pawns: a2-a4 might well be useful after ...a6 or ...b6, while dxc5 Nxc5; b3-b4 will seize some useful enough space.  10...b6  11.Qe2  Bb7  12.Rfd1   Black is pretty solid here, but we are nicely centralised, might probe with a4-a5 and/or Ba6, and can also look to pressure c5 with a combination of Rac1 @@StartBracket@@stepping away from any nasty accidents on the long diagonal@@EndBracket@@ and Ba3. Moreover, the immediate 13. dxc5 is a threat to weaken Black's structure. }
10. cxd5
{ A well-timed exchange and White is also happy to exchange knights here. His simple idea is Rc1 and then to begin to pressure the pawns on c5 and d5. }
10... exd5
{ 10...Nxd5  11.Nxd5  exd5  12.Rc1  This also sufficed for a pleasant edge in Yusupov-Sprenger, German Championship, Altenkirchen 2005. White has firm control of d4 @@StartBracket@@i.e. any exchange there will be met by a piece recapture, leaving Black with an IQP@@EndBracket@@, and might simply continue with Qe2 and Rfd1, but with the rook away from the gaze of the bishop on g7, he can very much also consider Ba3 ideas, as, indeed, Yusupov did:  12...Bb7  13.Ba3!  Rc8?!  14.Bb5!  Suddenly Black was under significant pressure with the c5-pawn pinned and in the game he walked into a neat little tactic:  14...Bc6?  15.Bxc6  Rxc6  16.b4!  Due to the pin down the c-file and idea of  16...c4?  17.b5  hitting both rooks, Yusupov was already winning a clear pawn. }
11. Rc1
{ Thematically stepping away from the a1-h8 diagonal and beginning to pressure c5. }
11... Bb7 12. Ne2
{ White gives himself yet another piece which can recapture on d4, but is mainly aiming to increase the pressure on d5 with Nf4, while unfurling the Zukertort bishop on b2. }
12... Ne4 13. Nf4
{ White enjoyed a small but pleasant edge here in Keymer-Santiago, Titled Tuesday Blitz 2020, in part because Black can't easily release the central tension without taking on an IQP. Keymer continued in instructive fashion and a manner which would have pleased Richard Reti: Rc2  @@StartBracket@@overprotecting the bishop on b2 and allowing the queen to slide leftwards@@EndBracket@@, Qa1 and Rfc1, leaving White with a most harmonious set-up and Black a little bottled up. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "5) ...Nbd7 / ...Bd6 Setup"]
[Black "...Nbd7 / ...Bd6 Setup: 8...Qe7"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Nf3
{ With this move, White prepares to enter the Colle setup, and remains flexible with the c-pawn, contrary to the Queen's Gambit. The extra control over e5 rules out lines such as the Albin Countergambit. }
2... Nf6 3. e3 e6 4. Bd3
{ The natural square to develop the bishop, which will very often prove White's most effective attacker. }
4... c5 5. b3 { Preparing the fianchetto of the dark-squared Colle bishop. }
5... Nbd7
{ Playing the queen's knight to d7 at such an early stage is a little rare, but as we're already well aware, transpositions abound in the Colle-Zukertort and here we'll examine all those lines were Black combines an early ...c5 with ...Nbd7.  He may well, for instance, begin  5...Be7  6.Bb2  and only now  go  6...Nbd7   or even  5...Be7  6.Bb2  O-O  7.O-O  b6  8.Nbd2  Bb7  9.Ne5  and only then  9...Nbd7  .  Specifically we'll examine:   Chapter 5: Black combines ...c5, ...Nbd7 and ...Bd6   Chapter 6: Black combines ...c5, ...Nbd7 and ...Be7   Of these, the lines in chapter 6 is the more common in practice, at least at club level where players often react to the Colle-Zukertort in a rather passive fashion. We should also mention here that on the odd occasion Black has been known to consider another destination for his dark-squared bishop. }
6. Bb2
{ We'll now see what happens when Black develops his bishop to  d6  . Note that  6...cxd4  7.exd4  Bd6  8.O-O  makes even less sense for Black than when the knight is on c6 and, as such, has rarely been seen. White need no longer worry about any ...Nb4 ideas and can simply continue with Nbd2, Qe2, f2-f4 and our favourite kingside attacking plans. }
6... Bd6 7. O-O
{ Consistently castling before completing queenside development, not that there's anything wrong with  7.Nbd2  and only then 8. O-O. }
7... O-O 8. Nbd2
{ Calmly continuing development ahead of looking to launch the other knight into e5. Now Black usually continues by fianchettoing his own queen's bishop. Instead  8...Re8?!  is rather passive and misguided, if just the sort of solid-looking move which might be seen at lower levels. We'll see how White was quick to whip up a powerful attack inSambuev-Lyn, where we'll also observe how  8...cxd4  9.exd4  b6  10.Qe2  again only helps White, who controls both e5 and e4. }
8... Qe7 9. Ne5
{ Forwards we go and let's now see what happens if Black continues to avoid developing the bishop on c8: }
9... cxd4 10. exd4 Ba3 11. Bxa3
{ Dragging the black queen potentially offside and away from the defence of the king. }
11... Qxa3 12. Qe2
{ Our standard development, although we should point out that the great Miguel Najdorf once won a crushing game with  12.Re1  b6  13.Re3!?  which is also promising. After 12. Qe2 we are all set to expand with f2-f4; just watch out for any annoying issues with a timely ...Qb2: }
12... b6 13. f4 Bb7 14. Rae1
{ This direct approach is yet to be tested, but White is now all set to go Rf3 with ...Qb2 no longer forking a1 and d4. That queen raid can now be met simply enough by Qe3 or Qf2 and meanwhile White is quite happy to gambit a2: }
14... Qxa2 15. Nxd7 Nxd7 16. f5
{ Having dragged the knight away from f6, White already enjoys a powerful initiative and very promising compensation. Black is highly vulnerable on all of e6, f7 and h7 and far from helped by  16...exf5  17.Qe7!  pinning the knight to the bishop on b7 ahead of going Rxf5. }
