9... b6 10. cxd5 { Exchanging straightaway to clear the c-file for Rac1. }
10... exd5 11. Rc1
{ Yet more simple chess, pinning the pawn on c5.  11.e4!?  is also tempting, but Black should be able to neutralise with it accurate play. Instead, we simply want to go Qc2, leaving Black once again solid, but struggling slightly to free his position. }
11... Bb7 12. Qc2
{ Here rather than e2 as the potential pressure against h7 might prove useful. White has two main plans in this type of position: Rfd1 and Bf5, slowly increasing the pressure and potentially pinning the knight on d7 to a rook on c8; arranging dxc5 when ...bxc5 can be well met by e3-e4, drastically changing the structure and aiming to leave Black vulnerable in the centre and certainly having lost control of c4.   Two other ideas which can also be useful are Nd2-f1-g3 and Qb1, to clear the c-file and possibly facilitate Qa1. }
