6. Bb2
{ We'll now see what happens when Black develops his bishop to  d6  . Note that  6...cxd4  7.exd4  Bd6  8.O-O  makes even less sense for Black than when the knight is on c6 and, as such, has rarely been seen. White need no longer worry about any ...Nb4 ideas and can simply continue with Nbd2, Qe2, f2-f4 and our favourite kingside attacking plans. }
6... Bd6 7. O-O
{ Consistently castling before completing queenside development, not that there's anything wrong with  7.Nbd2  and only then 8. O-O. }
7... O-O 8. Nbd2
{ Calmly continuing development ahead of looking to launch the other knight into e5. Now Black usually continues by fianchettoing his own queen's bishop. Instead  8...Re8?!  is rather passive and misguided, if just the sort of solid-looking move which might be seen at lower levels. We'll see how White was quick to whip up a powerful attack inSambuev-Lyn, where we'll also observe how  8...cxd4  9.exd4  b6  10.Qe2  again only helps White, who controls both e5 and e4. }
8... b6 9. Ne5
{ There's nothing wrong with  9.Qe2  but here we really would encourage you to expand without delay, particularly as White lays the framework for The Trap. }
9... Bb7 10. f4
{ Taking firm control of e5, while also encouraging Black to slide his queen to c7. Should Black proceed very slowly then White may just go 11. Qe2 and 12. Rf3 or even perhaps 11. Qf3 and 12. g4. }
10... Qe7 11. Rf3
{ White is happy to provoke any ...Ba3 plan Black may have in mind and otherwise will calmly go 12. Rh3, including in response to 11...Ne4: }
11... cxd4 12. Rh3
{ A powerful intermezzo. Suddenly Nxd7 is a rather large threat. } 12... Nxe5
13. fxe5 Bxe5 14. Bxh7+ Nxh7 15. Qh5
{ Here Black can stay on the board, but not affect the notion that White just has a strong initiative: }
15... f6 16. Qxh7+ Kf7 17. Nf3
{ Black must now be on the lookout for not just ideas of Qh5+, but also Nxe5 followed by Rf3+. }
17... Bd6 18. Qh5+
{ Now Black must advance and lose his g-pawn when he remains in some trouble, but much better that than: }
18... Kg8 19. Rf1 { The threat of Ng5's a killer. } *

