[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Nf3
{ With this move, White prepares to enter the Colle setup, and remains flexible with the c-pawn, contrary to the Queen's Gambit. The extra control over e5 rules out lines such as the Albin Countergambit. }
2... Nf6 3. e3 e6 4. Bd3
{ The natural square to develop the bishop, which will very often prove White's most effective attacker. }
4... c5 5. b3 { Preparing the fianchetto of the dark-squared Colle bishop. }
5... Nbd7
{ Playing the queen's knight to d7 at such an early stage is a little rare, but as we're already well aware, transpositions abound in the Colle-Zukertort and here we'll examine all those lines were Black combines an early ...c5 with ...Nbd7.  He may well, for instance, begin  5...Be7  6.Bb2  and only now  go  6...Nbd7   or even  5...Be7  6.Bb2  O-O  7.O-O  b6  8.Nbd2  Bb7  9.Ne5  and only then  9...Nbd7  .  Specifically we'll examine:   Chapter 5: Black combines ...c5, ...Nbd7 and ...Bd6   Chapter 6: Black combines ...c5, ...Nbd7 and ...Be7   Of these, the lines in chapter 6 is the more common in practice, at least at club level where players often react to the Colle-Zukertort in a rather passive fashion. We should also mention here that on the odd occasion Black has been known to consider another destination for his dark-squared bishop. }
6. Bb2
{ We'll now see what happens when Black develops his bishop to  d6  . Note that  6...cxd4  7.exd4  Bd6  8.O-O  makes even less sense for Black than when the knight is on c6 and, as such, has rarely been seen. White need no longer worry about any ...Nb4 ideas and can simply continue with Nbd2, Qe2, f2-f4 and our favourite kingside attacking plans. }
6... Bd6 7. O-O
{ Consistently castling before completing queenside development, not that there's anything wrong with  7.Nbd2  and only then 8. O-O. }
7... O-O 8. Nbd2
{ Calmly continuing development ahead of looking to launch the other knight into e5. Now Black usually continues by fianchettoing his own queen's bishop. Instead  8...Re8?!  is rather passive and misguided, if just the sort of solid-looking move which might be seen at lower levels. We'll see how White was quick to whip up a powerful attack inSambuev-Lyn, where we'll also observe how  8...cxd4  9.exd4  b6  10.Qe2  again only helps White, who controls both e5 and e4. }
8... b6 9. Ne5
{ There's nothing wrong with  9.Qe2  but here we really would encourage you to expand without delay, particularly as White lays the framework for The Trap. }
9... Bb7 10. f4
{ Taking firm control of e5, while also encouraging Black to slide his queen to c7. Should Black proceed very slowly then White may just go 11. Qe2 and 12. Rf3 or even perhaps 11. Qf3 and 12. g4. }
10... Ne4 11. Nxe4
{ Our preferred method of dealing with an intruder on e4,  although here  11.Bxe4!?  dxe4  12.Ndc4  is also promising, White landing up with a small but pleasant edge in a queenless middlegame after  12...Be7  13.Nxd7  Qxd7  14.dxc5  Qxd1  15.Rfxd1  Bxc5  16.Ba3!  . }
11... dxe4 12. Bc4
{ White's bishops are already the more active and we already have a large threat: @@StartFEN@@r2q1rk1/pb1n1ppp/1p1bp3/2p1N3/2BPpP2/1P2P3/PBP3PP/R2Q1RK1 w - - 0 12@@EndFEN@@  13.Nxd7  Qxd7  14.dxc5  bxc5  15.Qg4  ,  and if  15...g6  then crashing through with  16.f5   Moreover,  12...cxd4?!  13.Nxd7  Qxd7  14.Qxd4  also leaves White rather well set on the dark squares @@StartBracket@@and d-file@@EndBracket@@ , so Black should probably retain his knight: }
12... Nf6 13. Ng4
{ Continuing to play on the dark squares, as well as to crash through with f4-f5. Now  13...Nxg4?  14.Qxg4  would only help White to increase the pressure with Rad1 and make Black significantly weaken the kingside. }
13... Nd5 14. Nh6+
{ A handy resource and clearly  14...gxh6?  is cleaned up by  15.Qg4+  Kh8  16.dxc5  so Black must decline the offer: }
14... Kh8 15. Bxd5 Bxd5 16. Qh5
{ The knight is still pretty much taboo due to the discovered check and meanwhile not only is f7 attacked, but White is all set to roll forwards with c2-c4 and f4-f5. }
*

