[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "6) ...Nbd7 / ...Be7 Setup"]
[Black "...Nbd7 / ...Be7 Setup: 7...Bb7 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Nf3
{ With this move, White prepares to enter the Colle setup, and remains flexible with the c-pawn, contrary to the Queen's Gambit. The extra control over e5 rules out lines such as the Albin Countergambit. }
2... Nf6 3. e3 e6 4. Bd3
{ The natural square to develop the bishop, which will very often prove White's most effective attacker. }
4... c5 5. b3 { Preparing the fianchetto of the dark-squared Colle bishop. }
5... Nbd7 6. Bb2 b6 7. O-O Bb7 8. Ne5
{ A slight twist on our standard  8.Nbd2  approach, which is absolutely fine here too of course, but we quite like this Yusupov-endosed immediate leap.   Now  8...Bd6  9.Nd2  O-O  10.f4  would take us back into the realm of Chapter 5   And  8...Be7  9.Nd2  would be our main line here with 6...Be7, but what about if Black instead is in an optimistic mindset and aims for queenside expansion? }
8... a6 9. Nd2
{ Everything is now set for f2-f4 and there's certainly no need to fear Black delaying kingside development: }
9... b5 10. Nxd7
{ The first stage in the plan to open up our favourite Zukertort bishop. }
10... Nxd7 11. dxc5 Nxc5 12. Qh5
{ As we've already noted in the notes to Yusupov-Scheeren, White is clearly for choice here with the much better dark-squared bishop and f2-f4 followed by Nf3 the plan. }
*

