[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "6) ...Nbd7 / ...Be7 Setup"]
[Black "...Nbd7 / ...Be7 Setup: 7...O-O / 8...Qc7"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Nf3
{ With this move, White prepares to enter the Colle setup, and remains flexible with the c-pawn, contrary to the Queen's Gambit. The extra control over e5 rules out lines such as the Albin Countergambit. }
2... Nf6 3. e3 e6 4. Bd3
{ The natural square to develop the bishop, which will very often prove White's most effective attacker. }
4... c5 5. b3 { Preparing the fianchetto of the dark-squared Colle bishop. }
5... Nbd7 6. Bb2 Be7 7. O-O O-O 8. Nbd2
{ Standard development so far from White. As so often,  8...cxd4  9.exd4  would only now play into our hands with Qe2 followed by Ne5 then leaving White in control of e5 and e4. }
8... Qc7 9. Ne5
{ This echoes how we'll meet 8...b6. Now 10. f4 or even 10. Qf3 is next up and we still don't need to fear any central exchanges: }
9... cxd4 10. exd4 Nxe5 11. dxe5 Nd7 12. Qh5
{ White has generally preferred  12.Re1  with an edge here   or  12.f4  Nc5  13.Nf3  but we rather like the direct text, forcing a weakness.   Now @@StartFEN@@r1b2rk1/ppqnbppp/4p3/3pP2Q/8/1P1B4/PBPN1PPP/R4RK1 b - - 2 12@@EndFEN@@  12...g6  13.Qh6!  Nxe5?  14.f4  would of course win material down the long diagonal, so Black might involve Harry: }
12... h6 13. c4
{ A powerful follow-up. White clearly has ideas of Rac1, but mainly wants to meet ...Nc5 with Bc2. The other big idea is the direct Rae1-e3-g3, with f2-f4 kept in reserve for any misguided ...Bg5. }
*

[Event "?"]
