[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "6) ...Nbd7 / ...Be7 Setup"]
[Black "...Nbd7 / ...Be7 Setup: 7...O-O / 8...a6"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Nf3
{ With this move, White prepares to enter the Colle setup, and remains flexible with the c-pawn, contrary to the Queen's Gambit. The extra control over e5 rules out lines such as the Albin Countergambit. }
2... Nf6 3. e3 e6 4. Bd3
{ The natural square to develop the bishop, which will very often prove White's most effective attacker. }
4... c5 5. b3 { Preparing the fianchetto of the dark-squared Colle bishop. }
5... Nbd7 6. Bb2 Be7 7. O-O O-O 8. Nbd2
{ Standard development so far from White. As so often,  8...cxd4  9.exd4  would only now play into our hands with Qe2 followed by Ne5 then leaving White in control of e5 and e4. }
8... a6 9. Ne5
{ Our thematic expansion. Now Black may worry that ...b5 will run into Nc6, but in any case f2-f4 is coming and White again need not fear an exchange on e5: }
9... Nxe5 10. dxe5 Nd7 11. c4
{ A slight change of approach from  11.f4  but it makes decent sense to first hold Black up on the queenside before targeting his king.   Now @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/1p1nbppp/p3p3/2ppP3/2P5/1P1BP3/PB1N1PPP/R2Q1RK1 w - - 0 11@@EndFEN@@  12.cxd5  exd5  13.e6!?  is even an idea, and if  13...fxe6?  14.Qh5  .   @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/1p1nbppp/p3p3/2ppP3/2P5/1P1BP3/PB1N1PPP/R2Q1RK1 b - c3 0 11@@EndFEN@@  11...dxc4?  12.Nxc4  would only direct White's knight towards the hole on d6.   With @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/1p1nbppp/p3p3/2ppP3/2P5/1P1BP3/PB1N1PPP/R2Q1RK1 b - c3 0 11@@EndFEN@@  11...f6?  12.Qh5!  also rather bad new for Black, perhaps he would try and use the b-pawn after all: }
11... b5 12. Qc2
{ White holds everything together and is slightly for choice. Recapturing on c4 with bxc4 won't cause any problems, h7 is attacked and both the pressure-increasing Rad1 and f2-f4 are on their way. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "6) ...Nbd7 / ...Be7 Setup"]
[Black "...Nbd7 / ...Be7 Setup: 7...O-O / 8...b6 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Nf3
{ With this move, White prepares to enter the Colle setup, and remains flexible with the c-pawn, contrary to the Queen's Gambit. The extra control over e5 rules out lines such as the Albin Countergambit. }
2... Nf6 3. e3 e6 4. Bd3
{ The natural square to develop the bishop, which will very often prove White's most effective attacker. }
4... c5 5. b3 { Preparing the fianchetto of the dark-squared Colle bishop. }
5... Nbd7 6. Bb2 Be7 7. O-O O-O 8. Nbd2
{ Standard development so far from White. As so often,  8...cxd4  9.exd4  would only now play into our hands with Qe2 followed by Ne5 then leaving White in control of e5 and e4. }
8... b6 9. Ne5
{ It's high time to free the f-pawn for duty while also worrying Black with ideas over the bishop-pair-bagging Nc6. }
9... Nxe5 10. dxe5 Nd7 11. f4
{ Thematic expansion as again the central pawn bridgehead gives White a nice game. Qh5 will follow and we're also happy with exchanges on f6: }
11... f5 12. exf6
{ Now White will always be able to clamp down on e5 with Nf3 and also has ideas of all of Qh5, c2-c4 and e3-e4 to increase the pressure. }
12... Bxf6 13. Bxf6 Nxf6 14. Nf3
{ White's hold on e5 supplies a pleasant edge. Ne5, Qe2 and Rad1 may well follow, all the while as White also looks out for a timely pawn break, be it c2-c4 or even f4-f5 or g2-g4-g5. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "6) ...Nbd7 / ...Be7 Setup"]
[Black "...Nbd7 / ...Be7 Setup: 7...O-O / 8...b6 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Nf3
{ With this move, White prepares to enter the Colle setup, and remains flexible with the c-pawn, contrary to the Queen's Gambit. The extra control over e5 rules out lines such as the Albin Countergambit. }
2... Nf6 3. e3 e6 4. Bd3
{ The natural square to develop the bishop, which will very often prove White's most effective attacker. }
4... c5 5. b3 { Preparing the fianchetto of the dark-squared Colle bishop. }
5... Nbd7 6. Bb2 Be7 7. O-O O-O 8. Nbd2
{ Standard development so far from White. As so often,  8...cxd4  9.exd4  would only now play into our hands with Qe2 followed by Ne5 then leaving White in control of e5 and e4. }
8... b6 9. Ne5
{ It's high time to free the f-pawn for duty while also worrying Black with ideas over the bishop-pair-bagging Nc6. }
9... Bb7 10. Qe2
{ We've already seen that this restrained queen move can work well, as White connects the rooks and holds back on f2-f4 to first see what Black's up to. We'll now control e4 in the event of  10...cxd4  11.exd4  which usefully rules out any invasion there.   Note too that  10...a5  11.a4!  keeping lines closed, changes little bar to leave Black potentially weak on b5 and with any ...a6 and ...b5 advance ruled out.   As an alternative,  10.Qf3!?  is possible and has been tried by Richard a few times, as we saw back at the start of the course in 'the e5 outpost' section.   10.f4  cxd4  11.Bxd4!?   11.exd4  is possible too, as per one of our recommendations inChapter 6, solid though Black is with the bishop on e7 after  11...Nc5  12.Rf3!?  .  11...Ne4!  is very solid for Black. }
10... Nxe5 11. dxe5 Nd7 12. c4
{ An important restrictive advance, holding up Black's play, while also preparing to set up a pawn-roller with 13. cxd5 and 14. f4. White enjoys a very pleasant game with Rad1 and Qg4 or Qh5 also high on the agenda. }
*

