{ It's high time to free the f-pawn for duty while also worrying Black with ideas over the bishop-pair-bagging Nc6. }
9... Bb7 10. Qe2
{ We've already seen that this restrained queen move can work well, as White connects the rooks and holds back on f2-f4 to first see what Black's up to. We'll now control e4 in the event of  10...cxd4  11.exd4  which usefully rules out any invasion there.   Note too that  10...a5  11.a4!  keeping lines closed, changes little bar to leave Black potentially weak on b5 and with any ...a6 and ...b5 advance ruled out.   As an alternative,  10.Qf3!?  is possible and has been tried by Richard a few times, as we saw back at the start of the course in 'the e5 outpost' section.   10.f4  cxd4  11.Bxd4!?   11.exd4  is possible too, as per one of our recommendations inChapter 6, solid though Black is with the bishop on e7 after  11...Nc5  12.Rf3!?  .  11...Ne4!  is very solid for Black. }
10... Ne4 11. Nxd7
{ An important exchange to drag the black queen forwards so that she can be hit with tempo. If, though, you prefer to retain pieces and a complex early middlegame, rather than claim a simplifying edge, then by all means prefer  11.f4  . }
11... Qxd7 12. Nxe4
{ With the d-file not open,  12.Bxe4  dxe4  and Nc4 ideas make much less sense, so we instead make our generally preferred exchange ahead of heading forwards with the light-squared bishop. }
12... dxe4 13. Bb5 Qc7 14. dxc5
{ Opening up the gaze of our favourite bishop and bringing Qg4 ideas very much into the equation. }
14... Bxc5 15. Bc4
{ While we have to admit that Black is solidly placed and that a draw was agreed here in Doettling-A.Petrosian, Dortmund 2000, we actually feel that White has a small but pleasant edge. Of course, Qg4 is an idea, as is Rfd1, and a2-a4 will both restrain Black on the queenside and set White's pawn majority in motion.  Yes, Black can hoover, but we need not fear exchanges:  15...Rfd8  16.Rfd1  Rxd1+  17.Rxd1  Rd8  18.a4  Seizing space and in an endgame White may be able to start to roll the pawns with c2-c3 then b3-b4. For now White can create some useful luft with h2-h3 and also simply go Rd2 then Qd1.   Black, for his part, should be careful not to hurry with too many exchanges:  18...Rxd1+  19.Qxd1  Qd6?  20.Qg4!  Suddenly White is clearly better due to having much the better queen, whether after  20...Qf8  21.Qg3   or  20...g6  21.Qg5  when  21...Qd1+?  22.Bf1  Ba6  23.c4  more than holds everything together - just try to visualise Black's extremely vulnerable dark squares. }
