1. d4 d5 2. Nf3
{ With this move, White prepares to enter the Colle setup, and remains flexible with the c-pawn, contrary to the Queen's Gambit. The extra control over e5 rules out lines such as the Albin Countergambit. }
2... Nf6 3. e3 e6 4. Bd3
{ The natural square to develop the bishop, which will very often prove White's most effective attacker. }
4... c5 5. b3 { Preparing the fianchetto of the dark-squared Colle bishop. }
5... Nbd7 6. Bb2 Be7 7. O-O O-O 8. Nbd2
{ Standard development so far from White. As so often,  8...cxd4  9.exd4  would only now play into our hands with Qe2 followed by Ne5 then leaving White in control of e5 and e4. }
8... b6 9. Ne5
{ It's high time to free the f-pawn for duty while also worrying Black with ideas over the bishop-pair-bagging Nc6. }
9... Bb7 10. Qe2
{ We've already seen that this restrained queen move can work well, as White connects the rooks and holds back on f2-f4 to first see what Black's up to. We'll now control e4 in the event of  10...cxd4  11.exd4  which usefully rules out any invasion there.   Note too that  10...a5  11.a4!  keeping lines closed, changes little bar to leave Black potentially weak on b5 and with any ...a6 and ...b5 advance ruled out.   As an alternative,  10.Qf3!?  is possible and has been tried by Richard a few times, as we saw back at the start of the course in 'the e5 outpost' section.   10.f4  cxd4  11.Bxd4!?   11.exd4  is possible too, as per one of our recommendations inChapter 6, solid though Black is with the bishop on e7 after  11...Nc5  12.Rf3!?  .  11...Ne4!  is very solid for Black. }
10... Qc7 11. f4
{ We clamp down on e5 and may even here combine that policy with c2-c4, looking to exploit the position of the black queen, or White will just improve the pieces with Rad1 and Ndf3. However, with the bishop on b7 @@StartBracket@@and protected@@EndBracket@@ do try to avoid any Rf3 @@StartBracket@@or Qf3@@EndBracket@@ ...c4 tactics. }
11... Rac8 12. Rad1
{ Calm centralisation rather than  12.c4!?  . White brings his final piece into play, overprotecting d4 before any c2-c4 push.   We'll now see Andreikin in action after  12...g6  13.Ndf3  inAndreikin-Hakobyan, Chess.com Global Championship Knockout @@StartBracket@@rapid@@EndBracket@@ 2022, but what if Black instead brings his final rook into the centre? }
12... Rfd8 13. f5
{ White has seized the initiative and  13...exf5?!  14.Bxf5  would now place Black in a slightly awkward pin.   He also can't so easily deal with White's control of e5 and may well be rather scared that @@StartFEN@@2rr2k1/pbqnbppp/1p2pn2/2ppNP2/3P4/1P1BP3/PBPNQ1PP/3R1RK1 w - - 0 13@@EndFEN@@  14.Nxf7!  Kxf7  15.fxe6+  is about to hit him @@StartBracket@@  15...Kxe6  16.e4  is a key point@@EndBracket@@. }
13... Bd6 14. fxe6 fxe6 15. Ndf3
{ White's control of e5 and, thanks to that, also c4 leaves him clearly for choice, with ideas of both Ng5 and c2-c4 to increase the pressure high on the agenda. }
