14... Bf6 15. Rad1 Qc8 16. g4
{ A change of gear, but, well, why not, with all the pieces on good squares? White's space advantage left her slightly for choice in Koneru-T. Kosintseva, Women's Grand Prix, Rostov-on-Don 2011, where a2-a4 helped to keep the queenside closed and meanwhile g4-g5 was coming. Once the pawn is on g5, White might then look to arrange the f4-f5 break or even hurl Harry forwards.  Note too that Black can't very easily hold up g4-g5:  16...h6?  17.g5!  hxg5  18.Qg4  A powerful pawn sacrifice, simply intending to obliterate Black with 19. fxg5 and 20. g6 or:  18...gxf4?  19.Rxf4  Suddenly there's no good defence as retreating the bishop runs into dxc5. }
