[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "7) The Delayed ...c5 Setup"]
[Black "Delayed ...c5 Setup: 4...b6 / 5...Ba6"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Nf3
{ With this move, White prepares to enter the Colle setup, and remains flexible with the c-pawn, contrary to the Queen's Gambit. The extra control over e5 rules out lines such as the Albin Countergambit. }
2... Nf6 3. e3 e6 4. Bd3
{ We now move on to discuss a few rare ideas, which Black occasionally plays. In all cases, we'll be aiming to make good use of our favourite Zukertort bishop after 5. b3 and Bb2. Specifically, we'll discuss:  Chapter 8: ...Qa5+ and ...Bb4+ ideas  Chapter 8: An early ...Ne4 and other rare lines after ...c5  Chapter 7: Black delays ...c5  Of these, White has little to fear in the first two lines, but the third option is quite a solid choice from Black and we may have to be content to patiently probe away, looking for an edge. }
4... b6 5. b3
{ We'll now take a look at a solid line from Black where he mirrors White with a queenside fianchetto and holds back on a central challenge with ...c5. Note though that on pretty much every move Black can go ...c5 if he prefers when play is extremely likely to transpose back into a line we considered in Theory One, Two or Three, depending on where the bishop on f8 and knight on b8 are developed to.   For our part, standard Colle-Zukertort development with Bb2, O-O and Nbd2 is the main plan, while also keeping an eye on an early c2-c4 break should Black be a little ambitious with an early ...Ne4 or ...Ba6. }
5... Ba6 6. Bxa6
{ Simple chess, misplacing Black's queen's knight and an easier line to play than the Queen's Indian-like  6.c4!?  Bb4+  7.Nbd2  . }
6... Nxa6 7. O-O
{ White wants to continue with Qe2 and then gain some central pressure with c2-c4 and/or Ne5. }
7... Be7 8. Qe2 Nb8 9. c4
{ A useful space-gainer, as well as a move which may leave Black a little vulnerable on c6 and down the c-file in general after an exchange on d5. }
9... O-O 10. Bb2
{ White is in no rush and would be quite happy to activate his queen with  10...dxc4  11.Qxc4  . Black is pretty solid, but White should be happy enough and has two main plans to pick from: the Zukertort-like Nbd2 followed by Ne5 and f2-f4; slightly more aggressive development with Nc3 and Rac1, looking to exert some pressure down the c-file and/or break with e3-e4. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "7) The Delayed ...c5 Setup"]
[Black "Delayed ...c5 Setup: 4...b6 / 5...Bb7 / 6...Nbd7 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Nf3
{ With this move, White prepares to enter the Colle setup, and remains flexible with the c-pawn, contrary to the Queen's Gambit. The extra control over e5 rules out lines such as the Albin Countergambit. }
2... Nf6 3. e3 e6 4. Bd3
{ We now move on to discuss a few rare ideas, which Black occasionally plays. In all cases, we'll be aiming to make good use of our favourite Zukertort bishop after 5. b3 and Bb2. Specifically, we'll discuss:  Chapter 8: ...Qa5+ and ...Bb4+ ideas  Chapter 8: An early ...Ne4 and other rare lines after ...c5  Chapter 7: Black delays ...c5  Of these, White has little to fear in the first two lines, but the third option is quite a solid choice from Black and we may have to be content to patiently probe away, looking for an edge. }
4... b6 5. b3
{ We'll now take a look at a solid line from Black where he mirrors White with a queenside fianchetto and holds back on a central challenge with ...c5. Note though that on pretty much every move Black can go ...c5 if he prefers when play is extremely likely to transpose back into a line we considered in Theory One, Two or Three, depending on where the bishop on f8 and knight on b8 are developed to.   For our part, standard Colle-Zukertort development with Bb2, O-O and Nbd2 is the main plan, while also keeping an eye on an early c2-c4 break should Black be a little ambitious with an early ...Ne4 or ...Ba6. }
5... Bb7 6. Bb2
{ Increasing the grip on e5 and now Black's most solid approach sees him setting up with ...Nbd7 and ...Be7. }
6... Nbd7 7. O-O
{ Standard stuff from White and now 7...Be7 is the most annoying move to face, but is by no means forced. }
7... Bd6 8. Ne5
{ While there's nothing wrong with  8.Nbd2  we prefer to expand first and only then go Nbd2, trying to tempt Black into a misguided exchange. }
8... Bxe5 9. dxe5 Ne4 10. b4
{ This bold push seems even stronger than Ter Sahakyan's  10.f3  Nec5  11.Be2  when White only has a pleasant edge. Indeed, we aim for even more by aiming to embarrass Black's knight with  @@StartFEN@@r2qk2r/pbpn1ppp/1p2p3/3pP3/1P2n3/3BP3/PBP2PPP/RN1Q1RK1 w kq - 0 10@@EndFEN@@  11.f3  Ng5  12.h4  . }
10... f5 11. f3 Ng5 12. Nd2
{ Black has saved his knight, but it is rather strangely placed on g5. White will always now be able to consider a timely f3-f4, but mainly wants to break with c2-c4, increasing the pressure on d5, while helping the queen's rook which will step across to c1. Note that any cxd5 exd5 exchange will leave White with a mighty bridgehead and passed pawn on e5. }
