[White "7) The Delayed ...c5 Setup"]
[Black "Delayed ...c5 Setup: 4...b6 / 5...Bb7 / 7...Ne4 "]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Nf3
{ With this move, White prepares to enter the Colle setup, and remains flexible with the c-pawn, contrary to the Queen's Gambit. The extra control over e5 rules out lines such as the Albin Countergambit. }
2... Nf6 3. e3 e6 4. Bd3
{ We now move on to discuss a few rare ideas, which Black occasionally plays. In all cases, we'll be aiming to make good use of our favourite Zukertort bishop after 5. b3 and Bb2. Specifically, we'll discuss:  Chapter 8: ...Qa5+ and ...Bb4+ ideas  Chapter 8: An early ...Ne4 and other rare lines after ...c5  Chapter 7: Black delays ...c5  Of these, White has little to fear in the first two lines, but the third option is quite a solid choice from Black and we may have to be content to patiently probe away, looking for an edge. }
4... b6 5. b3
{ We'll now take a look at a solid line from Black where he mirrors White with a queenside fianchetto and holds back on a central challenge with ...c5. Note though that on pretty much every move Black can go ...c5 if he prefers when play is extremely likely to transpose back into a line we considered in Theory One, Two or Three, depending on where the bishop on f8 and knight on b8 are developed to.   For our part, standard Colle-Zukertort development with Bb2, O-O and Nbd2 is the main plan, while also keeping an eye on an early c2-c4 break should Black be a little ambitious with an early ...Ne4 or ...Ba6. }
5... Bb7 6. Bb2
{ Increasing the grip on e5 and now Black's most solid approach sees him setting up with ...Nbd7 and ...Be7. }
6... Nbd7 7. O-O
{ Standard stuff from White and now 7...Be7 is the most annoying move to face, but is by no means forced. }
7... Ne4 8. c4
{ With the king safe on g1 and the queen's bishop fianchettoed, we revert back to our favourite way of dealing with an early ...Ne4, namely increasing the central pressure with c2-c4. Now Nbd2 and Qc2 may well follow and  8...Be7  9.Nbd2  transposes to a line we will examine via  @@StartFEN@@r2qkb1r/pbpn1ppp/1p2pn2/3p4/3P4/1P1BPN2/PBP2PPP/RN1Q1RK1 b kq - 4 7@@EndFEN@@  7...Be7  8.Nbd2  Ne4  9.c4  . Better that for Black than immediately setting up a Stonewall formation. }
8... f5 9. cxd5
{ A strong exchange and now  9...Bxd5  10.Qe2  followed by Nbd2 and Rac1 is a pleasant edge for White, if also likely the lesser evil for Black. }
9... exd5 10. Ne5
{ Immediately invading the hole on e5, while both freeing the pawn on f2 for action and threatening Qh5+. }
10... Nxe5 11. dxe5
{ Thanks to the bridgehead and passed pawn on e5 White is clearly for choice, with one decent plan that of Nc3 and if Black doesn't exchange knights, then Ne2-f4, beginning to eye the weaknesses in Black's position. }
