{ Again, the best response to the invasion of e4, in contrast to which  9.Ne5  Nxe5!  10.dxe5  O-O  is just extremely solid for Black. We are now ready to increase the pressure against e4 and also begin to generate some pressure down the c-file with Qc2. }
9... O-O 10. Qc2 Ndf6 11. Rac1 Rc8 12. Rfd1
{ It makes good sense to centralise the rooks so, keeping Ne5 ideas in reserve for now, while encouraging Black to break when we want to exchange on c5, hoping then to exploit the line-up of white rook and black queen on the d-file: }
12... c5 13. dxc5 Nxc5 14. Be2
{ Black has side-stepped any issues on e4, but is yet to fully equalise, as we saw back in our introductory section on the c2-c4 break. Here White might regroup on the long diagonal with Bd4 or Qb2, while if the knight ever leaves c5, a Qb1 and Bd3 pairing would make good sense. }
