4... b6 5. b3
{ We'll now take a look at a solid line from Black where he mirrors White with a queenside fianchetto and holds back on a central challenge with ...c5. Note though that on pretty much every move Black can go ...c5 if he prefers when play is extremely likely to transpose back into a line we considered in Theory One, Two or Three, depending on where the bishop on f8 and knight on b8 are developed to.   For our part, standard Colle-Zukertort development with Bb2, O-O and Nbd2 is the main plan, while also keeping an eye on an early c2-c4 break should Black be a little ambitious with an early ...Ne4 or ...Ba6. }
