8... O-O 9. c4
{ A change of approach, but  9.Ne5  Ne4  has been shown to be very solid for Black. Instead, we expand on the queenside and will look to combine play down the c-file with Ne5 ideas.   Now @@StartFEN@@r2q1rk1/pbpnbppp/1p2pn2/3p4/2PP4/1P1BPN2/PB1N1PPP/R2Q1RK1 b - c3 0 9@@EndFEN@@  9...Ne4  10.Qc2  transposes back to a position we tackled via  @@StartFEN@@r2qk2r/pbpnbppp/1p2pn2/3p4/3P4/1P1BPN2/PBPN1PPP/R2Q1RK1 b kq - 6 8@@EndFEN@@  8...Ne4  9.c4  O-O  10.Qc2  but while that has happened fairly often in practice, Black does have a big alternative here. }
9... dxc4 10. bxc4
{ @@StartFEN@@r2q1rk1/pbpnbppp/1p2pn2/3p4/2PP4/1P1BPN2/PB1N1PPP/R2Q1RK1 b - c3 0 9@@EndFEN@@  9...c5  is by some margin Black's most popular move, but the solid exchange on c4 was Gledura's sensible recommendation. All three recaptures are possible, but this is the most unbalancing and richest choice and now White will push forwards with e3-e4 unless Black hits back immediately in the centre. }
10... c5 11. a4
{ A new idea here, if not a new idea in general. White gives himself the option of a timely queenside challenge with a4-a5 and doesn't commit the queen just yet. She will be much happier on e2 only after  11...cxd4  12.exd4  but Black is by no means compelled to exchange. }
11... Qc7 12. Bc3
{ The position is roughly level, if also far from dull or even. White simply wants to exert a bit of pressure with a4-a5 and may also bring the queen into play with Qc2-b2 ahead of committing the king's rook to e1, d1, c1 or even b1. }
