{ With this move, White prepares to enter the Colle setup, and remains flexible with the c-pawn, contrary to the Queen's Gambit. The extra control over e5 rules out lines such as the Albin Countergambit. }
2... Nf6 3. e3 e6 4. Bd3
{ We now move on to discuss a few rare ideas, which Black occasionally plays. In all cases, we'll be aiming to make good use of our favourite Zukertort bishop after 5. b3 and Bb2. Specifically, we'll discuss:  Chapter 8: ...Qa5+ and ...Bb4+ ideas  Chapter 8: An early ...Ne4 and other rare lines after ...c5  Chapter 7: Black delays ...c5  Of these, White has little to fear in the first two lines, but the third option is quite a solid choice from Black and we may have to be content to patiently probe away, looking for an edge. }
4... b6 5. b3
{ We'll now take a look at a solid line from Black where he mirrors White with a queenside fianchetto and holds back on a central challenge with ...c5. Note though that on pretty much every move Black can go ...c5 if he prefers when play is extremely likely to transpose back into a line we considered in Theory One, Two or Three, depending on where the bishop on f8 and knight on b8 are developed to.   For our part, standard Colle-Zukertort development with Bb2, O-O and Nbd2 is the main plan, while also keeping an eye on an early c2-c4 break should Black be a little ambitious with an early ...Ne4 or ...Ba6. }
5... Bb7 6. Bb2
{ Increasing the grip on e5 and now Black's most solid approach sees him setting up with ...Nbd7 and ...Be7. }
6... Nbd7 7. O-O
{ Standard stuff from White and now 7...Be7 is the most annoying move to face, but is by no means forced. }
7... Be7 8. Nbd2
{ The first stage of development is complete and will Black now house his king or try something more ambitious? The latter is, perhaps unsurprisingly, recommended by Benjamin Gledura on his Lifetime Repertoires: Gledura's Queen's Gambit Accepted. }
8... O-O 9. c4
{ A change of approach, but  9.Ne5  Ne4  has been shown to be very solid for Black. Instead, we expand on the queenside and will look to combine play down the c-file with Ne5 ideas.   Now @@StartFEN@@r2q1rk1/pbpnbppp/1p2pn2/3p4/2PP4/1P1BPN2/PB1N1PPP/R2Q1RK1 b - c3 0 9@@EndFEN@@  9...Ne4  10.Qc2  transposes back to a position we tackled via  @@StartFEN@@r2qk2r/pbpnbppp/1p2pn2/3p4/3P4/1P1BPN2/PBPN1PPP/R2Q1RK1 b kq - 6 8@@EndFEN@@  8...Ne4  9.c4  O-O  10.Qc2  but while that has happened fairly often in practice, Black does have a big alternative here. }
9... c5 10. Rc1
{ Retaining the tension, while hoping that Black will struggle to follow suit. }
10... Rc8 11. Qe2
{ A much safer square for the queen than stepping on to the c-file. Now the rooks are connected and White has ideas of Rfd1 when after, say, cxd5 exd5, a plan of Nd2-f1-g3 might well be a good one.   Even here ideas of Ne5 followed by a kingside attack are by no means off the table. Note too that, in contrast, the black queen doesn't have a particularly enticing square to move to, which may be why Black's most popular move here has been to invade on e4 after all. }
11... cxd4 12. Nxd4
{ Maintaining control  @@StartBracket@@  12.exd4  dxc4  13.bxc4  might tempt more aggressive types@@EndBracket@@, while simply intending to keep Black a little jammed up with Rfd1. }
12... dxc4 13. Bxc4
{ Nakamura preferred  13.Nxc4  in a blitz game with Karjakin, but we would prefer to keep Black a little bottled up, while on top of Rfd1, introducing the idea of Ba6 to probe the black queenside and exploit White's slightly more active queen.   Note too that Bxe6!? ideas very much come into the equation too, exchanging two pieces for a rook and two pawns ahead of beginning to expand with e3-e4. }
