[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "8) Rare Setups (Early ...Ne4 & ...Qa5)"]
[Black "Rare Setups: 4...c5 / 5...cxd4 / 6...Bb4+ #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Nf3
{ With this move, White prepares to enter the Colle setup, and remains flexible with the c-pawn, contrary to the Queen's Gambit. The extra control over e5 rules out lines such as the Albin Countergambit. }
2... Nf6 3. e3 e6 4. Bd3
{ The natural square to develop the bishop, which will very often prove White's most effective attacker. }
4... c5 5. b3 { Preparing the fianchetto of the dark-squared Colle bishop. }
5... cxd4 6. exd4 Bb4+ 7. c3
{ Just as against 5...Qa5+, this is a good choice and not  7.Nbd2?  when  7...Bc3!  8.Rb1  Nc6  is already a bit awkward. White's plan is now to castle, then delay Bb2 for a bit to clamp down on the key e5-square: }
7... Be7 8. O-O
{ Here Black isn't fighting for e5, but in any case it makes decent sense for White to go Re1 next before completing queenside development: }
8... O-O 9. Re1
{ Now White may simply continue with Ne5, Bb2 and Nbd2 in true Zukertort fashion, but with Black quite active you may prefer to angle for an improved version of a London System with Bf4!?.   In either case, a quick Ne5, looking to seize the initiative is no bad idea. }
9... b6 10. Ne5
{ Crossing Black's plans. White might now even go super-aggressive with Re3-h3 and Bg5, a policy endorsed by the engines. Michael Adams once met @@StartFEN@@rnbq1rk1/pp2bppp/4pn2/3p4/3P4/1PPB1N2/P4PPP/RNBQ1RK1 w - - 0 9@@EndFEN@@  9.Nbd2  with  9...b6  but here Black cannot follow through with ...Ba6: }
10... Ba6 11. Bxa6 Nxa6 12. Nc6
{ The point. Black is going to lose the exchange after a trade on e7 and Ba3. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "8) Rare Setups (Early ...Ne4 & ...Qa5)"]
[Black "Rare Setups: 4...c5 / 5...cxd4 / 6...Bb4+ #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Nf3
{ With this move, White prepares to enter the Colle setup, and remains flexible with the c-pawn, contrary to the Queen's Gambit. The extra control over e5 rules out lines such as the Albin Countergambit. }
2... Nf6 3. e3 e6 4. Bd3
{ The natural square to develop the bishop, which will very often prove White's most effective attacker. }
4... c5 5. b3 { Preparing the fianchetto of the dark-squared Colle bishop. }
5... cxd4 6. exd4 Bb4+ 7. c3
{ Just as against 5...Qa5+, this is a good choice and not  7.Nbd2?  when  7...Bc3!  8.Rb1  Nc6  is already a bit awkward. White's plan is now to castle, then delay Bb2 for a bit to clamp down on the key e5-square: }
7... Bd6 8. O-O
{ Sensibly housing the king ahead of preparing to clamp down on the e5-square with Re1. }
8... Nc6 9. Re1
{ Now White might simply continue in standard Colle-Zukertort fashion with Bb2 and Nbd2, but just as against 7...Be7, we would prefer something even more aggressive.   Indeed, White can go for a rapid Ne5 and/or Bg5, pinning the knight on f6 followed by Qf3, with a kind of souped-up Torre Attack and one where the small weakness on c3 doesn't seem especially important. }
9... b6 10. Ne5 Bb7 11. Bf4
{ Here a London-type approach appears stronger than  11.Bg5  Qc7  . White now has full control of e5,  @@StartFEN@@r2qk2r/pb3ppp/1pnbpn2/3pN3/3P1B2/1PPB4/P4PPP/RN1QR1K1 b kq - 3 11@@EndFEN@@  11...Nd7??  would be a blunder after  12.Nxc6  Bxc6  13.Bxd6  and Nbd2 will complete development, after which White can look to the kingside to attack. }
11... O-O 12. Nd2 Rc8 13. Re3
{ With the rook bound for g3 or h3, and c3 always at least indirectly defended by Bxh7+ tricks, White was already clearly better in Lemos-Akobian, Gibraltar 2019. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "8) Rare Setups (Early ...Ne4 & ...Qa5)"]
[Black "Rare Setups: 4...c5 / 5...Nc6"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Nf3
{ With this move, White prepares to enter the Colle setup, and remains flexible with the c-pawn, contrary to the Queen's Gambit. The extra control over e5 rules out lines such as the Albin Countergambit. }
2... Nf6 3. e3 e6 4. Bd3
{ The natural square to develop the bishop, which will very often prove White's most effective attacker. }
4... c5 5. b3 { Preparing the fianchetto of the dark-squared Colle bishop. }
5... Nc6 6. Bb2 cxd4
{ Relieving the central tension is very typical at this moment. } 7. exd4
{ Needless to say, we recapture with the pawn and so maintain maximum control of the key e5-square. }
7... Bb4+ 8. c3
{ Still the right response and a better choice than  8.Nbd2  Ne4  . } 8... Bd6
9. O-O
{ White's plan of clamping down on e5 is still a good one, with Re1, Nbd2 and Ne5 set to complete development, and clearly  9...e5?  would now be horribly premature due to  10.dxe5  Nxe5  11.Re1  causing early anguish down the e-file and for the black king. }
9... O-O 10. Re1 Qc7 11. c4
{ A loss of a tempo, but don't forget that Black took two moves to get the bishop to d6. White has an edge and the initiative here.   He threatens to clamp down with c4-c5, would be delighted to receive a mobile central duo after ...dxc4; bxc4, and also has ideas of pressuring d5 with Nc3, possibly followed by Rc1 and Ne5. }
