[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "8) Rare Setups (Early ...Ne4 & ...Qa5)"]
[Black "Rare Setups: 4...c5 / 5...Qa5+ #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Nf3
{ With this move, White prepares to enter the Colle setup, and remains flexible with the c-pawn, contrary to the Queen's Gambit. The extra control over e5 rules out lines such as the Albin Countergambit. }
2... Nf6 3. e3 e6 4. Bd3
{ The natural square to develop the bishop, which will very often prove White's most effective attacker. }
4... c5 5. b3 { Preparing the fianchetto of the dark-squared Colle bishop. }
5... Qa5+ 6. c3
{ Simple chess, intending to castle next out of the pin. If, though, you prefer something independent, then it appears that  6.Bd2!?  Qc7  7.c4  still contains some teeth. }
6... cxd4 7. exd4
{ The exchange on d4 has been Black's second most popular choice on move 6, but yet again White should welcome it. He will now castle and can then go Re1 and/or Ne5, taking control of that square, while again the dark-squared bishop may pop out to f4 or g5, as well as just tuck in on b2. }
7... Ne4 8. O-O
{ Now c3-c4 will follow and you may soon see Black having to rather weaken himself with ...f5. Meanwhile, the c-pawn is taboo: }
8... Nxc3 9. Qc2 Bb4 10. Nxc3 Bxc3 11. Bd2
{ White is winning material down the c-file. } *

