[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Nf3
{ With this move, White prepares to enter the Colle setup, and remains flexible with the c-pawn, contrary to the Queen's Gambit. The extra control over e5 rules out lines such as the Albin Countergambit. }
2... Nf6 3. e3 e6 4. Bd3
{ The natural square to develop the bishop, which will very often prove White's most effective attacker. }
4... c5 5. b3 { Preparing the fianchetto of the dark-squared Colle bishop. }
5... Qa5+ 6. c3
{ Simple chess, intending to castle next out of the pin. If, though, you prefer something independent, then it appears that  6.Bd2!?  Qc7  7.c4  still contains some teeth. }
6... Bd6 7. O-O Nbd7 8. Bb2
{ Simple stuff as White prepares to continue development with Nbd2, although when Black has to recapture with the queen,  8.dxc5!?  also comes into the equation. }
8... O-O 9. Nbd2
{ Now White is ready to open things up with c3-c4 and maybe also dxc5, and  8...Qc7  9.c4  would actually transpose to a position we saw inChapter 5, via a  @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/pp3ppp/4pn2/2pp4/3P4/1P1BPN2/P1P2PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Nbd7  6.Bb2  Bd6  7.O-O  O-O  8.Nbd2  Qc7  9.c4  move order, the only difference here being that both sides have expended an extra tempo @@StartBracket@@...Qa5-c7 and c2-c3-c4@@EndBracket@@. But what about if Black breaks in the centre without delay? }
9... e5 10. dxe5 { White must move quickly to open the position on his terms. }
10... Nxe5 11. Nxe5 Bxe5 12. Qc2
{ This is why we traded knights on e5. Now Nf3 followed by c3-c4 once the bishop retreats will seize a strong initiative. }
12... Qc7 13. f4
{ Much stronger than  13.Nf3  c4  . Now White will get in the ideal break after all: }
13... Bd6 14. Rae1
{ One final accurate move to overprotect e3 @@StartBracket@@and avoid the slightly messy  14.c4  d4!?  @@EndBracket@@ leaves White clearly for choice with c3-c4 next up, leaving White's position a model of harmony and Black's kingside and central control rather shaky. }
