[White "8) Rare Setups (Early ...Ne4 & ...Qa5)"]
[Black "Rare Setups: 4...c5 / 5...Qa5+ #6"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Nf3
{ With this move, White prepares to enter the Colle setup, and remains flexible with the c-pawn, contrary to the Queen's Gambit. The extra control over e5 rules out lines such as the Albin Countergambit. }
2... Nf6 3. e3 e6 4. Bd3
{ The natural square to develop the bishop, which will very often prove White's most effective attacker. }
4... c5 5. b3 { Preparing the fianchetto of the dark-squared Colle bishop. }
5... Qa5+ 6. c3
{ Simple chess, intending to castle next out of the pin. If, though, you prefer something independent, then it appears that  6.Bd2!?  Qc7  7.c4  still contains some teeth. }
6... Nc6 7. O-O
{ Escaping the pin ahead of simply continuing to complete development with Bb2 and Nbd2. }
7... Qc7 8. Bb2 Bd6 9. dxc5
{ Distracting the bishop before Black can entertain any ideas of ...e5. } 9...
Bxc5 10. Nbd2
{ Unlike after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/pp3ppp/4pn2/2pp4/3P4/1P1BPN2/P1P2PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Nc6  6.Bb2  Bd6  7.O-O  Qc7  8.dxc5!  Bxc5  9.Nbd2  White's c-pawn is slightly in the way, but we are still doing well, since c3-c4 will follow and there's no reason to fear ...e5: }
10... e5 11. c4
{ Now  11...e4?!  12.cxd5  ensures that White doesn't lose a piece, while opening up the bishop to the benefit of his forces, not least the bishop on b2. }
11... dxc4 12. Bxc4 O-O 13. Rc1
{ It may at first not look like all that much, but Black is actually under pressure here, with Bb5 a definite threat, as well as Bxf7+. White may also build up with Qc2 and would be delighted to powerfully leap forwards with  13...e4?  14.Ng5!  . }
