[White "8) Rare Setups (Early ...Ne4 & ...Qa5)"]
[Black "Rare Setups: 4...c5 / 5...Qa5+ #7"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Nf3
{ With this move, White prepares to enter the Colle setup, and remains flexible with the c-pawn, contrary to the Queen's Gambit. The extra control over e5 rules out lines such as the Albin Countergambit. }
2... Nf6 3. e3 e6 4. Bd3
{ The natural square to develop the bishop, which will very often prove White's most effective attacker. }
4... c5 5. b3 { Preparing the fianchetto of the dark-squared Colle bishop. }
5... Qa5+ 6. c3
{ Simple chess, intending to castle next out of the pin. If, though, you prefer something independent, then it appears that  6.Bd2!?  Qc7  7.c4  still contains some teeth. }
6... Nc6 7. O-O
{ Escaping the pin ahead of simply continuing to complete development with Bb2 and Nbd2. }
7... Be7 8. Bb2 O-O 9. Nbd2
{ Calm, thematic development. Yes, the Zukertort bishop is slightly restricted, but c3-c4 is imminent, although if Black, say, goes in for  9...cxd4  10.exd4  White may be happy with the queenside how it is, preferring to attack after a Ne5 leap. }
9... Rd8
{ 9...Qc7  10.dxc5!  Bxc5  11.c4  As we already saw back inChapter 1, the centre is opening up much faster than Black would wish. }
10. Qe2
{ There's no rush to go Ne5 and the text is quite sneaky. If Black, say, goes  10...Bd7  then White will advance with  11.Ne5  and f2-f4, as once played by Krasenkow/   Meanwhile  10...b6??  would be a tactical mistake due to  11.b4!  and if  11...cxb4  12.Nb3  Qa4  13.Bb5  winning material. }
10... Qc7 11. Rac1
{ Calm preparation for c3-c4, with  11.dxc5?!  e5!  no longer so convincing @@StartBracket@@with the queen on e2,  12.c4?  e4  would cost White a piece@@EndBracket@@. }
11... b6 12. c4
{ This strategically complex position is yet to receive a test, but we'd prefer to take White who is ready to try and inflict hanging pawns on Black with cxd5 exd5; dxc5 bxc5 followed, ideally, by the e3-e4 break.  White may also find a2-a3 a useful move to insert @@StartBracket@@or meet ...Nb4 with Bb1@@EndBracket@@, but should be wary of rushing with Ne5 when d4 is a little tender due to the rook on d8. }
*

