[White "8) Rare Setups (Early ...Ne4 & ...Qa5)"]
[Black "Rare Setups: 4...c5 / 5...Bd7"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Nf3
{ With this move, White prepares to enter the Colle setup, and remains flexible with the c-pawn, contrary to the Queen's Gambit. The extra control over e5 rules out lines such as the Albin Countergambit. }
2... Nf6 3. e3 e6 4. Bd3
{ The natural square to develop the bishop, which will very often prove White's most effective attacker. }
4... c5 5. b3 { Preparing the fianchetto of the dark-squared Colle bishop. }
5... Bd7 6. Bb2 { A calm response to another strange fifth move from Black. }
6... a6 7. O-O
{ Consistent play as White angles to provoke ...b5, being all set to then open up the long diagonal with dxc5, shattering Black's queenside ambitions in the process. }
7... Nc6 8. Nbd2
{ The first stage of development is complete and Ne5 followed by f2-f4 beckons, although White is also happy to favourably change tack: }
8... b5 9. dxc5 Bxc5 10. e4
{ As we saw back in our introductory section, 'Exchanging on c5', this left White with the superior bishops and a pleasant edge in Palliser-Price, Yeovil 2002, where  10.c4  would also have been pretty effective. }
