[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "8) Rare Setups (Early ...Ne4 & ...Qa5)"]
[Black "Rare Setups: 4...c5 / 5...Ne4"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Nf3
{ With this move, White prepares to enter the Colle setup, and remains flexible with the c-pawn, contrary to the Queen's Gambit. The extra control over e5 rules out lines such as the Albin Countergambit. }
2... Nf6 3. e3 e6 4. Bd3
{ The natural square to develop the bishop, which will very often prove White's most effective attacker. }
4... c5 5. b3 { Preparing the fianchetto of the dark-squared Colle bishop. }
5... Ne4 6. O-O
{ A calm response to Black's early aggression, which presumably angles to cause early trouble along the e1-a5 diagonal. 5...Ne4 is quite rare, but Richard did once face it twice in a simul, so clearly it appeals to a certain type of club player.   Now White can challenge the knight with Bb2 and Nbd2 or even begin to undermine it with a quick c2-c4. }
6... f5 7. c4
{ White moves swiftly to open the position and exploit the lead in development. }
7... Be7 8. cxd5 exd5 9. Bb2
{ White already enjoys a clear advantage. An exchange on c5 @@StartBracket@@or  9...cxd4  10.Nxd4  @@EndBracket@@ is going to leave Black with an IQP, as well as the gash in the kingside caused by ...f5. White will complete development with Nc3 and Rc1 and Black faces a hard time even trying half-sensibly to hold the position together. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "8) Rare Setups (Early ...Ne4 & ...Qa5)"]
[Black "Rare Setups: 4...Ne4 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Nf3
{ With this move, White prepares to enter the Colle setup, and remains flexible with the c-pawn, contrary to the Queen's Gambit. The extra control over e5 rules out lines such as the Albin Countergambit. }
2... Nf6 3. e3 e6 4. Bd3
{ The natural square to develop the bishop, which will very often prove White's most effective attacker. }
4... Ne4 5. Nbd2
{ If Black wants to mix things up with an early ...Ne4, which is a pretty rare approach, he probably does best to do so without any early ...c5, which always allows White the option of a line-opening dxc5.   Here with 5. Nbd2 we break away from our standard Zukertort pattern to immediately challenge the intruder on e4. As an exchange on d2 would merely speed up White's development, Black is likely to set up a Stonewall formation. }
5... f5 6. Ne5
{ With a certain threat and it's not so easy for Black to easily cover the h5- and/or g6-squares. After  6...Nf6  7.c4  c6  8.Nef3  White's firm grip on e5 must supply a pleasant edge @@StartBracket@@b2-b3 and Bb2 may well still follow@@EndBracket@@.   So perhaps Black will deploy the queen and not with  6...Qh4  when  7.O-O  @@StartBracket@@don't fail to spot the threat!@@EndBracket@@ followed by Ndf3 and c2-c4 will gain time for White: }
6... Qf6 7. Nxe4
{ This direct approach is yet to be tried over the board, but we quite like it, denying Black straightforward development. Now  7...dxe4  8.Bc4  will be followed by O-O and f2-f3 or f2-f4 and we're also intending to make good use of the f-pawn after the other recapture: }
7... fxe4 8. Be2 Bd6 9. f4
{ White will either enjoy a fairly easy game after O-O and c2-c4 or the f-file will open: }
9... exf3 10. Nxf3 O-O 11. O-O
{ Thanks to the c2-c4 break and the superior development, White enjoys an edge. Note too that even @@StartFEN@@rnb2rk1/ppp3pp/3bpq2/3p4/3P4/4PN2/PPP1B1PP/R1BQ1RK1 w - - 0 11@@EndFEN@@  12.e4  is a threat, and if  12...dxe4  13.Ng5  . }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "8) Rare Setups (Early ...Ne4 & ...Qa5)"]
[Black "Rare Setups: 4...Ne4 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Nf3
{ With this move, White prepares to enter the Colle setup, and remains flexible with the c-pawn, contrary to the Queen's Gambit. The extra control over e5 rules out lines such as the Albin Countergambit. }
2... Nf6 3. e3 e6 4. Bd3
{ The natural square to develop the bishop, which will very often prove White's most effective attacker. }
4... Ne4 5. Nbd2
{ If Black wants to mix things up with an early ...Ne4, which is a pretty rare approach, he probably does best to do so without any early ...c5, which always allows White the option of a line-opening dxc5.   Here with 5. Nbd2 we break away from our standard Zukertort pattern to immediately challenge the intruder on e4. As an exchange on d2 would merely speed up White's development, Black is likely to set up a Stonewall formation. }
5... f5 6. Ne5
{ With a certain threat and it's not so easy for Black to easily cover the h5- and/or g6-squares. After  6...Nf6  7.c4  c6  8.Nef3  White's firm grip on e5 must supply a pleasant edge @@StartBracket@@b2-b3 and Bb2 may well still follow@@EndBracket@@.   So perhaps Black will deploy the queen and not with  6...Qh4  when  7.O-O  @@StartBracket@@don't fail to spot the threat!@@EndBracket@@ followed by Ndf3 and c2-c4 will gain time for White: }
6... Qf6 7. Nxe4
{ This direct approach is yet to be tried over the board, but we quite like it, denying Black straightforward development. Now  7...dxe4  8.Bc4  will be followed by O-O and f2-f3 or f2-f4 and we're also intending to make good use of the f-pawn after the other recapture: }
7... fxe4 8. Be2 Nd7 9. f4
{ If now  9...exf3  10.Nxf3  followed by O-O when Black's queen may wish she wasn't on the now-open f-file. In any case, O-O and c2-c4 is on the cards, and there's no reason to fear an exchange of knights and/or check: }
9... Nxe5 10. dxe5
{ Unbalancing the pawn structure and gaining a potentially useful kingside majority, with the c2-c4 and f4-f5 breaks two ways to increase the pressure. }
10... Qh4+ 11. g3 Qh3 12. Bf1 { Kicking the queen backwards. } 12... Qf5 13. c4
c6 14. Bd2
{ Black is quite solid here, but we definitely prefer White, who may well be able to expand with g3-g4 and h2-h4 ahead of safely housing the king after Qb3 and O-O-O. }
