{ With this move, White prepares to enter the Colle setup, and remains flexible with the c-pawn, contrary to the Queen's Gambit. The extra control over e5 rules out lines such as the Albin Countergambit. }
2... Nf6 3. e3
{ We've already, of course, covered Black's main third move here,  3...e6  but that copycat advance is by no means forced and there are alternatives here. Note too though that had Black played ...e6 on move one or two, these options would not be available to him, as well as that the alternatives to 3...e6 here are generally seen more at higher levels than in club chess.   Here we must consider:   Chapter 9:  3...Bg4    Chapter 9:  3...Bf5  @@StartBracket@@and  3...c6  @@EndBracket@@   Chapter 10:  3...g6    Chapter 11:  3...c5    Or, in other words, we'll begin with some solid options for Black before looking at how he may attempt to inject some early dynamism into the position. }
