[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "9) 3rd Moves: Bishop Out (3...Bg4 & 3...Bf5)"]
[Black "Bishop Out: 2...c6 / 3...Bf5 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Nf3
{ With this move, White prepares to enter the Colle setup, and remains flexible with the c-pawn, contrary to the Queen's Gambit. The extra control over e5 rules out lines such as the Albin Countergambit. }
2... c6 3. e3
{ While  3.Bf4!?  might be an improved version of a London System, there's no reason to break away from our usual Colle approach.   3...Nf6  4.Nbd2  is likely to follow unless Black prefers to first touch the Slav bishop: }
3... Bf5 4. Nh4
{ Our standard approach against an early bishop development as we aim to run down the bishop-pair at a very early stage. }
4... Be4 5. f3
{ A key follow-up to ensure we will pick up the two bishops and possible here as g2-g3 will secure the knight if needs be. }
5... e6 6. g3 Bg6 7. Nxg6 hxg6 8. Nd2
{ An alternative to a more standard idea in  8.c4  . White hints at c2-c3 followed by e3-e4 and may even be quite radical again on the kingside: }
8... Bd6 9. f4
{ 9.Kf2  is also possible, but please don't fall for  9.Bg2?  Rxh2!  . } 9...
Nf6 10. Bg2
{ Black is very solid, but at least White will now break with c2-c4 or e3-e4, while the king should be pretty safe on g1. }
*

