[White "9) 3rd Moves: Bishop Out (3...Bg4 & 3...Bf5)"]
[Black "Bishop Out: 2...c6 / 3...Bf5 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Nf3
{ With this move, White prepares to enter the Colle setup, and remains flexible with the c-pawn, contrary to the Queen's Gambit. The extra control over e5 rules out lines such as the Albin Countergambit. }
2... c6 3. e3
{ While  3.Bf4!?  might be an improved version of a London System, there's no reason to break away from our usual Colle approach.   3...Nf6  4.Nbd2  is likely to follow unless Black prefers to first touch the Slav bishop: }
3... Bf5 4. Nh4
{ Our standard approach against an early bishop development as we aim to run down the bishop-pair at a very early stage. }
4... Be6 5. Bd3
{ White simply prepares to castle and as well as ideas of Nd2, c2-c3 and e3-e4, might even cause some problems for Black's slightly congested position with a timely f2-f4. }
5... g6 6. O-O Bg7 7. Nd2
{ There's no rush to reinvolve the knight on the rim. Let Black lose time with ...Bf6; Ngf3 if he really wants to. }
7... Nd7 8. c3 Ngf6 9. f4
{ Black had dissuaded e3-e4 due to multiple exchanges, but still remained slightly cramped as White set up a good version of a Stonewall in Terrieux-Buhmann, European Individual Championship, Aix-les-Bains 2011, where f4-f5 was already a threat and White also quite happy to send his queen kingsidewards via e1. }
