[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Nf3
{ With this move, White prepares to enter the Colle setup, and remains flexible with the c-pawn, contrary to the Queen's Gambit. The extra control over e5 rules out lines such as the Albin Countergambit. }
2... c6 3. e3
{ While  3.Bf4!?  might be an improved version of a London System, there's no reason to break away from our usual Colle approach.   3...Nf6  4.Nbd2  is likely to follow unless Black prefers to first touch the Slav bishop: }
3... Bf5 4. Nh4
{ Our standard approach against an early bishop development as we aim to run down the bishop-pair at a very early stage. }
4... Bc8 5. g3
{ Against this extremely rare retreat, you might also tease Black by first repeating moves with  5.Nf3  Bf5  6.Nh4  Bc8  and only then going  7.g3  . Now the knight on h4 is secure and White just wants to go Bg2 and O-O before deciding how to challenge in the centre: }
5... Nf6 6. Bg2 g6 7. O-O
{ The knight may have to return to f3 one day, but at least that will help White to control e5. Meanwhile the good, old Zukertort approach with b2-b3, Bb2, Nbd2 and c2-c4 is likely to follow, aiming to leave Black slightly cramped, in part due to his lack of a great square for the light-squared bishop. }
