[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Nf3
{ With this move, White prepares to enter the Colle setup, and remains flexible with the c-pawn, contrary to the Queen's Gambit. The extra control over e5 rules out lines such as the Albin Countergambit. }
2... Nf6 3. e3
{ We've already, of course, covered Black's main third move here,  3...e6  but that copycat advance is by no means forced and there are alternatives here. Note too though that had Black played ...e6 on move one or two, these options would not be available to him, as well as that the alternatives to 3...e6 here are generally seen more at higher levels than in club chess.   Here we must consider:   Chapter 9:  3...Bg4    Chapter 9:  3...Bf5  @@StartBracket@@and  3...c6  @@EndBracket@@   Chapter 10:  3...g6    Chapter 11:  3...c5    Or, in other words, we'll begin with some solid options for Black before looking at how he may attempt to inject some early dynamism into the position. }
3... Bg4 4. Nbd2
{ A slightly clever move order as we prepare to recapture with the knight on f3 in the event of any exchange there, will safely be able to meet  4...c5?!  with  5.dxc5!  and also tempt Black into advancing his e-pawn then attempting to save his light-squared bishop.   If you don't mind a slow Slav, then by all means prefer  4.c4  c6  5.Nc3   or even  4.h3  Bxf3   4...Bh5  5.g4  Bg6  6.Ne5  is a bit risky for Black - compare with our 4. Nbd2 coverage  5.Qxf3  .   However, do please here avoid  4.Bd3  c5  5.b3  when after  5...c5  Black just has a much improved version of the main lines of the Colle-Zukertort since the pin on the f3-knight rather inhibits White's options. }
4... e6 5. h3
{ Once again we are quick to ask the question of the black bishop. } 5... Bf5
6. g4 Be4 7. g5
{ This is a key point, and problem for Black.  7...Bxf3  8.Qxf3!  @@StartBracket@@to keep Black out of e4@@EndBracket@@  8...Nfd7  9.h4  would now leave White with a handy early space advantage, as well as the bishop-pair, but the alternative is arguably even worse. }
7... Nfd7 8. Nxe4 dxe4 9. Nd2
{ As  9...f5?  10.gxf6  Nxf6  11.Bg2  would be pretty horrible for Black, he must give up e4. }
9... Qxg5 10. Nxe4 Qg6 11. Qf3
{ White enjoys a very pleasant advantage, in part due to the unopposed light-squared bishop which will settle happily on d3 or g2. Moreover, Bd2 and O-O-O will safely house the king and Black's queen may well land up being a bit exposed on g6. }
