[Black "Bishop Out: 2...Nf6 / 3...c6 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Nf3
{ With this move, White prepares to enter the Colle setup, and remains flexible with the c-pawn, contrary to the Queen's Gambit. The extra control over e5 rules out lines such as the Albin Countergambit. }
2... Nf6 3. e3
{ We've already, of course, covered Black's main third move here,  3...e6  but that copycat advance is by no means forced and there are alternatives here. Note too though that had Black played ...e6 on move one or two, these options would not be available to him, as well as that the alternatives to 3...e6 here are generally seen more at higher levels than in club chess.   Here we must consider:   Chapter 9:  3...Bg4    Chapter 9:  3...Bf5  @@StartBracket@@and  3...c6  @@EndBracket@@   Chapter 10:  3...g6    Chapter 11:  3...c5    Or, in other words, we'll begin with some solid options for Black before looking at how he may attempt to inject some early dynamism into the position. }
3... c6 4. Nbd2
{ Our favourite little knight manoeuvre in these lines, aiming to cause problems for Black's Slav bishop whether it goes to g4  @@StartBracket@@  4...Bg4  5.h3  Bh5?!  6.g4!  Bg6  7.Ne5  rather echoes our ideal play against the early Bg4.@@EndBracket@@ or f5.   Incidentally it's also a move which went under the radar and isn't covered in the popular course Lifetime Repertoires: Shankland's Semi-Slav, while in Lifetime Repertoires: Sethuraman's Semi-Slav, which is also generally excellent, we're told that  4.Bd3  is 'is the only independent line' @@StartBracket@@the Indian GM wants to then go  4...Bg4  and also looks at  4.b3  ,  as well as  4.c4  @@EndBracket@@, but 4. Nbd2 very much deserves to exist too. }
4... Bf5 5. Nh4
{ Once again putting the question to the bishop without delay while being quite happy to meet  5...Be4  with  6.f3  . }
5... Bg4 6. f3
{ Now  6...Bh5  7.g4  keeps White nicely on track, but Black is also allowed to be cleverer than to allow that: }
6... Bc8 7. f4
{ Keeping the knight safe @@StartBracket@@it now has f3 available@@EndBracket@@ and we much prefer this to the  7.Bd3  e5!  of Hernandez Onna-Vilela de Acuna, Santa Clara 1999. Black still has to solve the problem of his light-squared bishop and White may simply continue with Bd3 and O-O, and must have a pretty reasonable version of a Stonewall. }
