[Black "Bishop Out: 2...Nf6 / 3...Bf5 #5"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Nf3
{ With this move, White prepares to enter the Colle setup, and remains flexible with the c-pawn, contrary to the Queen's Gambit. The extra control over e5 rules out lines such as the Albin Countergambit. }
2... Nf6 3. e3
{ We've already, of course, covered Black's main third move here,  3...e6  but that copycat advance is by no means forced and there are alternatives here. Note too though that had Black played ...e6 on move one or two, these options would not be available to him, as well as that the alternatives to 3...e6 here are generally seen more at higher levels than in club chess.   Here we must consider:   Chapter 9:  3...Bg4    Chapter 9:  3...Bf5  @@StartBracket@@and  3...c6  @@EndBracket@@   Chapter 10:  3...g6    Chapter 11:  3...c5    Or, in other words, we'll begin with some solid options for Black before looking at how he may attempt to inject some early dynamism into the position. }
3... Bf5 4. Nh4
{ Our favourite policy, but if you don't mind the slow Slav then by all means go  4.c4  c6  and then either Mark Hebden's old favourite  5.cxd5  cxd5  6.Qb3  which Richard has also won a few games with, or the Avrukhesque  5.Nc3  e6  6.Nh4  hunting down the bishop-pair after all. }
4... Bg4 5. f3
{ Necessary if White doesn't want to go in for exchanges with  5.Be2  . We both used to like the idea of  5.Qd3?!  but on checking the lines again it became clear that White just doesn't have a great response then to  5...c5!  when Black becomes much more active than we would like. }
5... Bd7 6. f4
{ White sensibly deals with the threat of ...g5 and while giving his knight a potential path back into the game via f3. Objectively Black must be fine here @@StartBracket@@there's always 4. c4 if you want to be present more of a theoretical challenge, if also less of a surprise@@EndBracket@@, but it's also easy to imagine a club player being a little disorientated by the structural changes and unusual manoeuvring which has already taken place. }
6... c5 7. Be2
{ Directed against any notion of Black deploying his bishop outside the pawn chain by returning with ...Bg4 ahead of going ...e6. White is now set to castle and may then bolster d4 in typical Stonewall fashion with c2-c3. }
7... Nc6 8. O-O Qb6 9. c3
{ This rather unbalanced position wasn't so easy to assess in Onkoud-Maitesian, Rosny sous Bois 2002, but we certainly don't mind White's set-up and the position is far from Slav-like!   Black is fairly active, but White has a big grip on e5 and is all set to go 10. Nd2 and then most likely Nf3-e5, after which Bd3 and a classic kingside attack might well be the order of the day. }
