[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "10) 3rd Moves: Grunfeld Setup (3...g6)"]
[Black "Grunfeld Setup: 4...c6 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Nf3
{ With this move, White prepares to enter the Colle setup, and remains flexible with the c-pawn, contrary to the Queen's Gambit. The extra control over e5 rules out lines such as the Albin Countergambit. }
2... Nf6 3. e3
{ We'll now see what happens if Black goes in for a kingside fianchetto, in Grünfeldesque fashion. This can be a slightly annoying line to face, but is also quite rare. How many players do you know who play both 1...d5 and the Grünfeld as Black? }
3... g6 4. c4
{ Heading towards Grünfeld-type waters @@StartBracket@@don't worry, we won't be transposing to any of the main lines@@EndBracket@@, as here, despite much searching, we just couldn't find an independent, definitely Colle alternative, which we liked. }
4... c6 5. Nc3
{ If surprised by 4. c4 Black may react in such solid fashion, but White should not fear this Schlechter Slav and will now complete kingside development with Be2 and O-O. }
5... Bg7 6. Be2 O-O 7. O-O
{ Black has tried a great many different schemes here, but never found a way to equalise. If Black now plays slowly, White may complete development with b2-b3 and Bb2 or Ba3 @@StartBracket@@for example,  7...e6  8.b3  @@EndBracket@@,  otherwise White should be looking towards an early Qb3, often in conjunction with an exchange on d5. }
7... Nbd7 8. cxd5 cxd5 9. Qb3
{ With Bd2 and Rfc1 on their way, as well as ideas of expansion with a4-a5, White enjoys a definite pull. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "10) 3rd Moves: Grunfeld Setup (3...g6)"]
[Black "Grunfeld Setup: 4...c6 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Nf3
{ With this move, White prepares to enter the Colle setup, and remains flexible with the c-pawn, contrary to the Queen's Gambit. The extra control over e5 rules out lines such as the Albin Countergambit. }
2... Nf6 3. e3
{ We'll now see what happens if Black goes in for a kingside fianchetto, in Grünfeldesque fashion. This can be a slightly annoying line to face, but is also quite rare. How many players do you know who play both 1...d5 and the Grünfeld as Black? }
3... g6 4. c4
{ Heading towards Grünfeld-type waters @@StartBracket@@don't worry, we won't be transposing to any of the main lines@@EndBracket@@, as here, despite much searching, we just couldn't find an independent, definitely Colle alternative, which we liked. }
4... c6 5. Nc3
{ If surprised by 4. c4 Black may react in such solid fashion, but White should not fear this Schlechter Slav and will now complete kingside development with Be2 and O-O. }
5... Bg7 6. Be2 O-O 7. O-O
{ Black has tried a great many different schemes here, but never found a way to equalise. If Black now plays slowly, White may complete development with b2-b3 and Bb2 or Ba3 @@StartBracket@@for example,  7...e6  8.b3  @@EndBracket@@,  otherwise White should be looking towards an early Qb3, often in conjunction with an exchange on d5. }
7... dxc4 8. Bxc4 Bg4 9. Be2
{ A simple retreat to break the pin. Black has bypassed any cxd5 exchanges, but may well now land up having to cede the bishop-pair: }
9... Nbd7 10. h3 Bxf3 11. Bxf3 e5 12. dxe5
{ A straightforward alternative to avoid Black's main idea of  12.d5  e4!?  although that too shouldn't fully equalise. }
12... Nxe5 13. Be2
{ White plays for a long-term advantage with the two bishops. He would now quite like to go Qc2 followed by Bd2 and Rfd1, so Black might remove the queens: }
13... Qxd1 14. Rxd1 Rfd8 15. Rxd8+ Rxd8 16. e4
{ White prepares 17. Be3, which will even be the answer to 16...Nd3, and retains a small but definite pull with the bishop-pair. }
