[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "10) 3rd Moves: Grunfeld Setup (3...g6)"]
[Black "Grunfeld Setup: 4...Bg7 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Nf3
{ With this move, White prepares to enter the Colle setup, and remains flexible with the c-pawn, contrary to the Queen's Gambit. The extra control over e5 rules out lines such as the Albin Countergambit. }
2... Nf6 3. e3
{ We'll now see what happens if Black goes in for a kingside fianchetto, in Grünfeldesque fashion. This can be a slightly annoying line to face, but is also quite rare. How many players do you know who play both 1...d5 and the Grünfeld as Black? }
3... g6 4. c4
{ Heading towards Grünfeld-type waters @@StartBracket@@don't worry, we won't be transposing to any of the main lines@@EndBracket@@, as here, despite much searching, we just couldn't find an independent, definitely Colle alternative, which we liked. }
4... Bg7 5. cxd5
{ The strong German Grandmaster Matthias Blübaum has made good use of this line of late. Now after 5...Nxd5 6.e4 White will have lost a tempo with his e-pawn, but crucially there is no knight on c3 for Black to exchange off, as in the standard Grünfeld. }
5... Nxd5 6. e4
{ Logical expansion and now  6...Nf6  7.Nc3  leaves White with his perfect centre, and if  7...Bg4  8.Be3  so Black usually prefers to head to b6. }
6... Nb6 7. h3
{ Ruling out ...Bg4 and this is actually a rare position in the course where you have a definite choice, since here  7.Be2  is very likely to transpose to our 5...O-O coverage after  7...O-O  8.O-O  or even  7...Bg4  8.Nbd2!  .   Here  7.a4!?  is also a decent option, followed by a4-a5 or  7...a5  8.Bb5+  ,  .   Black should be OK now after  7.Nc3  Bg4  8.Be3  O-O  and ...Nc6, pressuring d4. After 7. h3 White will now be able to develop the queenside with Nc3 and Be3, and the onus is on Black to demonstrate counterplay. }
7... O-O 8. Nc3 Nc6 9. Be3
{ Suddenly White threatens to seize the initiative with @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/ppp1ppbp/1nn3p1/8/3PP3/2N1BN1P/PP3PP1/R2QKB1R w KQ - 0 9@@EndFEN@@  10.d5  and if  10...Na5  11.Bd4!  . }
9... e5 10. d5 Ne7 11. a4
{ With a4-a5 on the way and both Qb3 and d5-d6 very much ideas, White enjoyed the initiative and a promising version of a King's Indian in Blübaum-Kozak, Titled Tuesday Blitz 2021. }
*

