[White "10) 3rd Moves: Grunfeld Setup (3...g6)"]
[Black "Grunfeld Setup: 4...Bg7 #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Nf3
{ With this move, White prepares to enter the Colle setup, and remains flexible with the c-pawn, contrary to the Queen's Gambit. The extra control over e5 rules out lines such as the Albin Countergambit. }
2... Nf6 3. e3
{ We'll now see what happens if Black goes in for a kingside fianchetto, in Grünfeldesque fashion. This can be a slightly annoying line to face, but is also quite rare. How many players do you know who play both 1...d5 and the Grünfeld as Black? }
3... g6 4. c4
{ Heading towards Grünfeld-type waters @@StartBracket@@don't worry, we won't be transposing to any of the main lines@@EndBracket@@, as here, despite much searching, we just couldn't find an independent, definitely Colle alternative, which we liked. }
4... Bg7 5. cxd5
{ The strong German Grandmaster Matthias Blübaum has made good use of this line of late. Now after 5...Nxd5 6.e4 White will have lost a tempo with his e-pawn, but crucially there is no knight on c3 for Black to exchange off, as in the standard Grünfeld. }
5... O-O 6. Be2
{ Here too Blübaum has experimented with  6.h3!?  , but there's no good reason not to prioritise straightforward kingside development. }
6... Nxd5 7. e4
{ Being able to advance so is one of the main points behind the whole 5.cxd5 concept. }
7... Nb6 8. O-O
{ White is now ready to complete development with Be3 and Nc3, although the knight may also find another useful role. Instead,  8.h3  c5  9.d5  e6!  would seem to give Black sufficient counterplay. }
8... Nc6 9. Be3 Bg4 10. Nbd2
{ A key concept. White reinforces the knight on f3 and continues to reap the rewards from not playing an early Nc3. Now 11. d5 may well follow unless Black reacts in the centre. }
10... e5 11. dxe5
{ This seems simpler than the  11.d5  Nd4!  of Tabatabaei-Nazemi, Yerevan 2017. }
11... Nxe5 12. Nxe5 Bxe2 13. Qxe2 Bxe5 14. Rad1
{ With Nc4 threatened and f2-f4 also high on the agenda, White should be slightly for choice. }
