[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "11) 3rd Moves: The Early ...c5 Setup (3...c5)"]
[Black "Early ...c5: 4...Qa5+ #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Nf3
{ With this move, White prepares to enter the Colle setup, and remains flexible with the c-pawn, contrary to the Queen's Gambit. The extra control over e5 rules out lines such as the Albin Countergambit. }
2... Nf6 3. e3 c5 4. dxc5
{ By no means forced, but capturing the en prise pawn takes the fight to Black and is a good test of his ambitious last. He should now aim to regain the pawn with  4...e6  or at least White especially welcomes the alternatives. }
4... Qa5+ 5. Nbd2
{ The simplest way to meet the check as White prepares queenside play: a2-a3 is likely to be a very useful move, ideally followed by b2-b4 and c2-c4. }
5... Nc6 6. a3 g6 7. Be2 Bg7 8. b4
{ White preferred the simple  8.O-O  Qxc5  9.b4  in Blübaum-Vidit, Chess.com @@StartBracket@@rapid@@EndBracket@@ 2022, but here we can hang on to the extra pawn thanks to a fearless follow-up: }
8... Nxb4 9. Nb3
{ There are two double, discovered checks. Gulp! However,  9...Nd3+  10.Kf1  leaves Black without a good follow-up and losing a piece, while we also have matters under control after the other capture: }
9... Nxc2+ 10. Kf1 Qc3 11. Rb1 { Calmly does it and now Bd2 is a huge threat. }
11... Ne4 12. Bd3
{ The knight on c2 is trapped, leaving Black losing a piece for insufficient compensation. Incidentally,  12.Bb5+  Kf8  13.Qxd5  Bf5!  14.g4!  may be even stronger, but is also much messier and harder to play. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "11) 3rd Moves: The Early ...c5 Setup (3...c5)"]
[Black "Early ...c5: 4...Qa5+ #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Nf3
{ With this move, White prepares to enter the Colle setup, and remains flexible with the c-pawn, contrary to the Queen's Gambit. The extra control over e5 rules out lines such as the Albin Countergambit. }
2... Nf6 3. e3 c5 4. dxc5
{ By no means forced, but capturing the en prise pawn takes the fight to Black and is a good test of his ambitious last. He should now aim to regain the pawn with  4...e6  or at least White especially welcomes the alternatives. }
4... Qa5+ 5. Nbd2
{ The simplest way to meet the check as White prepares queenside play: a2-a3 is likely to be a very useful move, ideally followed by b2-b4 and c2-c4. }
5... Nc6 6. a3 Bg4 7. Be2
{ Breaking the pin and simply preparing to castle followed by Nb3 or b2-b4. }
7... Qxc5 8. b4
{ Seizing some very useful space and preparing Bb2, as White did in Guimard-Wade, Barcelona 1946. }
8... Qb6 9. Bb2 e6 10. c4
{ Bronznik's analysis here leaves White somewhat for choice. We may simply castle and prod the bishop with h2-h3, but there are also ideas of c4-c5, b4-b5 and simply exchanging on d5, aiming to leave Black with an IQP. }
