[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Nf3
{ With this move, White prepares to enter the Colle setup, and remains flexible with the c-pawn, contrary to the Queen's Gambit. The extra control over e5 rules out lines such as the Albin Countergambit. }
2... Nf6 3. e3 c5 4. dxc5
{ By no means forced, but capturing the en prise pawn takes the fight to Black and is a good test of his ambitious last. He should now aim to regain the pawn with  4...e6  or at least White especially welcomes the alternatives. }
4... Qa5+ 5. Nbd2
{ The simplest way to meet the check as White prepares queenside play: a2-a3 is likely to be a very useful move, ideally followed by b2-b4 and c2-c4. }
5... Qxc5 6. a3
{ White still wants to expand with b2-b4 and Bb2, thereby taking a grip on the e5-square. }
6... g6 7. c4
{ Here before b2-b4, although there's also nothing wrong with  7.b4  .   Now if  7...dxc4  8.Bxc4  when again 9. b4 and 10. Bb2 will leave White competing for the long diagonal, but that expansion is coming in any case. }
7... Bg7 8. b4 Qc7 9. Bb2
{ Thematic expansion and White already enjoys a very pleasant game with Rc1 next on the agenda. }
9... O-O 10. Rc1 dxc4 11. Bxc4 { With a certain threat. } 11... Qb6 12. Qb3
{ White finds another useful move before castling. Black's position may not look too bad, but he is low on counterplay, his light-squared bishop lacks a great role and f7 may come under direct attack. }
