[White "11) 3rd Moves: The Early ...c5 Setup (3...c5)"]
[Black "Early ...c5: 4...Nc6 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Nf3
{ With this move, White prepares to enter the Colle setup, and remains flexible with the c-pawn, contrary to the Queen's Gambit. The extra control over e5 rules out lines such as the Albin Countergambit. }
2... Nf6 3. e3 c5 4. dxc5
{ By no means forced, but capturing the en prise pawn takes the fight to Black and is a good test of his ambitious last. He should now aim to regain the pawn with  4...e6  or at least White especially welcomes the alternatives. }
4... Nc6 5. c3
{ A change of approach, but there's absolutely no reason here not to hang on to the extra pawn if allowed in reversed Semi-Slav fashion: }
5... e5 6. b4
{ If Black plays slowly White will go Bb2 then Be2 and O-O. Nbd2 is also likely to be a useful move, as may be a2-a3 @@StartBracket@@or even a2-a4@@EndBracket@@, after which White will ideally arrange the c3-c4 break and simply be a pawn to the good. }
6... e4 7. Nd4 Ng4 8. Be2
{ A calm approach against Black's aggression. There's always h2-h3 if needed, as well as O-O, and we also don't need to fear an early deployment of the black queen: }
8... Qh4 9. g3 Qh3 10. Nb5
{ The rook will slide over to f1 if attacked and White's threats @@StartBracket@@Nc7+ and Qxd5 principally@@EndBracket@@ will be much more important than Black picking off h2 with his knight and the exchange on f1. }
