[Black "Early ...c5: 4...Nc6 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Nf3
{ With this move, White prepares to enter the Colle setup, and remains flexible with the c-pawn, contrary to the Queen's Gambit. The extra control over e5 rules out lines such as the Albin Countergambit. }
2... Nf6 3. e3 c5 4. dxc5
{ By no means forced, but capturing the en prise pawn takes the fight to Black and is a good test of his ambitious last. He should now aim to regain the pawn with  4...e6  or at least White especially welcomes the alternatives. }
4... Nc6 5. c3
{ A change of approach, but there's absolutely no reason here not to hang on to the extra pawn if allowed in reversed Semi-Slav fashion: }
5... a5 6. Bb5
{ A key move as White pins the knight to set up the b2-b4 advance after all. }
6... e6 7. b4 Bd7 8. Qb3
{ Blübaum's simple choice, keeping control of  b4  and just intending to complete development with Bb2, O-O and Nbd2. If, though, you prefer something more ambitious then by all means head for a favourable and reversed form of an Abrahams-Noteboom:  8.a4!?  axb4  9.Bxc6  Bxc6  10.cxb4  b6  11.Bb2  bxc5  12.b5  Bb7  13.Nbd2  pitting White's queenside duo against Black's centre. }
8... b6 9. Bxc6 { A powerful exchange. } 9... Bxc6 10. b5 a4 11. Qb2
{ This left Black faced with the miserable choice between losing a piece and allowing White a huge protected passed pawn on c6 in Blübaum-Vardanyan, Titled Tuesday Blitz 2021. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "11) 3rd Moves: The Early ...c5 Setup (3...c5)"]
[Black "Early ...c5: 4...e6 / 5...b6 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Nf3
{ With this move, White prepares to enter the Colle setup, and remains flexible with the c-pawn, contrary to the Queen's Gambit. The extra control over e5 rules out lines such as the Albin Countergambit. }
2... Nf6 3. e3 c5 4. dxc5
{ By no means forced, but capturing the en prise pawn takes the fight to Black and is a good test of his ambitious last. He should now aim to regain the pawn with  4...e6  or at least White especially welcomes the alternatives. }
4... e6 5. b4
{ White's most ambitious choice, holding on to the pawn for now. If, though, you prefer a quieter game, then by all means opt for  5.a3  Bxc5  6.b4  followed by Bb2. }
5... b6 6. cxb6 Bxb4+ 7. c3
{ Once again, the best way of blocking the check and this line briefly became slightly trendy last year, with Levon Aronian the main champion of the black cause. The good news for White is that we're a pawn up, can exchange on a7 and will quickly complete kingside development with Bb5+ and O-O: }
7... Bc5 8. Bb5+ { Developing with tempo as per the plan. } 8... Nbd7 9. bxa7
O-O 10. O-O
{ Our queenside is a little fragmented, but a pawn is a pawn and now White can aim to untangle with both c3-c4 and Nb1-d2-b3. }
10... Rxa7 11. c4
{ This might be a small improvement over the  11.Nbd2  Ba6  from the first clash in this line between Le Quang Liem and Aronian in the 2021 Chessable Masters. As well as Bb2, White may now be able to exchange on d5. }
*

