5... a5 6. c3
{ Needless to say we maintain our extra pawn and this way, not  6.a3?  axb4  .   As we've already noted, @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/1p3ppp/4pn2/p1Pp4/1P6/2P1PN2/P4PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6...Nc6  7.Bb5  would now place Black under some pressure, while the slightly slow  6...Be7  should be met by  7.Nbd2  ,  and if  7...O-O  then  8.a3  followed by Bb2 and Be2. As such, Black is likely to force the issue on the queenside. }
6... axb4 7. cxb4 b6 8. Bb5+
{ Naturally we avoid  8.cxb6?  Bxb4+  and instead speed up development while exchanging a pair of pieces ahead of relying on the a4- and b4-pawn duo. }
8... Bd7 9. Bxd7+ Nbxd7 10. a4
{ White's invariable approach, preparing to pit his queenside majority against Black's centre. }
10... bxc5 11. b5
{ Unlike in the Abrahams-Noteboom proper, the side with the centre doesn't also have the bishop-pair, but we should still show the centre some respect. White would ideally now like to go Bb2, O-O, Nbd2 and Qc2, after which it might be time for some central play or to simply begin to roll away with Bc3 and a4-a5. For his part, Black is now likely to try and force through ...e5 at some point. }
11... g5 12. Bb2
{ We react calmly to Wesley So's shocking idea from 2021. Now  12...g4?  13.Ne5  just weakens the black position, but otherwise we don't want to snaffle the pawn on g5 and see the g-file quickly open. }
12... Bd6 13. Nfd2
{ Yet another interesting idea from Blübaum. The knight moves before it can be kicked and White now threatens to fight back with e3-e4: }
13... Rg8 14. O-O
{ Fearless play and likely an improvement over the  14.e4  Ne5  of Blübaum-Xiong, Chess.com Rapid 2022. Only now do we want to strike back and fast with e3-e4: }
14... g4 15. e4
{ Now Re1 is on the way and White shouldn't be getting mated, whether after  15...Qc7  16.g3  or something more radical: }
15... Rg5 16. exd5
{ Opening up the centre and also very much enabling White to continue his fight-back with f2-f4. }
16... Nxd5 17. g3
{ Now that the black queen's path to h4 wasn't blocked by the knight, 17...Bxh2+ was a big threat. We calmly parry that and in this still rather unclear position we'd rather take White with both Ne4 and Nc4 threatened, while Ra3 may prove useful to help cover the third rank. }
