{ Naturally we avoid  8.cxb6?  Bxb4+  and instead speed up development while exchanging a pair of pieces ahead of relying on the a4- and b4-pawn duo. }
8... Bd7 9. Bxd7+ Nbxd7 10. a4
{ White's invariable approach, preparing to pit his queenside majority against Black's centre. }
10... bxc5 11. b5
{ Unlike in the Abrahams-Noteboom proper, the side with the centre doesn't also have the bishop-pair, but we should still show the centre some respect. White would ideally now like to go Bb2, O-O, Nbd2 and Qc2, after which it might be time for some central play or to simply begin to roll away with Bc3 and a4-a5. For his part, Black is now likely to try and force through ...e5 at some point. }
11... g5 12. Bb2
{ We react calmly to Wesley So's shocking idea from 2021. Now  12...g4?  13.Ne5  just weakens the black position, but otherwise we don't want to snaffle the pawn on g5 and see the g-file quickly open. }
12... Bd6 13. Nfd2
{ Yet another interesting idea from Blübaum. The knight moves before it can be kicked and White now threatens to fight back with e3-e4: }
13... Ne5 14. Qe2 { Keeping Black out of d3 makes sense. } 14... g4 15. f4
{ Fighting back on the kingside and long diagonal and we prefer this here to  15.O-O  and a transposition to Blübaum-Grischuk, Chess.com Rapid 2022. }
15... gxf3 16. Nxf3
{ The position is still far from clear, but White will meet ...Nc4 with Bc3 and should also be able to complete development with Nbd2 and O-O. Don't forget either that the black king is still on e8 and that long term we have two very useful trumps on the queenside. }
