[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "11) 3rd Moves: The Early ...c5 Setup (3...c5)"]
[Black "Early ...c5: 4...e6 / 5...a5 #7"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Nf3
{ With this move, White prepares to enter the Colle setup, and remains flexible with the c-pawn, contrary to the Queen's Gambit. The extra control over e5 rules out lines such as the Albin Countergambit. }
2... Nf6 3. e3 c5 4. dxc5
{ By no means forced, but capturing the en prise pawn takes the fight to Black and is a good test of his ambitious last. He should now aim to regain the pawn with  4...e6  or at least White especially welcomes the alternatives. }
4... e6 5. b4
{ White's most ambitious choice, holding on to the pawn for now. If, though, you prefer a quieter game, then by all means opt for  5.a3  Bxc5  6.b4  followed by Bb2. }
5... a5 6. c3
{ Needless to say we maintain our extra pawn and this way, not  6.a3?  axb4  .   As we've already noted, @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/1p3ppp/4pn2/p1Pp4/1P6/2P1PN2/P4PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6...Nc6  7.Bb5  would now place Black under some pressure, while the slightly slow  6...Be7  should be met by  7.Nbd2  ,  and if  7...O-O  then  8.a3  followed by Bb2 and Be2. As such, Black is likely to force the issue on the queenside. }
6... axb4 7. cxb4 b6 8. Bb5+
{ Naturally we avoid  8.cxb6?  Bxb4+  and instead speed up development while exchanging a pair of pieces ahead of relying on the a4- and b4-pawn duo. }
8... Bd7 9. Bxd7+ Nbxd7 10. a4
{ White's invariable approach, preparing to pit his queenside majority against Black's centre. }
10... bxc5 11. b5
{ Unlike in the Abrahams-Noteboom proper, the side with the centre doesn't also have the bishop-pair, but we should still show the centre some respect. White would ideally now like to go Bb2, O-O, Nbd2 and Qc2, after which it might be time for some central play or to simply begin to roll away with Bc3 and a4-a5. For his part, Black is now likely to try and force through ...e5 at some point. }
11... Ra7 12. O-O
{ Calmly housing the king as White might now bring the bishop to d2, as well as to b2, against what is another highly creative idea from Wesley So. }
12... Qa8 13. Bb2
{ Preparing a gambit and we slightly prefer this to the equally logical  13.Bd2  of Blübaum-So, Opera Euro @@StartBracket@@rapid@@EndBracket@@ 2021. Now if Black doesn't attack a4, White will complete development with Nbd2 and then look to break with e3-e4. }
13... Nb6 14. Qc2
{ White overprotects the bishop on b2 and now has ideas of both Ne5-c6 and Nc3, as well as a timely exchange on f6 to break up Black's kingside. }
14... Nxa4 15. Nc3 Nxb2 16. Qxb2
{ With White about to take over the a-file and the passed b-pawn looking rather useful, White's initiative should supply far more than enough for the pawn. }
