[Black "Bishop Out: 2...Bf5 #4"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Nf3
{ By a huge margin here, Black's most popular move is  2...Nf6  but on the odd occasion an enterprising soul may prefer something else and we should also be ready for all:  Chapter 12:  2...Bg4    Chapter 12:  2...Bf5    Chapter 13:  2...Nc6    Chapter 14:  2...e6    Chapter 14:  2...c5    We'll again aim to meet these in a logical enough manner, while also creating some early obstacles for Black. As we've already seen, he also has  2...c6  when after  3.e3  play is extremely likely to transpose, either back toChapter 9   3...Nf6  ,  3...Bf5  or with  3...e6  4.Bd3  into a position we'll briefly cover inChapter 14. }
2... Bf5 3. c4
{ Freeing a route for the queen while pressuring d5 is the best way of dealing with Black's Baltic Defence, a line which has attracted the support of some pretty decent players on the odd occasion. In keeping with our approach back in Chapter 9, if you want to spring an early counter-surprise then  3.Nh4!?  might very much also be considered. }
3... e6 4. Qb3
{ This must be critical, exploiting the downside to Black's early light-square play and now he must be prepared to gambit the b-pawn. }
4... Nc6 5. Bd2
{ Simple chess. This old favourite of Aleksander Wojtkiewicz's keeps Black out of b4 and a5 while renewing the threat to b7. It's certainly a much better choice than allowing Black too much fun with  5.Qxb7?!  Nb4  .   although if you quite like blocked positions you may also wish to consider  5.c5!?  seizing space. }
5... Rb8 6. e3
{ More simple chess as White frees a path for his light-squared bishop. If you don't mind a Carlsbad structure then  6.Nc3  followed by an exchange on d5 and Bf4 or Bg5 is also a decent approach. }
6... Nf6 7. Nc3
{ Straightforward development is fine when we can meet  7...Na5+  8.Qa4+  and now we have ideas of both Nh4 and cxd5 exd5; Ne5, expanding in the centre while threatening to pin with Bb5. }
7... Be7 8. Nh4 Be4 9. cxd5
{ 9.f3  is also good here.   In both cases White is securing the bishop-pair and  9...Bxd5  10.Nxd5  Nxd5?!  11.Nf3  would now leave Black struggling for a good pawn break. }
9... exd5 10. f3
{ A much more challenging idea than  10.Be2  which was already agreed drawn after  10...h6  in Wojtkiewicz-Gulko, National Open, Las Vegas 1993. Instead, we prefer to remove one of Black's bishops while doubling his pawns in the process. }
10... Bg6 11. Nxg6 hxg6 12. O-O-O
{ Not our usual approach with the king, but a strong one here. White's king should be safe enough on b1, in contrast to g2-g4 and h2-h4 which will be quick to exploit the hook on g6 as soon as Black castles kingside. }
