{ More simple chess as White frees a path for his light-squared bishop. If you don't mind a Carlsbad structure then  6.Nc3  followed by an exchange on d5 and Bf4 or Bg5 is also a decent approach. }
6... Nf6 7. Nc3
{ Straightforward development is fine when we can meet  7...Na5+  8.Qa4+  and now we have ideas of both Nh4 and cxd5 exd5; Ne5, expanding in the centre while threatening to pin with Bb5. }
7... h6 8. Ne2
{ Against this idea from Erwin L'Ami and Mr Chess Explained, Christof Sielecki, which we note is yet to be tested over the board, we quite like this cheeky engine idea, ruling out any notion of ...Na5 or ...Nb4.The queen can always recapture on c4 if needed and the knight will be quite happy on the kingside. }
8... Be7 9. Ng3 Bh7 10. Be2
{ Nothing too terrible is happening to Black, but with O-O and Rac1 on the way, we slightly prefer White's game as just what exactly is the knight doing on c6? }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "12) 2nd Moves: Bishop Out (2...Bg4 or 2...Bf5)"]
[Black "Bishop Out: 2...Bf5 #6"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Nf3
{ By a huge margin here, Black's most popular move is  2...Nf6  but on the odd occasion an enterprising soul may prefer something else and we should also be ready for all:  Chapter 12:  2...Bg4    Chapter 12:  2...Bf5    Chapter 13:  2...Nc6    Chapter 14:  2...e6    Chapter 14:  2...c5    We'll again aim to meet these in a logical enough manner, while also creating some early obstacles for Black. As we've already seen, he also has  2...c6  when after  3.e3  play is extremely likely to transpose, either back toChapter 9   3...Nf6  ,  3...Bf5  or with  3...e6  4.Bd3  into a position we'll briefly cover inChapter 14. }
2... Bf5 3. c4
{ Freeing a route for the queen while pressuring d5 is the best way of dealing with Black's Baltic Defence, a line which has attracted the support of some pretty decent players on the odd occasion. In keeping with our approach back in Chapter 9, if you want to spring an early counter-surprise then  3.Nh4!?  might very much also be considered. }
3... e6 4. Qb3
{ This must be critical, exploiting the downside to Black's early light-square play and now he must be prepared to gambit the b-pawn. }
4... Nc6 5. Bd2
{ Simple chess. This old favourite of Aleksander Wojtkiewicz's keeps Black out of b4 and a5 while renewing the threat to b7. It's certainly a much better choice than allowing Black too much fun with  5.Qxb7?!  Nb4  .   although if you quite like blocked positions you may also wish to consider  5.c5!?  seizing space. }
5... Rb8 6. e3
{ More simple chess as White frees a path for his light-squared bishop. If you don't mind a Carlsbad structure then  6.Nc3  followed by an exchange on d5 and Bf4 or Bg5 is also a decent approach. }
6... a6 7. Nc3
{ White has often preferred  7.a3  here, but there's no need for that just yet.   7...Na5?  8.Qa4  is clearly still not an issue and  7...dxc4  8.Bxc4  b5  9.Be2  just looks quite nice for White with Rc1 on the way. }
7... Nf6 8. Nh4
{ Not for the first time we go after the bishop which is outside the pawn chain. White is quite happy to see  8...Be4  9.f3  or  8...Bg4  9.h3  Bh5  10.g4  ,  but what about if Black reacts on the queenside? }
8... dxc4 9. Bxc4 { With a certain threat. } 9... b5 10. Be2
{ Naturally we retain an important bishop and now want to exchange on f5 @@StartBracket@@or g6@@EndBracket@@ followed by castling and then starting to probe with Bf3 and Rc1. }
10... Ne4 11. Nxf5
{ Naturally and now Black's light squares would be extremely weak after  11...exf5?  12.Nxe4!  fxe4  13.Rc1  . }
11... Nxd2 12. Kxd2
{ A calm recapture, in contrast to  12.Nxg7+?  Bxg7  13.Kxd2  Bxd4!  14.exd4  Qg5+  which gave Black enough for his piece in Wojtkiewicz-Kopec, Manchester NH 2000. }
12... exf5 13. Qd5
{ By no means the only good move, but a simple choice. White would love to see the queens removed, after which he should be able to put his light-square control to good use and gradually build up against Black's weakened queenside. }
13... Qf6 14. g4
{ This powerful pawn break is why we need not fear Black retaining the queens, as surely many a Baltic Defence player would. }
14... fxg4 15. Qe4+
{ White is clearly for choice, since the check is far from easy for Black to deal with. Now, as well as Rac1 and Bxg4, Nd5 is very much an idea too. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "13) 2nd Moves: Chigorin Setup (2...Nc6)"]
[Black "Chigorin Setup: 3...Nf6 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Nf3
{ With this move, White prepares to enter the Colle setup, and remains flexible with the c-pawn, contrary to the Queen's Gambit. The extra control over e5 rules out lines such as the Albin Countergambit. }
2... Nc6 3. e3
{ The Colle works quite well against Black's Chigorin approach as we don't only support the c2-c4 break, but introduce the idea of pinning the knight with Bb5. }
3... Nf6 4. c4
{ This central challenge is a little awkward for Black, since he has no desire to block in his light-squared bishop with  4...e6  when  5.Nc3  possibly followed by Bd3, a2-a3 and Qc2 is a pleasant enough set-up for White, who may also consider seizing space with c4-c5.   Moreover,  4...dxc4  5.Bxc4  is also quite nice for White with Nc3 and e3-e4 on the way or if  5...Bg4?!  6.Qb3  . }
4... Bg4 5. Qb3
{ White has scored extremely well with this move when he's been brave enough to take up the challenge so  5.cxd5  Qxd5  6.Nc3   and @@StartFEN@@r2qkb1r/ppp1pppp/2n2n2/3p4/2PP2b1/4PN2/PP3PPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 1 5@@EndFEN@@  5.Nc3  e6  6.h3  are safer options.   Now @@StartFEN@@r2qkb1r/ppp1pppp/2n2n2/3p4/2PP2b1/1Q2PN2/PP3PPP/RNB1KB1R b KQkq - 2 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Rb8  6.Ne5!  is quite awkward for Black, since White dominates the centre after  6...Nxe5  7.dxe5  Nd7  8.cxd5  Nxe5  9.e4  .   @@StartFEN@@r2qkb1r/ppp1pppp/2n2n2/3p4/2PP2b1/1Q2PN2/PP3PPP/RNB1KB1R b KQkq - 2 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Na5?!  6.Qa4+  Nc6  7.Ne5  is also rather inadvisable, which explains why Black usually now makes the classic unbalancing Chigorin exchange on f3: }
5... e6 6. Qxb7 Nb4 7. Qb5+
{ This is clearly fairly essential and now the queen will scurry back to keep Black out of c2. }
7... c6 8. Qa4 Bf5 9. Na3
{ With Be2, O-O and Bd2 on the way, not to mention Ne5, Black shouldn't have enough for his pawn. }
*

