[White "13) 2nd Moves: Chigorin Setup (2...Nc6)"]
[Black "Chigorin Setup: 3...Bg4 #4"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Nf3
{ With this move, White prepares to enter the Colle setup, and remains flexible with the c-pawn, contrary to the Queen's Gambit. The extra control over e5 rules out lines such as the Albin Countergambit. }
2... Nc6 3. e3
{ The Colle works quite well against Black's Chigorin approach as we don't only support the c2-c4 break, but introduce the idea of pinning the knight with Bb5. }
3... Bg4 4. Bb5
{ 4.Nbd2!?  and  4.c4  are also good moves, but we rather like this pinning ploy, fighting for control of e5 and simply intending to challenge the bishop on g4 with h2-h3. In recent years this simple approach has begun to attract the attention of some strong players, including even Anish Giri. }
4... e6 5. Nbd2
{ White prepares to recapture on f3 with the knight in the event of any h3 Bxf3 exchange and also offers support to the c2-c4 advance. He is actually quite spoilt for choice here with both  5.h3  and  5.Bxc6+!?  bxc6  6.c4  also quite tempting.   Indeed, we'll definitely now meet  5...a6?!  with  6.Bxc6+  bxc6  7.c4  followed by Qa4  . }
5... Bd6 6. c4
{ White prepares to increase the force of the pin with Qa4 and also has ideas now of c4-c5. Giri preferred  6.h3  Bh5  7.c4  dxc4  8.Bxc6+  bxc6  9.Qa4  which is clearly very similar, but if anything Black's bishop is slightly more exposed on g4 than h5. }
6... dxc4 7. Bxc6+ { Not missing the chance to smash up Black's pawns. } 7...
bxc6 8. Qa4
{ White will clearly regain his pawn and should be doing so with a pleasant edge to boot. }
8... Ne7 9. Qxc4 O-O 10. O-O
{ Thanks to White's control of c5 and e5, Black was struggling to free his position and was slightly worse in Bronstein-Aronson, USSR Championship, Moscow 1957, where White was quick to powerfully expand with a2-a3 and b2-b4. }
