[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "14) 2nd Moves: Rare Tries (2...e6 & 2...c5)"]
[Black "Rare 2nd Moves: 2...e6 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Nf3
{ With this move, White prepares to enter the Colle setup, and remains flexible with the c-pawn, contrary to the Queen's Gambit. The extra control over e5 rules out lines such as the Albin Countergambit. }
2... e6 3. e3
{ Here we are certainly well placed to continue in true Colle style, not least because Black's usual choice here is  3...Nf6  when we're back in the Colle-Zukertort after  4.Bd3  . }
3... c6 4. Bd3
{ Straightforward development and now it's possible that we may even @@StartBracket@@on a good day@@EndBracket@@ be able break with e3-e4, as well as to carry out our favourite queenside fianchetto. Here Black has two main ways of fighting for control of e4: }
4... Nf6 5. b3
{ Black's set-up makes sense if White has a pawn on c4, but here we don't, so such a Semi-Slav-type approach looks a little strange. It's by no means unknown at lower levels though, where White often just continues with Bb2, O-O, Nbd2 and Ne5, while Black lands up a tempo down on a normal position by pushing ...c5 after all: }
5... Nbd7 6. Bb2 Bd6 7. Ne5
{ With Black quite passive, White is already able to advance so. Now ...Qc7 will be met by f2-f4 and in any case O-O, Nbd2 and f2-f4 are on their way, with an improved version of the standard Colle-Zukertort for White. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "14) 2nd Moves: Rare Tries (2...e6 & 2...c5)"]
[Black "Rare 2nd Moves: 2...e6 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Nf3
{ With this move, White prepares to enter the Colle setup, and remains flexible with the c-pawn, contrary to the Queen's Gambit. The extra control over e5 rules out lines such as the Albin Countergambit. }
2... e6 3. e3
{ Here we are certainly well placed to continue in true Colle style, not least because Black's usual choice here is  3...Nf6  when we're back in the Colle-Zukertort after  4.Bd3  . }
3... c6 4. Bd3
{ Straightforward development and now it's possible that we may even @@StartBracket@@on a good day@@EndBracket@@ be able break with e3-e4, as well as to carry out our favourite queenside fianchetto. Here Black has two main ways of fighting for control of e4: }
4... f5 5. c4
{ With Black having clamped down on e4, White switches approach and begins to play in both the centre and on the queenside. }
5... Nf6 6. O-O
{ Housing the king before going b2-b3 makes sense to reduce Black's options, while if you don't mind being aggressive and uncompromising yourself, do feel free to consider too  6.Nc3  Bd6  7.h3!?  looking to get in a quick g2-g4. }
6... Bd6 7. b3
{ For once this is not played to place the dark-squared bishop on b2, but rather to go Ba3, as we aim to weaken Black's control of the dark squares, not least e5. }
7... Qe7 8. Bb2 O-O 9. Qc1
{ White is determined to force through Ba3 after all, following which we'll be happy to exchange the queens too, if allowed, to further lessen the dynamic aspects of Black's position which compensate for the holes in his structure. }
9... Nbd7 10. Ba3 Ne4 11. Bxd6 Qxd6 12. Nc3
{ Here this might be even stronger than  12.Qa3  White will now improve this knight with Ne2-f4, while Qb2 will increase our hold on e5. If Black fianchettoes on the queenside, White can play down the c-file, while if the knight heads from d7 to f6 we will, of course, very much invade on e5. }
