1. d4 d5 2. Nf3
{ With this move, White prepares to enter the Colle setup, and remains flexible with the c-pawn, contrary to the Queen's Gambit. The extra control over e5 rules out lines such as the Albin Countergambit. }
2... c5 3. dxc5
{ We meet Black's ambitious second move head on, taking the pawn without delay, just as we did inChapter 11. Now  3...Nf6  4.e3  would, of course, transpose to those lines, but Black is more likely to play to immediately regain the pawn. }
3... Qa5+ 4. Nbd2
{ The simplest approach, although  4.Nc3!?  is also quite promising, obtaining active piece play after  4...e6  5.e4!  .   and  4...Nf6  5.Nd4  Qxc5  6.Nb3  .   After  4.Nbd2  play is likely to once again head back into the realm ofChapter 11 after  4...Nf6  5.a3  Qxc5  6.e3  unless Black prefers to try and recapture on c5 with his bishop. }
4... e6 5. c3
{ The right pawn to push here, seeing that  5.a3  can be safely met by  5...Bxc5  . Now, though, the bishop capture would, of course, blunder a piece to  6.b4  . }
5... Qxc5 6. e4
{ The position resembles a French Tarrasch where Black has misplaced his queen. Clearly  6...dxe4  7.Nxe4  will gain further time and meanwhile White will simply continue development with Bd3 and O-O, after which he might look to open the position with exd5 or head for a favourable type of French by closing the centre with e4-e5. }
