1. d4 d5 2. Nf3
{ With this move, White prepares to enter the Colle setup, and remains flexible with the c-pawn, contrary to the Queen's Gambit. The extra control over e5 rules out lines such as the Albin Countergambit. }
2... c5 3. dxc5
{ We meet Black's ambitious second move head on, taking the pawn without delay, just as we did inChapter 11. Now  3...Nf6  4.e3  would, of course, transpose to those lines, but Black is more likely to play to immediately regain the pawn. }
3... e6 4. e4
{ Even here this advance is a pretty decent one, if clearly far from forced, and now Black should really be prepared to take on an IQP. }
4... Bxc5 5. exd5
{ Simple chess as we inflict an IQP on Black. At least he can retain the queens here and we now reach a position which might even also come about from a French Exchange move order, @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  e6  2.d4  d5  3.exd5  exd5  and then  4.Nf3  c5!?  5.dxc5  Bxc5  . }
