5... Ne4 6. c4
{ Seizing space so while freeing a square for the queen on c2 looks like White's best way of dealing with the early invasion on e4, an unusual approach, if one once tried by the great Capablanca. }
6... Be7 7. Nbd2
{ Now  7...Nxd2  8.Bxd2  followed by e3-e4 @@StartBracket@@Legky-Boehme, Kiel 2022@@EndBracket@@ or  8...f5?!  9.Re1  and then e3-e4 would give White a very pleasant early space advantage, so here too Black may try and hang on to e4. }
7... f5 8. Qc2
{ Clearly  8...d5?  9.cxd5  exd5  10.Ne5  followed by f2-f3 would be positionally very bad news for Black, and meanwhile White need not fear doubled pawns. }
8... Nxd2 9. Bxd2 Bxf3 10. gxf3
{ The king will be quite safe on h1 and White enjoys the bishop-pair. He shouldn't hurry with e3-e4 and weaken d4, but might regroup with f3-f4 @@StartBracket@@which also rules out any notion of ...f4@@EndBracket@@, Be2 and Bf3 or simply expand on the queenside, beginning with b2-b4. }
