[Black "Queen's Indian Setup: 3...b6 / 5...Ne4 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 e6 3. e3
{ Against Black's classically-oriented second move we can very much continue with our favourite Colle approach. Now Black has three main moves:  3...b6  ,  3...c5  and  3...d5  . The first two can very easily transpose into each other; the last one we are, of course, already rather familiar with.   In any case, White's plan is Bd3, O-O @@StartBracket@@a slightly more accurate move order than b2-b3 first here, for reasons we'll see@@EndBracket@@ , and only then the queenside fianchetto. }
3... b6 4. Bd3 Bb7 5. O-O
{ Castling before going b2-b3 makes sense here, as we bypass any early ...Bb4+ possibilities and are also well placed to deal with a quick ...Ne4. }
5... Ne4 6. c4
{ Seizing space so while freeing a square for the queen on c2 looks like White's best way of dealing with the early invasion on e4, an unusual approach, if one once tried by the great Capablanca. }
6... d5 7. cxd5
{ White immediately exchanges in the centre ahead of both undermining e4 and beginning to eye c7 with Nc3 and Qc2. }
7... exd5 8. Nc3 Nd7 9. Qc2
{ Now  9...Nxc3  10.bxc3  would leave White with a nice centre and both the c3-c4 and e3-e4 pawn breaks high on the agenda, but better that for Black than a Stonewall approach: }
9... f5 10. Ne5
{ Hopping straight into the hole to threaten Bb5, as well as simply f2-f3. As an exchange of knights on e5 would leave White with a big pawn there, he was already clearly for choice in Rashkovsky-Sandhu, Oberwart 2002. }
*

