1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 e6 3. e3
{ Against Black's classically-oriented second move we can very much continue with our favourite Colle approach. Now Black has three main moves:  3...b6  ,  3...c5  and  3...d5  . The first two can very easily transpose into each other; the last one we are, of course, already rather familiar with.   In any case, White's plan is Bd3, O-O @@StartBracket@@a slightly more accurate move order than b2-b3 first here, for reasons we'll see@@EndBracket@@ , and only then the queenside fianchetto. }
3... b6 4. Bd3 Bb7 5. O-O
{ Castling before going b2-b3 makes sense here, as we bypass any early ...Bb4+ possibilities and are also well placed to deal with a quick ...Ne4. }
5... c5 6. b3
{ Zukertort play after all, although we should point out that Richard has also done well in practice with the sharper  6.c4!?  followed by Nc3, transposing to a line of the e3 Queen's Indian.   Again,  6...d5  7.Bb2  would now take us back into familiar waters, while  @@StartFEN@@rn1qkb1r/pb1p1ppp/1p2pn2/2p5/3P4/1P1BPN2/P1P2PPP/RNBQ1RK1 b kq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6...cxd4  7.exd4  Be7  8.Bb2  O-O  9.Nbd2  leads intoChapter 16. Black can also maintain the tension while continuing development. }
6... Be7 7. Bb2
{ Naturally we complete the fianchetto ahead of finishing development with Nbd2, which was, incidentally, a favourite set-up here of Edgard Colle's himself. Yes, the man who liked to set up with c2-c3 and Nbd2 preferred a Zukertort approach when Black refrained from an early ... d5. }
7... cxd4 8. exd4 Nd5 9. c4
{ A powerful response to Black's overly ambitious play. Now  9...Nb4  10.Be2  will preserve the bishop and leave Black's knights looking silly, but after the other leap we don't even have to retreat to c2. }
9... Nf4 10. d5
{ White wastes no time in unfurling the Zukertort bishop and is quite happy to swap the bishop-pair  @@StartBracket@@  10...Nxd3  11.Qxd3  @@EndBracket@@  in return for a cramping bridgehead on d5, one which does Black's queenside pieces no favours. Moreover, only a foolhardy opponent would be tempted to take on d5: }
10... exd5 11. cxd5
{ Now the tactics favour White in the event of  11...Nxd5?  12.Be4  Ne3  13.Qd4!  ,  with both black rooks potential targets and the other capture isn't much better. }
11... Bxd5 12. Bxg7 { Fearless and strong play. } 12... Rg8 13. Be5
{ The point. Now  13...Nxg2  14.Bg3  will leave the white king safe enough, while eyeing not just h7, as seizing a powerful initiative with Nc3 and @@StartBracket@@after ...Nf4@@EndBracket@@ Re1, which also frees a square for the king on f1. Much better that though for Black than the other capture. }
13... Rxg2+ 14. Kh1 Rg4 15. Bf5 Rg5 16. Nc3
{ White is quite happy to exchange light-squared bishops as it quickly becomes a massacre thanks to Black's lack of coordination, underdeveloped queenside and king still on e8. }
