7... O-O 8. Nbd2
{ Completing the first stage of White's development.  Now  8...d5  9.Ne5  is well-known to us @@StartBracket@@  9...Nc6  10.f4  would then beChapter 2 and  9...Nbd7  10.Qe2  the realm ofChapter 6.  We will now look at the two main ways Black can react:    Chapter 16:  @@StartFEN@@rn1q1rk1/pb1pbppp/1p2pn2/2p5/3P4/1P1BPN2/PBPN1PPP/R2Q1RK1 b - - 4 8@@EndFEN@@  8...cxd4  9.exd4    Chapter 17:  @@StartFEN@@rn1q1rk1/pb1pbppp/1p2pn2/2p5/3P4/1P1BPN2/PBPN1PPP/R2Q1RK1 b - - 4 8@@EndFEN@@  8...Nc6  &  @@StartFEN@@rn1q1rk1/pb1pbppp/1p2pn2/2p5/3P4/1P1BPN2/PBPN1PPP/R2Q1RK1 b - - 4 8@@EndFEN@@  8...d6  Releasing the tension is pretty popular in practice and often the exchange has already been made by now, sometimes as far back as move four, but set-ups where Black holds back on the central exchange are also quite valid, as we'll now see.   Incidentally, were Black now to play something slow, White might well change the nature of the struggle with c2-c4 or make a couple of useful moves in a2-a3 @@StartBracket@@it's pretty useful to control b4@@EndBracket@@ and Qe2. }
