[White "16) Queen's Indian Setup with ...cxd4"]
[Black "Queen's Indian Setup: 9...Nc6 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6
{ A very common opening move against 1. d4, after which very often Black intends the King's Indian Defense. In this case, we recommend other approaches rather than the Colle, such as the Torre with Bg5 or reverting to some d4-c4 mainlines.   We will, however, be able to play the Colle comfortably against the Queen's Indian Setup, the topic of these next chapters. }
2. Nf3 e6 3. e3
{ Now that e6 has been committed, a good King's Indian is out of the question for Black, meaning we are alright to continue in Colle fashion with e3. }
3... b6 { The start of the Queen's Indian Setup. } 4. Bd3 Bb7 5. O-O c5 6. b3
Be7 7. Bb2 O-O 8. Nbd2 { We have completed our Zukertort formation. } 8... cxd4
9. exd4
{ Now  9...d5  10.Ne5  would be familiar fare for us, but Black can fight against such a concept with his two main moves here,  9...d6  and  9...Nc6  . }
9... Nc6 10. a3
{ Adhering to our favourite policy for the sake of simplicity, although here  10.Re1  is also possible. Now  @@StartFEN@@r2q1rk1/pb1pbppp/1pn1pn2/8/3P4/PP1B1N2/1BPN1PPP/R2Q1RK1 b - - 0 10@@EndFEN@@  10...Nd5  11.Re1  again doesn't make a huge amount of sense for Black and in any case Re1 as well as c2-c4 are high on White's agenda.   We'll now see Julian Hodgson no less sitting behind the white pieces after @@StartFEN@@r2q1rk1/pb1pbppp/1pn1pn2/8/3P4/PP1B1N2/1BPN1PPP/R2Q1RK1 b - - 0 10@@EndFEN@@  10...Qc7  11.Re1  inHodgson-Jackelen, German Bundesliga 2001, but Black more usually prefers to begin a standard kingside regrouping. }
10... Re8 11. Re1
{ The rook is unlikely to find a better post and clearly it's going to take Black a while to arrange any ...e5 break here. }
11... Rc8 12. Qe2
{ A useful enough move, giving White the option of Ne4 and, yes, we are still allowed to go after h7 in this line! }
12... Nd5 13. g3 Nf6 14. Rad1
{ Centralisation. White is fairly happy for now to avoid too complex a central situation after  14.c4  d5  but  14.Rac1  Bf8  15.Qf1!?  was a creative alternative in Meulders-Langeweg, Amsterdam 1986. }
14... Bf8 15. Ne4
{ White plays to provoke a weakness in turn and  15...Nxe4  16.Qxe4  g6  17.d5!  begins to look a little awkward for Black. Meanwhile there is actually a threat. }
15... a6 16. d5 exd5 17. Nxf6+ gxf6 18. Qf1
{ Talk about a wrecked kingside for Black, and one which Qh3 will be quick to exploit. }
*

