[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6
{ A very common opening move against 1. d4, after which very often Black intends the King's Indian Defense. In this case, we recommend other approaches rather than the Colle, such as the Torre with Bg5 or reverting to some d4-c4 mainlines.   We will, however, be able to play the Colle comfortably against the Queen's Indian Setup, the topic of these next chapters. }
2. Nf3 e6 3. e3
{ Now that e6 has been committed, a good King's Indian is out of the question for Black, meaning we are alright to continue in Colle fashion with e3. }
3... b6 { The start of the Queen's Indian Setup. } 4. Bd3 Bb7 5. O-O c5 6. b3
Be7 7. Bb2 O-O 8. Nbd2 { We have completed our Zukertort formation. } 8... cxd4
9. exd4
{ Now  9...d5  10.Ne5  would be familiar fare for us, but Black can fight against such a concept with his two main moves here,  9...d6  and  9...Nc6  . }
9... d6 10. c4
{ Useful expansion, challenging for control of d5, with Black's queen's knight likely on the way to d7.  10.Re1  Nbd7  11.Qe2?!  is one to avoid due to  11...Nd5  when the threat of ...Nf4 is a bit annoying, although here  Simon's @@StartFEN@@r2q1rk1/pb1nbppp/1p1ppn2/8/3P4/1P1B1N2/PBPN1PPP/R2QR1K1 w - - 2 11@@EndFEN@@  11.Nf1!?  is an idea, sending the knight over to the kingside. }
10... Nbd7 11. Re1
{ Ever a useful move in this line, ensuring that Black won't easily get ...e5 in, while offering support to any ...d5; Ne5 raid. White also clears a path to regroup with Nf1-g3 at some stage and Black usually now follows suit with his own king's rook. }
11... d5 12. Rc1
{ Maintaining the tension and offering additional support to c4 in the event of any ...dxc4; bxc4 exchange. }
12... Rc8 13. a3
{ In a strategically complex position, this is a useful move to keep Black out of b4. White simply intends to continue with Qe2 and look to set up a battery with Bb1 and Qd3 and/or will look to advance with Ne5, especially in the event of ...Bd6. }
