[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "17) Queen's Indian Setup without ...cxd4"]
[Black "Queen's Indian Setup: 8...d6 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 e6 3. e3 b6 4. Bd3 Bb7 5. O-O c5 6. b3 Be7 7. Bb2 O-O 8. Nbd2
d6 9. c4
{ Logical expansion, fighting for control of the central squares and now  9...cxd4  10.exd4  would, of course, take play back intoChapter 16. }
9... Nbd7 10. a3
{ White's main moves are  10.Qe2  ,  10.Re1  and  10.Rc1  and if you don't mind a Hedgehog structure by all means play one of those and then push forwards with e3-e4, which is likely to be met by ...cxd4; Nxd4.   We quite like the text, however, and have already seen inChapter 16 that White might expand with b3-b4 and now  10...cxd4  11.exd4  d5  12.Re1  Rc8  13.Rc1  would return play to a position we considered there. Let's see here what might happen if Black instead retains the tension. }
10... e5 11. d5
{ As taking three times on e5 would drop the bishop on d3, White instead seizes space and this should be a good version of a Czech Benoni for us. The bishop on b2 is better placed than the one on b7 and while b3-b4 is very much an idea, White can also aim for another pawn break too in f2-f4: }
11... g6 12. Ne1 Ne8 13. e4
{ Logical expansion and all is now set for f2-f4 or if ...Bg5 then g2-g3. White can even meet  13...f5  with  14.f4  although we should point out that the engines prefer  14.exf5!?  gxf5  15.Kh1  followed by opening lines to the detriment of the black king with g2-g4!. }
