1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 e6 3. e3 b6 4. Bd3 Bb7 5. O-O c5 6. b3 Be7 7. Bb2 O-O 8. Nbd2
d6 9. c4
{ Logical expansion, fighting for control of the central squares and now  9...cxd4  10.exd4  would, of course, take play back intoChapter 16. }
9... Nbd7 10. a3
{ White's main moves are  10.Qe2  ,  10.Re1  and  10.Rc1  and if you don't mind a Hedgehog structure by all means play one of those and then push forwards with e3-e4, which is likely to be met by ...cxd4; Nxd4.   We quite like the text, however, and have already seen inChapter 16 that White might expand with b3-b4 and now  10...cxd4  11.exd4  d5  12.Re1  Rc8  13.Rc1  would return play to a position we considered there. Let's see here what might happen if Black instead retains the tension. }
10... Qc7 11. Rc1
{ Placing the rook vis-à-vis the enemy queen is rarely a bad policy, as we've seen on several occasions in this course. }
11... a6 12. b4
{ White clears the b3-square for the queen and now that we control c5 it may soon be time to head for a space advantage and Hedgehog structure with e4 cxd4; Nxd4, after which one good plan is to try and arrange a4-a5, another the more aggressive f2-f4 and all the while ensuring that Black can't easily break with ...b5 or d5. For example,  12...Rfe8  13.e4!?  cxd4  14.Nxd4  Rac8  15.Qb3  Black isn't about to break with ...b5 or ...d5 and f2-f4 will follow.   As White also has the extra space, it will make sense to meet any ... Ne5 leap with Bb1, keeping pieces on ahead of hitting the knight with f2-f4. }
