[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 e6 3. e3 b6 4. Bd3 Bb7 5. O-O c5 6. b3 Be7 7. Bb2 O-O 8. Nbd2
d6 9. c4
{ Logical expansion, fighting for control of the central squares and now  9...cxd4  10.exd4  would, of course, take play back intoChapter 16. }
9... Nbd7 10. a3
{ White's main moves are  10.Qe2  ,  10.Re1  and  10.Rc1  and if you don't mind a Hedgehog structure by all means play one of those and then push forwards with e3-e4, which is likely to be met by ...cxd4; Nxd4.   We quite like the text, however, and have already seen inChapter 16 that White might expand with b3-b4 and now  10...cxd4  11.exd4  d5  12.Re1  Rc8  13.Rc1  would return play to a position we considered there. Let's see here what might happen if Black instead retains the tension. }
10... Re8 11. b4
{ This has been pretty rare here, but we can't see anything wrong with gaining space so, asking Black exactly how he intends to untangle his slightly cramped position. Qb3 may follow and then e3-e4 or you might first deploy the rooks with, say, Rac1 and Rfd1.   There are also ideas of a timely exchange on c5, especially if the black rook steps away from the a-file: }
11... Rc8 12. dxc5
{ Changing the structure. White can very much also go  12.Qb3  here, but  12.e4?!  cxd4  was a bit awkward in Gayun-Y.Sokolov, Vinnytsia 2016, since  13.Nxd4  Ne5  would hit both c4 and the bishop on d3. Instead, we play to seize space with b4-b5 and expand on the queenside while also looking to use the e4-square: }
12... dxc5 13. b5 Nf8 14. Qc2
{ White is now all set to expand with a3-a4-a5, all the while as Black remains slightly low on counterplay. Another decent plan is Rfd1 and Ne4, looking to exchange off Black's best piece on b7 with Be4. }
