1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 e6 3. e3 b6 4. Bd3 Bb7 5. O-O c5 6. b3 Be7 7. Bb2 O-O 8. Nbd2
Nc6 9. a3
{ Our favourite and simple antidote to the black knight appearing on c6, keeping it out of b4. Now Black often continues on the queenside with  9...Rc8  ,  but that is by no means forced and, of course,  9...cxd4  10.exd4  would return play to the realm ofChapter 16. }
9... d5 10. Qe2
{ This seems the most accurate move  @@StartBracket@@  10.Ne5  Nxe5  11.dxe5  Ne4  should equalise@@EndBracket@@, stepping off the d-file and looking to transpose back intoChapter 2 with a timely Ne5 and f2-f4. }
10... Rc8 11. Ne5
{ Now, for instance,  11...Qc7  12.f4  would take play back into a position we considered inChapter 2. Black's only real independent option is to exchange on e5 when we'll get to see why the queen went to e2: }
11... Nxe5 12. dxe5 Ne4 13. Bxe4
{ Not for the first time we see this exchange, eyeing the hole on d6. } 13...
dxe4 14. Rfd1
{ White will continue with Qg4, not only attacking e4, but also working well in conjunction with a Nc4-d6 raid, since ...Bxd6; exd6 would, of course, but open up the Zukertort bishop and threaten mate. }
