1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 e6 3. e3 b6 4. Bd3 Bb7 5. O-O c5 6. b3 Be7 7. Bb2 O-O 8. Nbd2
Nc6 9. a3
{ Our favourite and simple antidote to the black knight appearing on c6, keeping it out of b4. Now Black often continues on the queenside with  9...Rc8  ,  but that is by no means forced and, of course,  9...cxd4  10.exd4  would return play to the realm ofChapter 16. }
9... d6 10. c4
{ The combination of ...Nc6 and ...d6 may look a little strange, but Black's position is quite solid. Against it, we once more seize space, although here, of course, it won't be so easy to follow up with b3-b4. }
10... Qc7 11. Rc1
{ It's hard to believe there's a better square for this rook and now Qe2 and Rfd1 will complete development. }
11... Rac8 12. Qe2 Rfd8 13. Rfd1
{ Thus far we've held back on e3-e4  @@StartBracket@@  13.e4  cxd4  14.Nxd4  Nxd4  15.Bxd4  Nd7  should be fine for Black@@EndBracket@@  waiting to see what Black is up to.   @@StartFEN@@2rr2k1/pbq1bppp/1pnppn2/2p5/2PP4/PP1BPN2/1B1NQPPP/2RR2K1 b - - 6 13@@EndFEN@@  13...cxd4  14.exd4  would free our position and allow us to seize more useful space with b3-b4,  13...e5?!  14.d5  also makes little sense for Black @@StartBracket@@White might well seize a rapid initiative with Ng5-e4 and f2-f4@@EndBracket@@, and the other central reaction also has its downsides. }
13... d5 14. cxd5
{ Suddenly ideas of b3-b4 are very much on the agenda, exploiting the line-up of rook and queen on the c-file: }
14... exd5 15. dxc5 bxc5 16. b4
{ A powerful break. Now  16...c4  17.Bf5  would see White both taking control and seizing the initiative @@StartBracket@@e3-e4 may well follow@@EndBracket@@, but otherwise Black will suffer somewhat with an IQP. }
16... cxb4 17. axb4 Bxb4 18. Bxf6
{ Destroying the black kingside is the real point of the pawn sacrifice. }
18... gxf6 19. Nh4
{ With Qh5 threatened and the knight en route to f5, it's extremely hard to imagine Black surviving. }
