1. d4
{ We're now almost at the end of this course, having seen how the Colle-Zukertort can pack a punch against both 1...d5 and @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/3P4/8/PPP1PPPP/RNBQKBNR b KQkq d3 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1...Nf6  2.Nf3  e6  .   So what else might you wish to have covered to be able to open 1. d4 with confidence? When Black can pair a fianchettoed king's bishop with going ...d6 and ...e5, a set-up with bishops on d3 and b2 doesn't make a huge amount of sense.   As such, we can't really recommend meeting the King's Indian with a Colle approach. Instead, after  @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/3P4/8/PPP1PPPP/RNBQKBNR b KQkq d3 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1...Nf6  2.Nf3  g6  why not consider  3.Bg5  and a Torre approach if you quite like to retain control or maybe  3.Nc3  and the Barry Attack if you want something more aggressive?   Likewise, after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/3P4/8/PPP1PPPP/RNBQKBNR b KQkq d3 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1...g6  we would really recommend that you tackle the Pirc/Modern complex with  2.e4  Bg7  3.Nc3  d6  and then go for control with  4.Nf3  and a classical Be2 approach or be a bit more aggressive with  4.Be3  followed by Qd2.   Here there's also  4.Be2!?  intending a quick h2-h4, as recommended on the second part of a certain Grandmaster Gambits: 1.e4 repertoire.   It shouldn't be too hard to find something you're happy with after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/3P4/8/PPP1PPPP/RNBQKBNR b KQkq d3 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1...b6  2.e4  Bb7  3.Nc3  e6  4.Bd3  followed by 5. Nge2 is one good set-up;  3.Bd3  e6  4.Nf3  and c2-c3 another if a more common one - or amongst the wide array of choice that White has against the Dutch, with  @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/3P4/8/PPP1PPPP/RNBQKBNR b KQkq d3 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1...f5  2.Nc3  one decent way to mix aggression with control, and if  2...Nf6  3.Bg5  or  2...d5  3.Bf4  .   And, yes, @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/3P4/8/PPP1PPPP/RNBQKBNR b KQkq d3 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1...e5?  2.dxe5  is just an extra pawn or a huge initiative after  2...Nc6  3.Nf3  Qe7  4.Bf4  Qb4+  5.Bd2  Qxb2  6.Nc3!   @@StartBracket@@and not  6.Bc3?  Bb4  ,  Black's dream Englund trap@@EndBracket@@  6...Bb4  7.Rb1  Qa3  8.Rb3  .   Black also has various Benoni tries, with many Colle players happy to meet @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/3P4/8/PPP1PPPP/RNBQKBNR b KQkq d3 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1...c5  with  2.d5  followed by Nc3 and e2-e4, claiming a space advantage, or with  @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/3P4/8/PPP1PPPP/RNBQKBNR b KQkq d3 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1...Nf6  2.Nf3  c5  3.d5  . In this latter move order,  3.e3  is very much also possible when  3...Nc6  4.Bd3  is going to lead into either Colle Queen's Indian waters:  4...b6  5.O-O  or a Colle-Zukertort with  @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pp1ppppp/2n2n2/2p5/3P4/3BPN2/PPP2PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 2 4@@EndFEN@@  4...d5  5.b3  . Likewise, play may transpose after  @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/pp1ppppp/5n2/2p5/3P4/4PN2/PPP2PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3...cxd4  4.exd4  to our favourite lines, while if instead  @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/pp1ppppp/5n2/2p5/3P4/4PN2/PPP2PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3...g6  then  4.dxc5!?  is a reasonable try for White.   After @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/3P4/8/PPP1PPPP/RNBQKBNR b KQkq d3 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1...c5  rejecting 2. d5 in favour of  2.e3  may actually lead to an Exchange Caro-Kann after  2...cxd4  3.exd4  d5   @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  c6  2.d4  d5  3.exd5  cxd5  being the normal move order here  and you may be happy enough continuing with Nf3 and Bd3 there in this reversed Carlsbad structure. }
1... e6
{ In the rest of this chapter we'll just take a look at one other important first move for Black, one which has definite relevance for our Colle Queen's Indian approach. }
