[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "18) Completing Your Colle Repertoire"]
[Black "Completing Your Repertoire: 1...e6 / 2...f5 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 e6 2. Nf3
{ Our standard second move, getting 3. e3 ready and hoping that Black, as he often does here, simply goes 2...d5. }
2... f5 3. d5
{ Against the delayed Dutch, this is a decent sideline to cut across Black's plans. White hopes that he'll be allowed to trade on e6 then remove the queens, thereby preventing Black from castling.  Here we really don't like  3.e3  . Black may then still consider a kingside fianchetto after all, while after  3...Nf6  4.Bd3  b6  5.O-O  Bb7  Black's firm hold on the e4-square means we haven't such a great version of the Colle.   If you're an aggressive player though, you may wish to consider the Tiger Hillarp Persson-endorsed  3.h3!?  and Richard once won a nice game with the line-opening  3...Nf6  4.g4!?  . Here, though, we'll map out a quick repertoire with 3. d5. }
3... d6 4. dxe6 Bxe6 5. Ng5
{ White bags the bishop-pair, since a retreat only serves to make matters worse for Black. }
5... Bd7 6. Qd5 { This is too much for Black. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "18) Completing Your Colle Repertoire"]
[Black "Completing Your Repertoire: 1...e6 / 2...f5 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 e6 2. Nf3
{ Our standard second move, getting 3. e3 ready and hoping that Black, as he often does here, simply goes 2...d5. }
2... f5 3. d5
{ Against the delayed Dutch, this is a decent sideline to cut across Black's plans. White hopes that he'll be allowed to trade on e6 then remove the queens, thereby preventing Black from castling.  Here we really don't like  3.e3  . Black may then still consider a kingside fianchetto after all, while after  3...Nf6  4.Bd3  b6  5.O-O  Bb7  Black's firm hold on the e4-square means we haven't such a great version of the Colle.   If you're an aggressive player though, you may wish to consider the Tiger Hillarp Persson-endorsed  3.h3!?  and Richard once won a nice game with the line-opening  3...Nf6  4.g4!?  . Here, though, we'll map out a quick repertoire with 3. d5. }
3... Nf6 4. dxe6 d5 5. Bf4
{ A much safer way of playing than  5.Ng5  Qe7  . White will now look to complete development with e2-e3, Bd3 and O-O, and hope to gradually show that Black has overextended. }
*

