[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "18) Completing Your Colle Repertoire"]
[Black "Completing Your Repertoire: 1...e6 / 2...f5 #6"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 e6 2. Nf3
{ Our standard second move, getting 3. e3 ready and hoping that Black, as he often does here, simply goes 2...d5. }
2... f5 3. d5
{ Against the delayed Dutch, this is a decent sideline to cut across Black's plans. White hopes that he'll be allowed to trade on e6 then remove the queens, thereby preventing Black from castling.  Here we really don't like  3.e3  . Black may then still consider a kingside fianchetto after all, while after  3...Nf6  4.Bd3  b6  5.O-O  Bb7  Black's firm hold on the e4-square means we haven't such a great version of the Colle.   If you're an aggressive player though, you may wish to consider the Tiger Hillarp Persson-endorsed  3.h3!?  and Richard once won a nice game with the line-opening  3...Nf6  4.g4!?  . Here, though, we'll map out a quick repertoire with 3. d5. }
3... exd5 4. Qxd5 d6 5. g3
{ Preparing to bring the bishop on to the long diagonal is a much safer choice than  5.Ng5  Qe7  6.Nxh7  c6  ,  as Simon endorsed for Black on his popular Dutch course. }
5... Nf6 6. Qb3
{ The queen remains on a slightly annoying diagonal for Black, while also keeping an eye on b7. White simply wants to continue development with Bg2 and O-O, after which it may even be possible to consider ideas of Nd4 or arranging the e2-e4 break. }
6... Na6 7. Be3
{ This move might look a little unnatural, but White is now ready to exchange off the knight should it land on c5, while Nbd2 will continue the queenside development. }
7... d5 8. Bg2 c6 9. c4
{ This strong central challenge, intending Nc3 then to exchange on d5, left White with an edge in Vachier Lagrave-Vaisser, French Team Championship 2011. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "18) Completing Your Colle Repertoire"]
[Black "Completing Your Repertoire: 1...e6 / 2...c5"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 e6 2. Nf3
{ Our standard second move, getting 3. e3 ready and hoping that Black, as he often does here, simply goes 2...d5. }
2... c5 3. e3
{ Having offered a French on move one @@StartBracket@@2. e4@@EndBracket@@, 2...c5 is a pretty ambitious try and sees Black now offering to play an ...e6 Sicilian.   You might decide that's a bluff and so take up the challenge with   3.e4!?  ,  but a Colle approach is very justified here and now Black's most popular move is  3...Nf6  ,  as indeed we saw inHodgson-Jackelen, when White would again be quite happy after  4.Bd3  .   As we saw inChapter 14,  3...d5  4.b3  is also fine for us.   And after  3...b6  4.Bd3  Black is extremely likely to quickly go ...Nf6, taking play into Colle Queen's Indian waters. }
3... cxd4 4. exd4 Nf6 5. Bd3
{ Our king's bishop takes up its favourite residence, as we prepare both to castle and fianchetto on the queenside. Now  5...b6  6.O-O  would once again be a Colle Queen's Indian. }
5... d5 6. b3
{ There's absolutely no reason not to fianchetto here, although thanks to the early exchange on d4 you could also consider London @@StartBracket@@f4@@EndBracket@@ or Torre @@StartBracket@@g5@@EndBracket@@ options for this bishop. }
6... Nc6 7. Bb2 Be7 8. O-O
{ This set-up should be pretty familiar and we're now back where we started inChapter 1. Good luck with your Colle and Colle-Zukertort adventures! }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Thematic Tactics"]
[Black "Thematic Tactic #1"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r2q1rk1/1b1Nbppp/p3pn2/1ppp4/3P4/1P1BP2Q/PBPN1PPP/R4RK1 b - - 0 12"]
[SetUp "1"]

12... Qxd7
{ With our bishops poised to attack, how do we punish Black for neglecting the kingside? }
13. dxc5
{ White threatens to remove the key defender on f6 and is also ready to secure the extra pawn with b3-b4. }
13... Ne4 14. f3 Ng5 15. Qg3
{ Clearly Black remains under pressure on the kingside, with h2-h4 being one threat, and White will at least manage to secure the rather handy extra pawn with b3-b4. Talk about an ideal outcome from the opening! }
*

