[SetUp "1"]

1... Qb2
{ Black's queen has ventured into no-man's land. What is White's cute resource? }
2. Ndc4 dxc4 3. Nxc4
{ A neat trap and the reason the black queen cannot stray too far forwards. Black is losing significant material. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Thematic Tactics"]
[Black "Thematic Tactic #3"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "2rr2k1/pp1b1ppp/1qnbpn2/3pN3/3P1P2/PP1B1N2/1BP1Q1PP/R4RK1 b - - 0 14"]
[SetUp "1"]

14... Nh5
{ What typical attacking idea can we execute if Black is not careful with their kingside? }
15. Bxh7+
{ Alarm bells should ring whenever the f6-knight wanders. Often it means the h7 square is a fatal invasion point. }
15... Kxh7 16. Ng5+
{ Exposing a discovery on the knight with a mating attack. } 16... Kg8 17. Qxh5
{ There's nothing for Black to do at this point, but let's see how the game finished... }
17... Nxe5 18. fxe5 Be8 19. Rxf7 Bxf7 20. Qxf7+ Kh8 21. Qh5+ Kg8 22. Rf1 Bxe5
23. Qh7# { A swift victory for Dylan of Chessable! } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Thematic Tactics"]
[Black "Thematic Tactic #4"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r4rk1/pbqn1ppp/1p1bp3/2Pp4/5P2/1P1BP3/PBPN2PP/R2Q1RK1 b - - 0 12"]
[SetUp "1"]

12... Bxc5
{ As usual in the Colle, both sides bishops are aimed towards the enemy kingside, but White's are always more effective, as shown by the following typical sequence: }
13. Bxh7+
{ Initiating a greek gift of sorts. Notice the absence of the f6-knight. }
13... Kxh7 14. Qh5+ Kg8 15. Bxg7
{ A classic double bishop sacrifice. White simply wants to give mate on either h8 or via Qg5+ and Rf3-h3. There's simply no good defence. For instance, if  4...Kxg7  then  5.Qg5+  Kh7  6.Rf3  with Rh3 next would be lights out. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Thematic Tactics"]
[Black "Thematic Tactic #5"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r4r2/pbq2ppk/1p1bp3/2np3Q/5P2/1P2P3/PBPN2PP/R4RK1 b - - 0 14"]
[SetUp "1"]

14... Kg8
{ Compare this with the previous position where the knight occupies c5 instead of the bishop. Surprisingly the killer blow is unique. }
15. Bf6
{ A gorgeous and quite deadly move.  15.Bxg7?  would fail to  15...f5!  when because the knight not on d7, the queen can readily defend laterally along the 7th. }
15... gxf6 16. Qg4+ Kh7 17. Rf3 { Mate follows. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Thematic Tactics"]
[Black "Thematic Tactic #6"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r4rk1/pb1q1ppp/1p2pB2/3p4/5P2/1P1Bb3/P1PN2PP/R2Q1R1K b - - 0 14"]
[SetUp "1"]

14... gxf6
{ By now you should understand how to put away your opponents for allowing their kingside to be opened like this. }
15. Bxh7+
{ Our favourite and quite decisive sacrifice, as in, amongst others, Cornhill-Barber, York @@StartBracket@@rapid@@EndBracket@@ 2012, and Malezkey-Kazantsev, Barnaul 2014. }
15... Kxh7
{ 15...Kh8  16.Qh5  This is also a game-ender with Qh6 and/or Rf3 up next. }
16. Qh5+ Kg7 17. Qg4+ { A key check, preventing the black king from fleeing. }
17... Kh7 18. Rf3
{ It's now mate in four, since White can even ignore any desperado black bishops. }
18... Bxf4 19. Rh3+ Bh6 20. Qh5 { The black king is going to be mated on g8. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
