[SetUp "1"]

15... g6
{ Black has severely misplayed this, apparent from his numerous kingside weaknesses. What is the most direct win? }
16. Qh5
{ The attack is already clearly a winner with so much firepower on the kingside. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Thematic Tactics"]
[Black "Thematic Tactic #11"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r1b2rk1/pp2qppp/2nbpn2/3p4/3P4/PP1B1N2/1BPN1PPP/R2Q1RK1 b - - 0 10"]
[SetUp "1"]

10... e5
{ One of Black's only ideas for counterplay being ...e5 break, it's very important to know how to punish it when it comes early. }
11. dxe5 { Exposing the poor placement of the black queen. } 11... Nxe5 12.
Bxe5
{ The other capture is also rather good. In both cases a pin on the e-file will prove near fatal for Black. }
12... Bxe5 13. Re1
{ Now  13...Ng4  is simply met by  14.h3  and even the more radical knight moves don't come close to saving Black. }
13... Nd7
{ 13...Ne4?!  14.Nxe4!?  Not the only good move, but perhaps the strongest. White simply wants to go two pawns to the good after  14...dxe4  15.Rxe4  f6  16.Nxe5  fxe5  17.Qe2  ,   and is quite happy to dangle the rook on  a1  before Black:  14...Bxa1  15.Neg5!   Even stronger than  15.Nc3  Qxa3  16.Qxa1  Qxa1  17.Rxa1  with a huge advantage in the endgame. }
14. Nxe5 Nxe5 15. Bxh7+
{ Simple chess, and not  15.f4?  Qc5+  . White isn't winning a piece, but we are obtaining a huge advantage. }
15... Kxh7 16. Qh5+ Kg8 17. Qxe5
{ Black is a pawn down with a miserable position, whether he keeps the queens on or not. White will in either case be quick to increase the pressure with Nf3-d4 @@StartBracket@@talk about an ideal square for a knight@@EndBracket@@ and Re3, preparing to double rooks. }
*

