[SetUp "1"]

9... Qc7
{ Often times ...Qc7 can leave the f6-knight vulnerable. How should White continue? }
10. Nxc6
{ An alert response. White spots that the Zukertort bishop can be unfurled with some effect now that the black queen isn't covering f6: }
10... Qxc6 11. dxc5 Qxc5 12. Bxf6
{ Removing a key defender and thereby teeing up Qh5. } 12... gxf6 13. Qh5
{ Notice there is no Bxh7+ here, since there's no way in for the rook. } 13...
f5 14. g4
{ A powerful follow-up as there's just no respite for Black. Suddenly gxf5 is a threat @@StartBracket@@and would be played after 14...Qc3@@EndBracket@@, when Kh1 and Rg1+ may follow and White also has the strong idea of Nf3-g5. }
*

