[Black "Thematic Tactic #20 "]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "2r2rk1/1b1qbppp/p3pn2/1p1p2N1/8/1P1BP1Q1/PBP2PPP/R4RK1 b - - 0 15"]
[SetUp "1"]

15... h6 { How can White respond to the threat on the knight? } 16. Nh7
{ A powerful leap and one which forces Black to part with the exchange on f8. }
16... Rfe8 17. Nxf6+ { Or  17.Bxf6 } 17... Bxf6 18. Bxf6
{ Leaves White a piece up. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Yusupov, A. vs. Spiridonov, N. Eu. Team Ch. 1983"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 e6 3. e3
{ Play begins with a Colle against Queen's Indian approach, one which we'll examine later in this course, but here things quickly transpose to the Colle-Zukertort. }
3... c5 4. Bd3 d5 5. b3
{ Preparing the fianchetto of the dark-squared Colle bishop. } 5... Nc6 6. Bb2
{ Completing White's ideal bishop set-up. We'll begin our detailed coverage by looking at what happens if Black fears ideas of dxc5 and so elects to exchange on d4 before going ...Be7. Such an idea was traditionally criticised, as now going Qe2 or Re1 will support a Ne5 advance while keeping Black out of e4, but the latest engines don't seem to mind it for Black. }
6... Be7 { Black gets on with the process of completing kingside development. }
7. O-O
{ Following our standard approach: deploy the bishops to fine squares, house the king and only then, usually, look to involve the knights with Nbd2 and Ne5. }
7... O-O 8. Nbd2
{ This position should be pretty familiar by now. With development largely complete, White can now look to expand with our favourite Ne5 and f2-f4 approach. }
8... b6 9. Ne5
{ Our ideal leap and one which reaches something of a tabiya, as we saw in such lines Chapter 2. Now we'll take a look at what happens if Black spots f2-f4 coming, panics slightly, and prematurely exchanges on e5. }
9... Nb4
{ The Bulgarian Grandmaster declines to complete the fianchetto and instead aims to stir up early trouble. White should not be perturbed though. }
10. Be2 { Naturally retaining an important bishop. } 10... Bb7 11. f4
{ Played immediately and only now will White, if allowed, kick Black backwards with a2-a3 then go Bd3 once again.   11.a3  Nc6  12.Bd3  This is far from a terrible alternative, but does allow Black a standard equaliser:  12...Nxe5  13.dxe5  Ne4  White hasn't anything here. For example:  14.Nxe4  dxe4  15.Bc4  Bc6  Black is absolutely fine, whereas if White's pawn was on f4, not f2, he would have an edge, as we saw inthis line, thanks to having a key pawn break in f4-f5. }
11... Ne4
{ Spiridonov continues to try to cut across White's plans, but we can now deploy our favourite strategy for dealing with an intruder on e4: the exchange of knights. }
12. Nxe4 dxe4 13. a3 Nd5 14. Qd2
{ Naturally Yusupov wants to hang on to the key base of his pawn structure on e3 and now White is all set to expand with c2-c4 and Rad1. }
14... Rc8
{ This time, Spiridonov fails to cross White's plans.   14...f6  15.Ng4  White still has chances for an edge here, as we saw inChapter 2, with queenside expansion on the agenda and the bishop ready to recapture on d4, but better this for Black than the game. }
15. c4 Nf6
{ 15...f6  This was still a more critical try for Black, if also now a definite edge for White:  16.Ng4  cxd4  17.Bxd4  White may aim to expand after Rfd1 with b3-b4 and might also try to put some pressure on the dead-point on e4, angling to induce a weakening ...f6-f5 push. }
16. Rad1
{ White is now nicely centralised and it's no surprise that Yusupov assessed the position as '+/-' in Chess Informant 35. Black's queen is going to have to vacate the d-file at some stage soon and with such a fine dark-squared bishop, White should be looking closely at the g7-square, which he might begin to target after Qe1 and Qg3, or even Qc3, as in the game. }
16... Bd6
{ Black is simply blown away after this.   16...cxd4  17.exd4  This would be a very pleasant edge, with ideas of Qc3 and Ng4 high on the agenda.   17.Bxd4!?  Bxa3  18.g4!?  A tempting engine-approved alternative, aiming to both cramp Black and attack on the dark squares after g4-g5 and Ng4, not to mention cause trouble with a timely Qa2. }
17. dxc5 { It's high time to begin to clear the long diagonal. } 17... Bxc5 18.
Qc3 Qe7 19. f5
{ Direct, and Yusupov is quickly rewarded when Black now exchanges.   19.b4!  Bd6  20.g4!?  This was likely even stronger, intending to crash through with g4-g5. Black's knight can drop back to e8, but after Ng4 White will then have such ideas as Nh6+, Kh1 and Rg1, and h4-h5-h6. }
19... exf5 20. Rxf5 Bxa3
{ In for a penny, in for a pound is all well enough and Black is also trying to exchange off White's monster dark-squared bishop, but now Spiridonov is obliterated on the kingside. }
21. Bxa3 Qxa3 22. Rxf6
{ Ouch. Even without the bishop, White will still enjoy a decisive attack on the dark squares. }
22... gxf6 23. Ng4
{ Not only is Nxf6+ a big threat, but even Qxf6 followed by Nh6#, and even returning the exchange won't come close to saving Spiridonov. }
23... Rc6
{ 23...Rfd8  24.Nxf6+  Kf8  25.Nxh7+  Removing what is actually a not totally irrelevant pawn ahead of continuing to wreak havoc with the knight:  25...Kg8  26.Nf6+  Kf8  27.Nd7+  Kg8  28.Qf6  There's no good defence to the simple threat of Qg5+. }
24. Nxf6+ Rxf6 25. Qxf6 Qxb3 26. Kf2
{ Calmly maintaining full control while preparing to invade with Rd7. Black is a pawn up, but quite lost and that's no surprise when we look at the huge holes around his king. }
26... Qa4 27. Qg5+ Kh8 28. Qe7
{ Spiridonov didn't need to be shown that he can't defend both rook and bishop due to the check on e5:   28.Qe7  Rb8  29.Qe5+ }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Bu Xiangzhi vs. Thorhallsson, T. Reykjavik (Rapid), 2013"]
[Result "*"]

1. Nf3
{ Not our recommended first move, of course, but we quickly get back on course and into a Colle-Zukertort. }
1... d5 2. d4 Nf6 3. e3 e6 4. Bd3
{ The natural square to develop the bishop, which will very often prove White's most effective attacker. }
4... c5 5. b3 { Preparing the fianchetto of the dark-squared Colle bishop. }
5... Nc6 6. O-O
{ We prefer to complete the fianchetto without delay, largely for the sake of simplicity, but there's absolutely nothing wrong with castling first. }
6... Be7 7. Bb2
{ Following our standard approach: deploy the bishops to fine squares, house the king and only then, usually, look to involve the knights with Nbd2 and Ne5. }
7... O-O 8. Nbd2 b6 9. Ne5
{ Our ideal leap and one which reaches something of a tabiya, as we saw in such lines Chapter 2. Now we'll take a look at what happens if Black spots f2-f4 coming, panics slightly, and prematurely exchanges on e5. }
9... Nxe5 10. dxe5 Nd7
{ The knight must, of course, retreat, since going to e4 would just drop a pawn with Black yet to play ...Bb7. }
11. f4
{ We cover this type of position inChapter 2. Simple and strong chess, although a decent case might very well be made too for deploying the queen straight to g4 or h5 and, yes,  11.c4!?  is also a strong advance, as we saw back in the introductory section on the e5 outpost. }
11... Re8
{ Black wants to defend with ...Nf8, but this is rather passive.   11...Bb7  12.Qg4  This would also be a pretty dangerous attack. Now ...f5; exf6 would see Black losing material, but otherwise f4-f5 is already on the cards, with Nf3, Rad1 and c2-c4 all also likely to prove useful moves for increasing the pressure.   11...f5!  12.exf6  Nxf6  13.c4  This gives White a very pleasant, long-term advantage, but at least this way Black doesn't become too cramped. }
12. Qf3
{ A fine spot for the queen, threatening to crash through with f4-f5, as well as to increase the pressure on Black's position with c2-c4. }
12... Nf8 13. Kh1
{ A sneaky waiting move, if not definitely best.   13.Rad1!  Bd7  14.c4  Black has done his best to hold up f4-f5, but his centre is under strong pressure and White would be delighted if he could recapture on c4 with his knight, then land it on d6. }
13... Bb7
{ It was the final chance for Black to, albeit slightly desperately, try pushing his own f-pawn. The Icelandic Grandmaster and then Icelandic Champion is now rather blown away. }
14. f5
{ Bu is quick to reveal why Black's light-squared bishop really had to stay on the c8-h3 diagonal. }
14... Qd7
{ 14...exf5  15.Qxf5  15...f6  16.Bb5  This would also have been very bad news for Black, who is going to shed material, whether the exchange on e8 or the d-pawn:  16...Bc8  17.Qd3  Bd7  18.Qxd5+  . }
15. f6
{ Clearly Black was ready to recapture with his queen on e6, but Bu must have been delighted to be allowed to carry out White's other threat. Already it's looking extremely unlikely that the black king will survive. }
15... Bd8 16. Qg4 Ng6 17. h4
{ Black has done his best to avoid fatally weakening his dark squares on the kingside, but has absolutely no defence to the arrival of Harry. }
17... c4 18. Bxg6
{ 18.bxc4  dxc4  19.Nxc4  This would have been even simpler with h4-h5 next up, but possibly Bu Xiangzhi was trying to win in style. }
18... hxg6 19. h5 c3 20. Bxc3 Rc8 21. hxg6
{ Bu does, indeed, find a stylish way to crash through. } 21... Rxc3 22. Qh3
{ Clearly it's going to be mate, unless Black gives up his queen. } 22... fxg6
23. f7+ Qxf7 24. Rxf7 Kxf7 25. Qh7
{ Ensuring that the hapless monarch won't easily manage to escape. } 25... Re7
{ 25...Bg5  26.Rf1+  Ke7  27.Qxg7+  Kd8  28.Rf8!  This looks like the simplest way to finish things off. With Black's pieces so loose and king still extremely exposed, the queen should run amok and can always be supported, if needed, by Nf3. }
26. Qh8
{ 26.Qh8  Ba6  27.Nc4  And the arrival of the rook on the open file will clean Black up. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Pukropski, G. vs. Radloff, D. Correspondence, 2008"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 e6 3. e3 d5 4. Bd3
{ The natural square to develop the bishop, which will very often prove White's most effective attacker. }
4... c5 5. b3 { Preparing the fianchetto of the dark-squared Colle bishop. }
5... Nc6 6. O-O
{ White goes in for an early exchange on c5 and different move order to our recommended one.   6.Bb2  Bd6  7.O-O  O-O  8.Nbd2  Qe7  9.a3!?  Our provocative little response to one of the two main branches of the main line of the Colle-Zukertort, 6...Bd6 and 8... Qe7. Now play would transpose to Pukropski-Radloff via:  9...e5  10.dxc5!  Bxc5  11.b4 }
6... Bd6 7. dxc5 Bxc5 8. Bb2 O-O 9. Nbd2 Qe7 10. a3 e5
{ We're now back in ourcritical continuation. } 11. b4
{ White simply must take up the challenge and force the pace so, otherwise he has allowed Black to expand in the centre for no good reason. }
11... Bb6 12. b5 e4 13. bxc6 bxc6 14. Bxf6
{ A key point and forcing move we hope you remembered. If  14...Qxf6  15.Nxe4 }
14... gxf6 15. Be2 { Retaining control and at least one bishop. } 15... exf3
16. Nxf3 Kh8
{ Invariably played here as Black tries to make something work down the g-file to offset his rather shoddy structure. }
17. Qd3
{ Ruling out any notion of ...Bf5, while adding extra support to c2-c4.   17.a4!?  This is yet to be tested here, but is a decent looking suggestion from the latest incarnation of Stockfish. White simply seizes space and hopes that Black will allow Rb1 with tempo by pushing his own a-pawn. Instead, he might yet still try to attack:  17...Rg8  18.a5  Bc7  19.g3!  White shuts down the h2-b8 diagonal and now has ideas of not just c2-c4, but even Ra4-h4.  19...Bh3  20.Re1  With Ra4 and Qd3 on their way, White's superior structure should count for an edge and there's another, more striking alternative.   20.Ra4!?  Bxf1  21.Bxf1  Talk about fantastic positional compensation for the exchange! The idea of Rh4 and Bd3 shouldn't be hard to grasp, with Nd4-f5 also very much on White's agenda. }
17... Rg8
{ 17...Be6  18.a4!?   18.Rfd1  c5!  19.g3  Ba5  didn't seem so bad for Black with Nd4 off the agenda in Perini-M.Jones, correspondence 2013, although  20.Rab1  should still be a little better for White.  18...c5  19.c4!  dxc4  20.Qc2  White will regain the pawn on c4 and holds a small but pleasant advantage thanks to the superior structure and Black's slightly subdued dark-squared bishop. }
18. Rfd1 { Moving the rook before ...Bh3 lands clearly makes decent sense. }
18... Bh3 19. g3 Rad8 20. Nd4
{ This is also a decent move, especially now that ...c5 would simply blunder the exchange, although even here the engines prefer  20.a4!?  to try and drive Black's bishop backwards with a4-a5 and then maybe invade down the b-file and/or play against c6. }
20... Bd7
{ 20...Qd7  21.c4  c5!  22.Nb3  White is only a touch better here and at correspondence Black should really be able to hold:  22...Be6?!   22...dxc4!  23.Qxd7  Otherwise, ...Qc6 is an issue.  23...Rxd7  24.Bxc4  Rxd1+  25.Rxd1  Kg7  26.f3  White is only a touch better, although you might imagine Magnus grinding down most opponents from here.  23.a4!  dxc4  24.Qc3  24...Qe7  25.Bxc4  By now White was back to having a comfortable plus and went on to grind out the win in Minte-Schaefer, correspondence 2009. }
21. Bf3
{ Improving the bishop and freeing e2 for the knight, but probably not best.   21.a4!  21...c5!?  22.Nf3  Be6  23.Qa3!?  White has a definite ongoing pull here with a4-a5 and Rab1 both ideas, and an even bigger threat is the initiative-seizing Nd4. }
21... Qe5
{ 21...c5!?  22.Ne2  This was likely White's idea, but the latest engines believe that Black has almost enough for the pawn he is about to sacrifice:  22...d4!  23.exd4  cxd4  24.Nxd4  Bh3  25.c3  While you'd probably still slightly favour White, Black is fairly active here with ...Rg5-c5 one idea. }
22. Bg2
{ Ruling out any notion of ...Bh3 and any subsequent back-rank concerns, and now Black continues to slightly drift. }
22... Qh5 23. a4
{ At last, White hits on the idea of 24. a5 followed by invading with 25. Qa6. }
23... c5
{ 23...a5  24.Qa3  With Rab1 on the way White is undoubtedly pressing and there's even a threat of  @@StartFEN@@3r2rk/3b1p1p/1bp2p2/p2p3q/P2N4/Q3P1P1/2P2PBP/R2R2K1 w - - 1 24@@EndFEN@@  25.Nxc6!  Bxc6  26.Qb2  , but this was likely still a tougher defence for Black. }
24. a5 Bc7
{ 24...cxd4  25.axb6  This is surely just extremely strong followed by Qxd4 or:  25...dxe3?  26.Qxe3  axb6  27.Rxd5  The upcoming pin down the d-file will be ruinous for Black. }
25. Qc3 Rc8 26. Nf3
{ Simple chess, although a very good case might also have been made for  26.Nc6!  . }
26... Bd8 27. Ne1
{ The hanging pawns are definitely rather weak here and Black now collapses immediately in a most uncorrespondence-like way. }
27... Be7 28. Rxd5
{ 28.Rxd5  Qg4  29.h3  Qe6  30.Nd3  Black is a pawn down and quite positionally bust with Nf4 followed by Rh5 and ganging up on h7 high on White's agenda. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Sambuev, B. vs. Hua, E. Ontario Open, 2019"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 d5 3. e3 e6 4. Bd3
{ The natural square to develop the bishop, which will very often prove White's most effective attacker. }
4... c5 5. O-O
{ It is possible to castle here before going b2-b3, but why give Black the option of raising the stakes and changing the tone of the game with the ambitious 5...c4?   5.b3  5...Nc6  6.Bb2  Bd6  7.O-O  This is, of course, our preferred move order. }
5... Nc6 6. b3 Bd6 7. Bb2 O-O 8. a3
{ This is fine and play soon transposes, but is also not the move order advocated inChapter 4.   8.Nbd2  b6  9.Ne5  Bb7  10.a3  A handy little prophylactic advance and by now the transposition should be fairly obvious:  10...Rc8  11.Qe2 }
8... b6 9. Nbd2 Bb7 10. Qe2 Rc8 11. Ne5
{ White aims to provoke an exchange on d4 @@StartBracket@@many club players are not good at maintaining the tension@@EndBracket@@, and holds back on f2-f4 for now, thereby giving us more options if Black goes in for a solid regrouping, as indeed Hua now does. }
11... Ne7
{ A critical test. White replies in critical fashion by opening up the Zukertort bishop and gaining space. }
12. dxc5 Rxc5 13. b4 Rc8 14. Rad1
{ This is where we left things inthis line in Chapter 4. The position is quite complex and Black shouldn't be worse, but White is now ready to quickly change through the gears and begin an attack after f2-f4 followed by Ndf3 or even Ng4 to remove the defender on f6. }
14... Qc7
{ A.  14...Ne4?!  15.Bxe4!  15...dxe4  16.Ndc4  This must have looked scary to Hua and even a counter-pin doesn't prove fully sufficient:  16...Ba6  17.a4!  17...Bxe5!  18.b5!   18.Rxd8?!  Bxc4  19.Rxf8+  Kxf8  20.Qd2  Bxb2  Black's three pieces equate to enticing compensation for the queen.  18...Bxh2+!  19.Kxh2  Qc7+  20.Nd6  20...Nf5  21.Be5  Bb7  22.Bf4  The dust is finally settling, with White doing well thanks to having that powerful knight @@StartBracket@@or bishop@@EndBracket@@ on d6.   B.  14...Ng6!?  15.f4!?  a5!  This feels like a critical continuation. Now White might just go 16. b5 then a3-a4 or try to sacrifice a pawn:  16.Ng4!?  Nxg4  17.Qxg4  axb4  18.axb4  Bxb4  19.Nf3  Interestingly the engines feel that White has enough for a pawn here, in large part due to that big bishop on b2. Immediately there is a big threat of f4-f5, as well as of Bxg6, and if ...hxg6; Ng5 followed by Qh4. }
15. f4 { Naturally White keeps the pivotal knight in place. } 15... Ng6 16. Ng4
{ This turns out well and helps us to see how practically dangerous such positions can be for Black, but wasn't objectively correct.   16.Ndf3!?  White maintains full control of e5 and would now like to whip up a sudden attack with Ng5 followed by Ng4. }
16... Ne4 17. f5
{ Really going for it. This advance isn't completely sound, but few players like to defend and here there are definite medium-term practical problems facing Black, '-1' though the engine may proclaim. }
17... exf5 18. Rxf5 Rcd8
{ 18...Nc3!  19.Bxc3  Qxc3  20.Nb3  Rce8!  White is in some positional trouble here, with f7 well defended and ...Bc8 on the way or even ...Nf4. }
19. Rdf1
{ 19.Rh5!?  This feels like a reasonable attempt to randomise and only then Rf1. }
19... Nxd2
{ 19...Bc8!  20.Nxe4!   20.Rh5?  Nxd2  dxe4  21.Bxe4  Bxf5  22.Rxf5  a5!  23.Bd5!?  A Tal might still go on to win from here and in style, but objectively speaking White shouldn't have quite enough for the exchange. }
20. Qxd2 Bc8 21. e4
{ Far from Sambuev's best ever move, but it was clearly to be the grandmaster's lucky day, or fortune favours the bold as they say!   21.Qf2!  Bxf5?!  22.Qxf5  This would have supplied promising compensation with Bxg7 already a big threat. }
21... Bxf5
{ 21...dxe4!  22.Nf6+   22.Bxg7  Bxf5  23.Rxf5  This leads to a forced mate if Black takes on g7, but he can do far better than that:  23...Bxh2+!  24.Kh1  Bf4!  25.Rxf4  Kxg7  26.Rxe4  f6  White is starting to run out of pieces.  gxf6  23.Qh6  The attack looks very scary, but White is all in. .. and bust:  23...Rfe8!  24.Rh5  Re5!  25.Qxh7+  Kf8  26.Bxe5  Bxe5  27.Bxe4  Ba6  It's Black who has the initiative here and already a decisive advantage in the view of the all-seeing silicon oracle. }
22. exf5 Ne5 23. Bxe5
{ Having been reprieved then granted a chance, Sambuev now makes no mistake. }
23... Bxe5 24. f6
{ Clearly Qg5 is a big threat and already Black lacks a decent defence. } 24...
Kh8 25. Qg5 Bd4+ 26. Kh1 Rg8 27. Qh4 g6 28. Rf3
{ Threatening a classic mate in two. } 28... Rge8 29. Qh6
{ A strange decision.   29.Bf1!  And only then Qh6 was the way to win. } 29...
Re1+ 30. Bf1 Rxf1+ 31. Rxf1
{ 31.Rxf1  Rg8  32.Qd2!  White is better here, but still has plenty of work to do, so, yes, of course, Black shouldn't have resigned!   32.Rf3?  g5  33.Rh3?  Qxc2  Presumably a stunned Hua overlooked this only but utterly devastating move. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Sambuev, B. vs. Lyn, C. Americas World Cup Qualifier, 2021"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 e6 3. e3 d5 4. Bd3
{ The natural square to develop the bishop, which will very often prove White's most effective attacker. }
4... Bd6 5. O-O
{ This is fine here, although White doesn't have to abandon our favourite move order just yet.   5.b3  O-O  6.Bb2  This is very much absolutely still fine here, as we'll see more in our next section, Theory Four. Moreover, play here may well transpose back to Sambuev-Lyn once Black goes ...c5:  6...Nbd7  7.O-O  c5  8.Nbd2 }
5... c5 6. b3 O-O 7. Bb2 Nbd7 8. Nbd2
{ Our favourite set-up and here we'll see what happens when Black doesn't opt to either move his queen or fianchetto without delay on b7. The alternatives are seen often enough at club level, but are rather slow. }
8... Re8
{ 8...cxd4  9.exd4  b6  10.Qe2  One of our favourite methods, reinforcing White's control of the key e4 and e5 points ahead of expanding in the centre.  10...Bb7  11.Ne5  Qe7  12.a3!?  This ruled out the plan of ...Ba3 and so kept Black fairly bottled up and low on counterplay in Anton Guijarro-Aditya, Dubai 2017.   12.a4!?  Rfc8  13.c3!?  This also looks pretty tempting and like a pleasant edge for White here, keeping Black at bay on the kingside and intending to expand with f2-f4, Rf3 and Rae1, followed by the usual powerful kingside attack. }
9. Ne5 { Thematically leaping forwards while freeing the f-pawn for action. }
9... Qc7 10. f4
{ This is rather a meister-gegen-amateur game, but we will at least see how White, having taken control of the key e5 point, need not fear an invasion on c3 and will very soon be enjoying a strong attack. }
10... cxd4 11. exd4 Bb4 12. c3
{ Exploiting the potential pin down the c-file. As such, Black clearly can't capture and so must lose further time. }
12... Bf8 13. Qf3
{ Very tempting here, as White simply wants to switch the queen to h3, then target h7.   13.Rf3  b6  14.Rh3  This also looks like a superb set-up for White, with Qe2 next up and Black already needing to be careful:  14...Bb7?  15.Nxd7!  15...Qxd7  16.Bxh7+!  Whoops! It's only move 16 and Black is getting cleaned up on the kingside. }
13... b6 14. Qh3 Bb7 15. Rae1
{ Calmly taking control of e4, if by no means the only good move here.   15.Ndf3!?  followed by Ng5 is endorsed by the engines. Let's see why:  15...Ne4?   15...h6  16.g4!  Ne4  17.g5  This is also a sudden and rather powerful attack with lines quickly set to open on the kingside.  16.Nxf7!  A pretty devastating sacrifice:  16...Kxf7?  17.Bxe4  dxe4  18.Ng5+  Now Black is mated if his king goes to e7 or g8 and even f6 isn't a safe haven:  18...Kf6  19.c4!  The Zukertort bishop will have the last laugh. }
15... g6
{ 15...Bd6!?  16.g4!?  And, well, why not?  16...Nf8  17.g5  This passive defence for Black followed by ditching a clear pawn on e4 is already the only way which the engines can see for him to prolong the game. }
16. Ndf3 { Suddenly Ng5 is quite the threat. } 16... Bg7
{ 16...h6  17.Nxf7!  Kxf7  18.Ng5+!  It's no surprise this double sacrifice is so strong as White rips open the black king's pawn shield and prepares to either crash through down an open f-file or pick off e6. }
17. Ng5 Rf8 18. Nexf7 { Fairly simple, but also pretty strong. } 18... Rae8
{ 18...Rxf7  19.Nxf7   19.Qxe6?  Nf8!  Kxf7?  20.Qxe6+  Kf8  21.Ba3+  Again, it's pretty much all over as the Zukertort bishop has some fun at the expense of the black king. }
19. Nh6+
{ 19.Rxe6!?  This would also have been extremely strong, with the idea:  19...Rxf7  20.Rxe8+!  Nxe8  21.Qxh7+  Kf8  22.Ne6+ }
19... Bxh6 20. Qxh6
{ Black is a pawn down with a wrecked kingside and must now deal with the threat of Bxg6 followed by Rf3. }
20... Rf7 21. Nxf7 Kxf7 22. g4
{ There's just no stopping Sambuev and already you wouldn't exactly have blamed Black had he resigned, }
22... Kg8 23. f5
{ 23.Bxg6!?  Re7  24.Bf5  This also more than does the business. } 23... Nxg4
24. Qf4
{ A grandmasterly approach. White is even happy to remove the queens and then pick up further material. }
24... Qxf4 25. Rxf4 Ngf6
{ 25...gxf5  26.Bxf5!  Ngf6  27.Rxe6  This would be an extra exchange and pawn, and that's just for starters. }
26. fxe6 Kg7 27. exd7 Rxe1+ 28. Kf2
{ Lyn had finally seen enough and decided not to test Sambuev's technique with an extra rook. Crushing if also instructive stuff. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Andreikin, D. vs. Hakobyan, A. Chesscom Global Ch. (Rapid), 2022"]
[Result "*"]

1. Nf3 d5 2. d4 Nf6 3. e3 { Entering the Colle via a slightly unusual route. }
3... e6 4. Bd3
{ The natural square to develop the bishop, which will very often prove White's most effective attacker. }
4... Be7 5. O-O
{ 5.b3  c5  6.Bb2  O-O  7.O-O  Nbd7  8.Nbd2  b6  9.Ne5  Bb7  10.Qe2  This is, of course, our recommended move order and by now play has transposed into Andreikin-Hakobyan. }
5... O-O 6. b3 b6 7. Bb2 Bb7 8. Nbd2 Nbd7
{ This is a very solid line for Black, as we'll see in Theory Four, next. } 9.
Qe2 c5 10. Ne5 { White is back on track and all set to expand with f2-f4. }
10... Qc7 11. f4 Rac8 12. Rad1
{ A harmonious little move, involving the rook while not rushing to commit to either a queenside  @@StartBracket@@c2-c4@@EndBracket@@ or kingside @@StartBracket@@g2-g4 and/or f4-f5@@EndBracket@@ approach. }
12... g6
{ Prophylaxis against White's ideas of f4-f5, as we noted in our coverage in the...Nbd7 / ...Be7 Chapter. }
13. Ndf3
{ Andreikin calmly continues to improve his pieces, fully aware that thanks to the knight on e5 and bishop on d3 White need not yet fear any ...c4 ideas.   13.Rf3?  c4!  This would, however, be a powerful advance and with the b1-h7 diagonal blunted, White shouldn't emerge with enough for the exchange. }
13... cxd4 14. Bxd4
{ Keeping the Zukertort bishop involved and now Black arguably underestimated the danger on the kingside, going after the now-restricted bishop on d3 @@StartBracket@@restricted, we should add, in return for that large dark-square gash in the black kingside@@EndBracket@@. }
14... Nc5 15. Ng5
{ This aggressive leap, intending Qf3-h3 or even Qe1-h4 quickly turns out well, but White had even better.   15.g4!  A blunt and very strong idea; White simply wants to go 16. g5 and 17. Ng4, with mayhem on the dark squares:  15...Ne8!?  16.g5  f5  17.gxf6  Bxf6  18.Kh1  Even here White enjoys a clear advantage since Rg1 will quickly leave the black king still feeling the heat. }
15... Nfe4
{ 15...h6  16.Ngf3  Nfe4  17.Qe1!  White has a definite edge here, with ideas of Ng4 and b3-b4, to force Black into a ...Nxd3; cxd3 exchange, but better this than the game for Black. }
16. Ng4 { Threatening mate. } 16... f6 17. Bxe4
{ The first in a sequence of powerful exchanges from Andreikin as White's attack proceeds at full speed and Black's position collapses on e6 or the dark squares. }
17... dxe4 18. Bxc5 fxg5
{ Otherwise, e6 then the exchange would have fallen, but now White crashes through. }
19. Nh6+ Kg7 20. Bd4+ Bf6
{ 20...Kxh6  21.Qg4!  Another threat of mate in one and a game-ender. For example:  21...gxf4  22.Qh3+  Kg5  23.exf4+  Rxf4  24.Rxf4  Qxf4  25.Be3  Winning the queen and that's just for starters. }
21. fxg5 Bxd4 22. Rxd4
{ The end is unsurprisingly nigh. Black is currently only a pawn down, but his bishop isn't playing and his king is extremely vulnerable. }
22... Rxf1+
{ 22...e5  23.Rxf8  23...Rxf8  24.Qd2!  This echoes the game to invade with the rook on d7 or d6, or even to force mate:  24...exd4?  25.Qxd4+ }
23. Qxf1 Rf8 { It's time to finish Black off in style! How? } 24. Rd7+ Qxd7 25.
Qa1+ { The knight and dark-square attack fittingly have the last laugh. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Hodgson, J. vs. Jackelen, T. German Bundesliga, 2001"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 e6 2. Nf3 c5 3. e3
{ We'll see a little more on this move order inChapter 18. Black now takes play back into Colle Queen's Indian waters. }
3... Nf6 4. b3
{ Fianchettoing immediately.   4.Bd3  b6  5.O-O  Bb7  6.b3  Be7  7.Bb2  cxd4  8.exd4  O-O  9.Nbd2  This is ourrecommended move order and play has now transposed into Hodgson-Jackelen. }
4... b6 5. Bb2 Bb7 6. Nbd2 Be7 7. Bd3 cxd4 8. exd4 O-O 9. O-O Nc6 10. a3
{ Prudently ruling out any ...Nb4 ideas ahead of developing the king's rook to e1. }
10... Qc7 11. Re1 Rfe8 12. Rc1
{ By no means forced here @@StartBracket@@the immediate  12.c4  also makes a lot of sense@@EndBracket@@, but Hodgson keeps Black guessing as to what he's up to, while placing the queen on the same file as the opposition queen, something which will prove especially handy in the event of any ...d5 and c2-c4. }
12... Rad8
{ 12...Rac8  13.c4  Suddenly  @@StartFEN@@2r1r1k1/pbqpbppp/1pn1pn2/8/2PP4/PP1B1N2/1B1N1PPP/2RQR1K1 w - - 0 13@@EndFEN@@  14.d5  is a threat, since  14...exd5?  15.Bxf6  Bxf6  16.cxd5  would win a piece due to the pin down the c-file.  @@StartFEN@@2r1r1k1/pbqpbppp/1pn1pn2/8/2PP4/PP1B1N2/1B1N1PPP/2RQR1K1 b - c3 0 13@@EndFEN@@  13...Qf4?!  14.Qe2  This gave White a small edge in Matlak-Nisipeanu, Cappelle-la-Grande 1998, where there was even better:   @@StartFEN@@2r1r1k1/pb1pbppp/1pn1pn2/8/2PP1q2/PP1B1N2/1B1N1PPP/2RQR1K1 w - - 1 14@@EndFEN@@  14.b4!  Seizing some useful space as the black queen rather floats in mid-air. Now ...d5 will always be well met by c4-c5 and meanwhile Ne4 is on the agenda, looking to whip up a quick attack after ...Nxe4; Rxe4. }
13. c4 Qb8 14. b4
{ White's space advantage confers a very pleasant advantage and just where is Black's counterplay? Now Jackelen possibly thought that he'd sidestepped d4-d5 ideas for good, but Hodgson was never going to pass over such an aggressive advance if he could make it work. }
14... a6 15. d5 { Boom! White sacrifices a pawn to activate all his pieces. }
15... exd5 16. cxd5
{ 16.b5!?  axb5  17.cxb5  This must also have greatly tempted Hodgson, since a powerful exchange sacrifice is coming up:  17...Na5  18.Rxe7!  18...Rxe7  19.Bxf6  gxf6  20.Nh4  Black's extremely vulnerable kingside clearly leaves White with excellent compensation and attacking chances. }
16... Nxd5 17. Qb3
{ 17.Bb1!  This was the right follow-up, simply intending to set up a powerful battery with Qc2. For example:  17...Nf4  18.h4!  18...Qd6  19.g3   19.Qc2?  Qg6!  Ne6  20.Ne5  The threat is Qh5 and Black clearly remains under heavy pressure. }
17... Nf6
{ 17...Bf6!  18.Bc4   18.Be4!?  Nce7  19.Ne5  This would be a more steady course than forcing the pace and retain enough play for the pawn.  18...Bxb2  19.Bxd5  Bxc1  20.Bxf7+  Kh8  21.Bxe8  Rxe8  22.Rxc1  At the end of the forcing line, the position is far from dead, but it would be surprising if White could really claim an advantage. }
18. Ne4
{ Increasing the pressure and faced with structural ruin on f6, Jackelen was now unable to find a good way to solve his difficulties. }
18... Qf4
{ 18...Nxe4  19.Rxe4!  Suddenly Rg4 is going to ask Black some serious questions.   18...d5!?  19.Neg5  Rd6  An engine defence if ever there was one, although here White can pick off h7 or try for more:  20.Ne5!?  20...Nd8  21.h4!?  Black is struggling to breathe and Bf5 followed by Qd3 will ratchet the pressure up yet further. }
19. Rc4
{ 19.Neg5  d5  20.g3  Qb8  21.Qc2  This would also have left White with a huge attack. }
19... Qh6
{ 19...Qb8  20.Bxf6  Bxf6  21.Nxf6+  gxf6  22.Bxh7+!  A simple yet powerful way to regain the pawn, since the bishop is immune:  22...Kxh7?  23.Rg4  It's a forced mate with the queen about to swing across to the kingside. }
20. Neg5 d5 21. Rh4 Nh5 22. g4
{ Talk about a rout! Unsurprisingly there isn't a defence. } 22... g6 23. gxh5
Bxg5 24. Rxe8+ Rxe8 25. hxg6
{ 25.hxg6  Bxh4  26.gxh7+  Fittingly White's monster bishops have the last laugh. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Yusupov, A. vs. Hulak, K. Jakarta Intn. 1983"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 e6 3. e3 c5 4. Bd3 b6 5. O-O Bb7 6. b3
{ Unsurprisingly as a pioneer of meeting a Queen's Indian set-up with the Colle, Yusupov knows the drill: develop the kingside, then the queen's bishop and only then go Nbd2. }
6... Be7 7. Bb2 O-O 8. Nbd2 Nc6 9. a3 Rc8 10. Qe2
{ The queen isn't going to find a better square and we'll now see what happens if Black hints at a kingside regrouping with ...Re8, ...Bf8, ...g6 and ...Bg7. }
10... Re8 11. Rfd1
{ White is in no rush, but you may well prefer  11.c4  here and only then Rac1 and Rfd1. }
11... Qc7
{ 11...Bf8  12.dxc5!?  bxc5  13.Ng5!?  This aggressive leap saw White fighting hard for the initiative at an early stage in the later Yusupov-Sigurjonsson, Reykjavik 1985.   13.Ne4  Nxe4  14.Bxe4  This followed by c2-c4 also makes good sense, leaving both White's bishops fairly active. }
12. Rac1 { Our favourite vis-à-vis policy. } 12... Qb8 13. dxc5
{ With Black maintaining the central tension, Yusupov decides that this is a good moment to change the structure himself, unfurling the Zukertort bishop ahead of going c2-c4.   13.c4  This also makes good sense and even prepares a pretty decent pawn sacrifice:  13...Qa8?  14.d5!  14...exd5  15.cxd5  Nxd5  16.Nc4  Hodgsonesque play as White suddenly seizes a strong initiative. Already Bxh7+ is threatened and Black is likely to have an major issue on d6, as his bishop on e7 may well be dragged to f6.  16...b5?  17.Bxh7+!  Kxh7  18.Rxd5  18...bxc4   18...Nd4!?  19.Rh5+  Kg8  20.exd4  Bxf3  21.gxf3  bxc4  22.Qc2  Even here the attack should be decisive.  19.Rh5+  Kg8   19...Kg6?  20.Nh4+!  Mate follows.  20.Qc2  20...Bf6  21.Bxf6  gxf6  22.Nh4!  It's game over. }
13... bxc5 14. c4
{ White still wants to fight for control of d5 and the text isn't just directed against ...d5 when White might simply exchange, but also prepares a certain aggressive regrouping. }
14... a5 15. Bb1
{ Preparing to set up a battery with Qd3, as well as also to target h7 with Ng5.   15.Ne4  Nxe4  16.Bxe4  This also feels slightly better for White, who might involve Harry and/or try to probe on the long diagonal with Bc3 and Qb2. }
15... d6 16. Ng5
{ 16.Qd3  g6  17.Qc3  d5!  This gives Black enough counterplay, so Yusupov prefers an alternative and equally direct approach. }
16... g6 17. f4
{ Cementing the knight in place ahead of swinging the queen rightwards with one of our favourite manoeuvres. }
17... d5 18. Qf3
{ Hulak has responded classically to the flank attack with a central counter and now logically reduces the gaze of the Zukertort bishop, but the feeling remains that Black's kingside is a bit shaky. }
18... d4 19. Qh3
{ Now the possibility of Nde4 causes Black to prematurely weaken his kingside. }
19... h5
{ 19...Rcd8  20.Nde4  h5  This would have maintained a rough balance. White can sacrifice here, but will only obtain sufficient compensation, not more than that:  21.Nxf7!?  Kxf7  22.Ng5+  Kg7!  23.Nxe6+  23...Kf7  And now White can either repeat moves or make a winning try, such as by involving the f-pawn or exchanging on d4. }
20. Qg3 { Threatening to crash through on f7. } 20... Ng4
{ 20...Rf8!?  21.Nxe6!  21...Ng4  22.Nxf8  Rxf8  23.e4  White should be better here, but matters are far from totally clear due to the powerful bridgehead on d4. }
21. Nxf7 { Anyway! } 21... Kxf7 22. h3 Bf6
{ 22...Nf6?  23.Qxg6+  Kf8  24.Qh6+  Kg8  25.Ne4  This is clearly rather crushing, so Black has to prefer to return the piece. }
23. Ne4
{ 23.hxg4  Ne7  24.g5  Bg7  25.e4  This would have been simple, strong and left White in full control. }
23... Nxe3
{ 23...Ne7!  An only move. Black must cover g6:  24.hxg4  Bxe4  25.Bxe4  Qxb3  Suddenly Black has counterplay and matters are far from clear. }
24. Nxf6 Ne7 25. Nd7
{ Simple chess and, likewise, invading with the queen on g5 would have been pretty strong. }
25... Qc7 26. Ne5+ Kg8 27. Re1
{ 27.Rd2!  27...N7f5!?  28.Qxg6+  Qg7  29.Qxg7+  Kxg7  30.b4!  Undermining d4 so while preparing to obtain a passed c-pawn would have given White every chance of success. }
27... h4
{ 27...N7f5!  28.Qxg6+  Qg7  Black is worse, but still fighting due to a key difference with our previous variation:  29.Qxg7+  Kxg7  30.b4?!  Nxg2 }
28. Qg5 N7f5 29. Ng4
{ Much stronger than taking on g6. Lines will now open after  29...Nxg4  30.hxg4  just as they quickly now do in the game. }
29... Nxg2 30. Qxg6+ Kf8
{ 30...Qg7  31.Bxf5!  Qxg6  32.Bxg6  Nxe1  33.Rxe1  With e6 so vulnerable, the two minor pieces should quickly prove far stronger than Black's rook. }
31. Rxe6 Rxe6 32. Qxe6 Ng7 33. Qh6 { Pinning and winning. } 33... Qe7 34. Bg6
{ There's just no good defence to the threat of mate on h8. } *

